 EC145|H145]]\n|''G-WENU''\n|[[File:G-WENU_Eurocopter_EC145_Helicopter_(Wales_Air_Ambulance)_Babcock_Mission_Critical_Services_Onshore_Ltd_(35487393015).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 59''\n|''G-WOBR''\n| [[File:G-WOBR Eurocopter EC145-MBB-BK117 Helicopter Babcock Mission Critical Services Onshore Ltd (31701732255).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 61''\n|''G-WROL''\n| [[File:G-WROL Eurocopter EC145 Helicopter Babcock Mission Critical Services Onshore Ltd Op for Welsh Air Ambulance (35928436820).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 67 (Children's)''\n|1 x [[Eurocopter EC135|EC135]]\n|''G-WASC''\n|[[File:G-WASC_Eurocopter_EC-135T-2+_(cn_1074)_Bond_Helicopters_Wales_Air_Ambulance_(Bond_Helicopters)._(10444871213).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Wiltshire Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 22''\n|[[Bell 429 GlobalRanger|Bell 429]]\n|''G-WLTS''\n|[[File:G-WLTS Bell 429 Helicopter Wiltshire Air Ambulance.jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |[[Yorkshire Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 98''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2 x [[Eurocopter EC145|H145]]\n|''G-YOAA''\n|\n|-\n|''Helimed 99''\n|''G-YAAC''\n|[[File:G-YAAC Eurocopter EC145 Helicopter (29158621942).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|}\n\n==Patient transport operations==\n[[File:Mercy Jets Gulfstream Air Ambulance.jpg|thumb|right|Privately operated fixed wing air ambulance from the UK]]\nThere are also a number of patient transport operations in the UK, generally using [[fixed wing aircraft]], and which are part of a system of moving patients between points of care, or as part of a repatriation to the UK.  There is a [[helicopter]] based patient transfer service, focused on paediatric cases, called the [[Children's Air Ambulance]], which first flew in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Express and Echo|date=18 December 2012|title=The Children's Air Ambulance|url=http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/Children-s-Air-Ambulance/story-17619843-detail/story.html#axzz2UmDzoZT4|access-date=1 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619120314/http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/Children-s-Air-Ambulance/story-17619843-detail/story.html#axzz2UmDzoZT4|archive-date=19 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Scottish Ambulance Service]] operates two fixed wing aircraft in this role, with patients flown to the mainland UK for treatment.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=BBC News|title=New air ambulance for NI after flight ordeal|URL=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-25831060}}</ref>  In 2015, the [[Emergency Medical Retrieval Service|neonatal, paediatric and adult emergency care and retrieval operations]] were brought together with the Scottish Ambulance Service and utilise the aircraft and road ambulances for this purpose. They are co-located at the Scottish Ambulance Air Base at Glasgow International Airport.\n\n==Notable accidents involving air ambulances==\n*On 19 May 1996, a [[Britten-Norman BN-2 Islander]] aircraft operated by [[Loganair]] for the [[Scottish Ambulance Service]] [[2005 Loganair Islander accident#1996 accident|crashed short of the runway]] at [[Tingwall Airport|Lerwick/Tingwall Airport]] in [[Shetland]] while turning to final approach at night during strong and gusting winds. The pilot was killed, and the physician and [[flight nurse]] were injured. There was no patient on board at the time.<ref name=AAIB96>{{cite web|last1=Air Accidents Investigation Branch|title=BN2A-26 Islander, G-BEDZ, 19 May 1996|url=https://www.gov.uk/aaib-reports/bn2a-26-islander-g-bedz-19-may-1996|website=GOV.UK|publisher=Department for Transport, Air Accidents Investigation Branch|accessdate=31 December 2015}}</ref>\n*On 26 July 1998, the three man crew of the [[Kent Air Ambulance]] died when the aircraft collided with power lines and crashed in a field in [[Burham]], near [[Rochester Airport (Kent)|Rochester Airport]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/139680.stm Helicopter crash kills three] BBC News, 27 July 1998</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaib.gov.uk/cms_resources/dft_avsafety_pdf_500724.pdf |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090316072639/http%3A//www.aaib.gov.uk/cms_resources/dft_avsafety_pdf_500724.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 March 2009 |format=PDF |title=AAIB Bulletin No: 2/2000 |publisher=[[Air Accidents Investigation Branch]] |accessdate=5 July 2009 }}</ref> Initial investigation established no definitive cause for the crash, due to the fireball produced on impact. Controversy ensued when the pilot's employers, Police Aviation Services, denied liability. On 19 February 2004, following a civil case brought by the pilot's widow to the High Court in Manchester, it ruled that the crash was caused by mechanical failure, not as suggested flying low for fun, and ordered compensation to be paid.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/3504239.stm | title = Air ambulance crash pilot cleared | work = BBC News | date = 19 February 2004}}</ref>\n*On 14 June 2000, four passengers and one pilot were killed when a [[Piper PA-31 Navajo|Piper PA-31-350 Navajo Chieftain]], chartered for a medical transfer from the [[Isle of Man]], crashed on approach to [[Liverpool John Lennon Airport|Liverpool Airport]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.aaib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/dft_avsafety_pdf_500947.pdf | title = Piper PA-31-350, G-BMBC| publisher = [[Air Accidents Investigation Branch|AAIB]] | accessdate = 27 July 2013}}</ref>\n*[[2005 Loganair Islander accident|On 15 March 2005]], a Britten-Norman BN-2 Islander aircraft operated by [[Loganair]] crashed into the sea while descending toward [[Campbeltown Airport]] in western Scotland. The aircraft was operating an air ambulance flight on behalf of the Scottish Ambulance Service. The pilot and [[paramedic]] both died in the crash.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/4349523.stm | title = Air crew search called off | work = BBC News | date = 15 March 2005}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Police aviation in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Air ambulances of the United Kingdom}}\n* [http://www.associationofairambulances.co.uk Association of Air Ambulances]\n\n[[Category:Air ambulance services in the United Kingdom|*]]\n[[Category:Emergency medical services in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Aviation in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Air Ambulances in the United Kingdom\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n}}\n\n'''Air ambulance services in the United Kingdom''' are provided by a mixture of organisations, operating either [[helicopter]]s or [[fixed-wing aircraft]] to respond to medical emergencies, and transport patients to, from, or between points of definitive care.  These [[air medical services|air ambulance]]s fulfil both [[emergency medical services in the United Kingdom|emergency medical services]] functions, as well as patient transport between specialist centres, or as part of a [[repatriation]] operation. All emergency air ambulances in England, Wales, and Northern Ireland are operated by charities, while Scotland has one charity service in addition to its four NHS-funded aircraft.\n\n==History==\nThe first air ambulance services in the UK commenced in Scotland in November 1933, with a flight from Wideford Airport, Kirkwall Orkney. The first night time ambulance flight was undertaken in February 1939, from Wideford to the island of Sanday, using car headlights to help take off and landing.  The aircraft used was a [[General Aircraft Monospar]], registration G-ACEW, operated by Highland Airways.\n\n==Emergency air ambulances==\nEmergency air ambulances are generally helicopter based, and used to respond to medical emergencies in support of local ambulance services.  In England, Wales, and Northern Ireland, all of these services are charitably funded, and either directly owned by the charity, or operated under contract with a private provider.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.airambulanceassociation.co.uk/amazing_facts.php | title= Amazing Facts about your Air Ambulance | publisher= Association of Air Ambulances | accessdate= 26 July 2009}}</ref> The [[emergency medical personnel in the United Kingdom|ambulance staff]] crewing these flights are generally seconded from the local NHS ambulance service.  In Scotland, there is the only publicly funded air ambulance service, with the [[Scottish Ambulance Service]] operating two helicopters and two fixed wing aircraft in this role, alongside a single charity helicopter ([[Eurocopter EC135]]), operated by [[Scotland's Charity Air Ambulance]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Organisation\n! Radio call-sign\n! Aircraft\n! Registration\n! Photograph\n\n|-\n\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Cornwall Air Ambulance]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" |  ''Helimed 01''\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2 \u00d7 [[MD Helicopters MD Explorer|MD 902]] \n(One spare)\n| ''G-CNWL''\n|[[File:G-CNWL_Explorer_MD900_Helicopter_Cornwall_Air_Ambulance_(23587884744).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| ''G-CIOS''\n|[[File:G-CIOS_MD900_Explorer_Helicopter_Specialist_Aviation_Services_Ltd_(22986597414).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\" |[[The Air Ambulance Service]]\n|Derbyshire, Leicestershire & Rutland Air Ambulance\n|''Helimed 54''\n|[[AgustaWestland AW109S Grand|AW109SP]]\n|''G-TAAS''\n|[[File:G-TAAS_(36135925083).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|Warwickshire & Northamptonshire Air Ambulance\n|''Helimed 53''\n|[[AgustaWestland AW109S Grand|AW109SP]]\n|''G-HEMZ''\n|[[File:G-HEMZ Agusta A109 Helicopter Sloane Helicopters Ltd (25626978516).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Children's Air Ambulance]]\n(emergency patient transfers only)\n|''Helimed 80''\n|rowspan=\"2\" |2 x [[AgustaWestland AW169|AW169]]\n|''G-PICU''\n|[[File:G-PICU_Leonardo_AW169_Helicopter_Specialist_Aviation_Services_Ltd_(38285934702).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 81''\n|''G-TCAA''\n|[[File:G-TCAA Agusta Westland AW169 Helicopter.jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Devon Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 70''\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2 \u00d7 [[Eurocopter EC135|EC135]]\n| ''G-DAAN''<br/>\n|[[File:EC135 - RIAT 2013 (9699699173).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 71''\n|''G-DVAA''\n|[[File:G-DVAA_(19680620089).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Dorset and Somerset Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 10''\n|[[AgustaWestland AW169|AW169]]\n| ''G-DSAA''\n|[[File:G-DSAA_Agusta_Westland_169_Helicopter_SAS_Dorset_and_Somerset_Air_Ambulance_(31094207335).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[East Anglian Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 85''\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2 x [[Eurocopter EC145|H145]]\n| ''G-RESU''\n|[[File:G-RESU_Airbus_MBB-BK_117_Helicopter_Babcock_Mission_Critical_Services_Onshore_Ltd_(30723119285).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 88''\n|''G-HEMC''\n|[[File:G-HEMC_(32597246695).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Essex & Herts Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 07''\n| [[MD Helicopters MD Explorer|MD 902]]\n| ''G-EHEM''\n|[[File:G-EHEM MD902 Explorer Helicopter (37454369434).jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 55''\n|[[AgustaWestland AW169|AW169]]\n|''G-HHEM''\n|[[File:EHAAT_AW169.jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\" | [[Great North Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 58''\n|rowspan=\"3\" | 3 \u00d7 [[Eurocopter AS365 Dauphin|AS365]]\n| ''G-NHAA''\n|[[File:Great_North_Air_Ambulance_(6203404439).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 63''\n|''G-NHAB''\n|[[File:The_Great_North_Air_Ambulance_(GNAAS)_Pride_of_Cumbria_aircraft_(G-NHAB).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|Dedicated spare\n|''G-NHAC''\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Great Western Air Ambulance Charity|Great Western Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 65''\n|[[Eurocopter EC135|EC135]]\n| ''G-GWAC''\n|[[File:G-GWAA_Eurcopter_EC135_Helicopter_Babcock_Mission_Critical_Services_Onshore_Ltd_(30979391531).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Hampshire & Isle of Wight Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 56''\n|[[Eurocopter EC135|EC135]]\n| ''G-HIOW''\n|[[File:G-HIOW_Eurocopter_EC135_Helicopter_Hampshire_and_Isle_of_Wight_Air_Air_ambulance_Babcock_Mission_Critical_Services_Onshore_Ltd_(35646401042).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\" | [[Air Ambulance Kent Surrey Sussex]]\n| ''Helimed 60''\n|rowspan=\"2\" |  2 x [[AgustaWestland AW169|AW169]]\n| ''G-KSST''\n|[[File:G-KSST_Agusta_AW169_Helicopter_(24619322189).jpg|alt=G-KAAT|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 21''\n|''G-KSSC''\n|[[File:Air_Ambulance_St_George's.jpg|alt=G-KAAC|frameless]]\n|-\n|Dedicated spare\n|[[MD Helicopters MD Explorer|MD 902]]\n|''G-KSSA''\n|[[File:G-KSSA Air Ambulance.jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Lincolnshire & Nottinghamshire Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 29''\n|[[AgustaWestland AW169|AW169]]\n| ''G-LNAC''\n|[[File:G-LNAC_Agusta_Westland_169_Helicopter_Specialist_Aviation_Services_Ltd_(31930013686).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |  [[London's Air Ambulance]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" | ''Helimed 27''<br/>''Helimed 28'' spare unit for major incidents\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2 x [[MD Helicopters MD Explorer|MD 902]] \n(One spare)\n| ''G-EHMS''\n|[[File:London Air Ambulance G-EHMS (1).jpg|alt=G-EHMS|frameless]]\n|-\n|''G-LNDN''\n|[[File:G-LNDN_Explorer_MD900_Helicopter_London's_Air_Ambulance_Ltd_(29633620852).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Magpas|Magpas Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 66''\n|[[AgustaWestland AW169|AW169]]\n|''G-MGPS''\n|[[File:G-MGPS Leonardo AW169 Helicopter.jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\" | [[Midlands Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 03''\n|[[Eurocopter EC145|H145]]\n| ''G-RMAA''\n|[[File:EGWC - Eurocopter EC145 - G-RMAA (43673025532).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 06''\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2 x [[Eurocopter EC135|EC135]]\n|''G-OMAA''\n|[[File:G-OMAA Eurocopter EC135 Helicopter Babcocok Mission Critical Services Onshore Ltd (32312619222).jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 09''\n|''G-HWAA''\n|[[File:G-HWAA Eurocopter EC135 Helicopter Babcock Mission Critical Services Onshore Ltd (31661844476).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\" | [[North West Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 08'' \n|rowspan=\"3\" | 3 x [[Eurocopter EC135|EC135]]\n| ''G-NWAA''\n|[[File:G-NWAA Eurocopter EC135 Helicopter (Babcock Mission Critial Serivces Onshore Ltd) (46273658405).jpg|alt=G-NWAA|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 72''\n|''G-NWAE''\n|[[File:G-NWAE_Eurocopter_EC135_Helicopter_Babcock_Mission_Critical_Services_Onshore_Ltd_(31484910296).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 75''\n|''G-NWEM''\n|[[File:G-NWEM_Eurocopter_EC135T2_(5845714312).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |[[Air Ambulance Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland Air Ambulance]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''Helimed 23''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2 x [[Eurocopter EC135|EC135]]\n|''G-NIHM''\n<br />\n|[[File:G-NIHM Eurocopter EC135 Helicopter Babcock Mission Critical Services Onshore Ltd (39565530215).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''G-NHEM''\n|[[File:G-NHEM Eurocopter EC135 Helicopter Babcock Mission Critical Services Onshore Ltd (32419110986).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |[[Scotland's Charity Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 76''\n|[[Eurocopter EC135|EC135]]\n|''G-SCAA''\n|[[File:G-SCAA_Prestwick_20181004.jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"4\" |[[Scottish Ambulance Service#Air wing|Scottish Air Ambulance]]\n|''Helimed 02''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2 x [[Eurocopter EC145|EC145]]\n|''G-SASN''\n|[[File:EC145_G-SASN_IMG_1843_(19639002395).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 05''\n|''G-SASS''\n|[[File:G-SASS (16716130046).jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | ''Gama xxx''\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2 x [[Beechcraft Super King Air|King Air 200C]]\n|''G-SASC''\n|[[File:G-SASC (36804421631).jpg|alt=G-SASC|frameless]]\n|-\n|''G-SASD''\n|[[File:G-SASD_(36317634432).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Thames Valley Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 24''\n|[[Eurocopter EC135|EC135]]\n| ''G-TVAL''\n|[[File:G-TVAL Airbus Helicopters H135 Babcock Mission Critical Services Onshore Ltd (41080891701).jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"4\" | [[Wales Air Ambulance]]<br>and Children's Air Ambulance Wales\n| ''Helimed 57''\n|rowspan=\"3\" | 3 x [[Eurocopter EC145|H145]]\n|''G-WENU''\n|[[File:G-WENU_Eurocopter_EC145_Helicopter_(Wales_Air_Ambulance)_Babcock_Mission_Critical_Services_Onshore_Ltd_(35487393015).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 59''\n|''G-WOBR''\n| [[File:G-WOBR Eurocopter EC145-MBB-BK117 Helicopter Babcock Mission Critical Services Onshore Ltd (31701732255).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 61''\n|''G-WROL''\n| [[File:G-WROL Eurocopter EC145 Helicopter Babcock Mission Critical Services Onshore Ltd Op for Welsh Air Ambulance (35928436820).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n|''Helimed 67 (Children's)''\n|1 x [[Eurocopter EC135|EC135]]\n|''G-WASC''\n|[[File:G-WASC_Eurocopter_EC-135T-2+_(cn_1074)_Bond_Helicopters_Wales_Air_Ambulance_(Bond_Helicopters)._(10444871213).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Wiltshire Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 22''\n|[[Bell 429 GlobalRanger|Bell 429]]\n|''G-WLTS''\n|[[File:G-WLTS Bell 429 Helicopter Wiltshire Air Ambulance.jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" |[[Yorkshire Air Ambulance]]\n| ''Helimed 98''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2 x [[Eurocopter EC145|H145]]\n|''G-YOAA''\n|\n|-\n|''Helimed 99''\n|''G-YAAC''\n|[[File:G-YAAC Eurocopter EC145 Helicopter (29158621942).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|}\n\n==Patient transport operations==\n[[File:Mercy Jets Gulfstream Air Ambulance.jpg|thumb|right|Privately operated fixed wing air ambulance from the UK]]\nThere are also a number of patient transport operations in the UK, generally using [[fixed wing aircraft]], and which are part of a system of moving patients between points of care, or as part of a repatriation to the UK.  There is a [[helicopter]] based patient transfer service, focused on paediatric cases, called the [[Children's Air Ambulance]], which first flew in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Express and Echo|date=18 December 2012|title=The Children's Air Ambulance|url=http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/Children-s-Air-Ambulance/story-17619843-detail/story.html#axzz2UmDzoZT4|access-date=1 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619120314/http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/Children-s-Air-Ambulance/story-17619843-detail/story.html#axzz2UmDzoZT4|archive-date=19 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Scottish Ambulance Service]] operates two fixed wing aircraft in this role, with patients flown to the mainland UK for treatment.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=BBC news|title=New air ambulance for NI after flight ordeal|URL=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-25831060}}</ref>  In 2015, the [[Emergency_Medical_Retrieval_Service|neonatal, paediatric and adult emergency care and retrieval operations]] were brought together with the Scottish Ambulance Service and utilise the aircraft and road ambulances for this purpose. They are co-located at the Scottish Ambulance Air Base at Glasgow International Airport.\n\n==Notable accidents involving air ambulances==\n*On 19 May 1996, a [[Britten-Norman BN-2 Islander]] aircraft operated by [[Loganair]] for the [[Scottish Ambulance Service]] [[2005 Loganair Islander accident#1996 accident|crashed short of the runway]] at [[Tingwall Airport|Lerwick/Tingwall Airport]] in [[Shetland]] while turning to final approach at night during strong and gusting winds. The pilot was killed, and the physician and [[flight nurse]] were injured. There was no patient on board at the time.<ref name=AAIB96>{{cite web|last1=Air Accidents Investigation Branch|title=BN2A-26 Islander, G-BEDZ, 19 May 1996|url=https://www.gov.uk/aaib-reports/bn2a-26-islander-g-bedz-19-may-1996|website=GOV.UK|publisher=Department for Transport, Air Accidents Investigation Branch|accessdate=31 December 2015}}</ref>\n*On 26 July 1998, the three man crew of the [[Kent Air Ambulance]] died when the aircraft collided with power lines and crashed in a field in [[Burham]], near [[Rochester Airport (Kent)|Rochester Airport]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/139680.stm Helicopter crash kills three] BBC News, 27 July 1998</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaib.gov.uk/cms_resources/dft_avsafety_pdf_500724.pdf |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090316072639/http%3A//www.aaib.gov.uk/cms_resources/dft_avsafety_pdf_500724.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 March 2009 |format=PDF |title=AAIB Bulletin No: 2/2000 |publisher=[[Air Accidents Investigation Branch]] |accessdate=5 July 2009 }}</ref> Initial investigation established no definitive cause for the crash, due to the fireball produced on impact. Controversy ensued when the pilot's employers, Police Aviation Services, denied liability. On 19 February 2004, following a civil case brought by the pilot's widow to the High Court in Manchester, it ruled that the crash was caused by mechanical failure, not as suggested flying low for fun, and ordered compensation to be paid.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/3504239.stm | title = Air ambulance crash pilot cleared | work = BBC News | date = 19 February 2004}}</ref>\n*On 14 June 2000, four passengers and one pilot were killed when a [[Piper PA-31 Navajo|Piper PA-31-350 Navajo Chieftain]], chartered for a medical transfer from the [[Isle of Man]], crashed on approach to [[Liverpool John Lennon Airport|Liverpool Airport]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.aaib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/dft_avsafety_pdf_500947.pdf | title = Piper PA-31-350, G-BMBC| publisher = [[Air Accidents Investigation Branch|AAIB]] | accessdate = 27 July 2013}}</ref>\n*[[2005 Loganair Islander accident|On 15 March 2005]], a Britten-Norman BN-2 Islander aircraft operated by [[Loganair]] crashed into the sea while descending toward [[Campbeltown Airport]] in western Scotland. The aircraft was operating an air ambulance flight on behalf of the Scottish Ambulance Service. The pilot and [[paramedic]] both died in the crash.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/4349523.stm | title = Air crew search called off | work = BBC News | date = 15 March 2005}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Police aviation in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Air ambulances of the United Kingdom}}\n* [http://www.associationofairambulances.co.uk Association of Air Ambulances]  \n\n[[Category:Air ambulance services in the United Kingdom|*]]\n[[Category:Emergency medical services in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Aviation in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Caps", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Air_ambulances_in_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "Bogdan Raczkowski", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Bogdan Feliks Raczkowski\n| image                 = File:B Raczkowski by Piotr Chmura 1935.jpg\n| image_size            = 200px\n| alt                   = \n| caption               = Bogdan Raczkowski by Piotr Chmura, ca. 1935\n| birth_name            = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date|1888|03|12}}\n| birth_place           = [[Pozna\u0144|Posen]], [[Kingdom of Prussia]] \n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|1939|10|04|1888|03|12}}                      \n| death_place           = [[Bydgoszcz]], [[Poland]]\n| other_names           = \n| nationality           = Polish\n| alma_mater            = \n| occupation            = [[architect]], [[engineer]]\n| spouse                = Maria Raczkowski n\u00e9e Zawadzkie (1895-1939)\n| partner               = \n| children              = Danuta Walentyna, Zdzis\u0142aw \n| parents               = Walentyna Raczkowski n\u00e9e D\u0105browska and Feliks Raczkowski\n| awards                = \n| signature             = \n| website               = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Bogdan Feliks Raczkowski''' (1888-1939) was an influential [[engineer]], builder and [[urbanism|urbanist]] in [[Bydgoszcz]], from the [[1920s]] till the outbreak of [[WWII]].\n\n==Personal life==\n===Early life===\nBogdan was born in [[Pozna\u0144]] on March 12, 1888 from Feliks and Walentyna nee Dabrowska.<ref name=\"KB87\">{{cite book |last=Jastrz\u0119bski |first=W\u0142odzimierz |author-link= |date=1987 |title=Tragedia rodziny Raczkowskich. Kalendarz Bydgoszki |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy |pages=70\u201373 |isbn=}}</ref> He graduated from the [[Saint Mary Magdalene High School in Pozna\u0144]] ({{lang-pl|Liceum Og\u00f3lnokszta\u0142c\u0105ce \u015bw. Marii Magdaleny}}), like his older brother Tadeusz Jan who later became an [[agronomy|agronomist]] and head of the School of the [[Institutes of Agriculture of Bydgoszcz|Chamber of Agriculture in Bydgoszcz]].<ref name=\"BSB\">{{cite book |last=B\u0142a\u017cejewski |first=Stanis\u0142aw, Kutta Janusz, Romaniuk Marek |date=1997 |title=Bydgoski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny. Tom IV |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Kujawsko-Pomorskie Towarzystwo Kulturalne |isbn=83-85327-42-8 |pages=84\u201386|language=pl}}</ref>\n\nHe then carried on his studies at the [[Lviv Polytechnic|faculty of architecture]] of [[Lviv]] university. There, he rubbed shoulders with students, some of whom outstanding engineers or architects:  \n* [[Jan Sas Zubrzycki]] (1860-1935)\n* {{in lang|pl}} [[:pl:Witold Minkiewicz|Witold Minkiewicz]] (1880-1961);\n* {{in lang|pl}} [[:pl:Jan Bagie\u0144ski|Jan Bagie\u0144ski]] (1883-1967);\n* {{in lang|pl}} [[:pl:Tadeusz Obmi\u0144ski|Tadeusz Obmi\u0144ski]] (1874-1932).\nShortly before the outbreak of [[WWI|First World War]], Bogdan Raczkowski, as a young graduated engineer, moved to [[Kharkiv]] to handle the construction of his first project. There, he met and married on August 24, 1917, Maria Zawadzkie, born on February 23, 1895, the daughter of a railway official. \nAs a result of the Russian [[October Revolution]] the same year, the couple fled Russia by boat across the Black Sea and got back home to Pozna\u0144 after a journey through [[Romania]], [[Hungary]] and [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref name=\"KB26\">{{cite book |last=Wysocka |first=Agnieszka |date=2004 |title=Bogdan Raczkowski - architekt i urbanista mi\u0119dzywojennej Bydgoszczy. Kronika Bydgoska 26 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142osnikow Miasta Bydgoszczy - Bydgoskie Towarzystwo Naukowe |pages=465\u2013485|language=pl}}</ref> In Pozna\u0144, their daughter Danuta Walentyna was born on May 23, 1920.\n\n===Life in Bydgoszcz===\nThe family settled in Bydgoszcz in spring 1921 at 3, [[Stanis\u0142aw Moniuszko]] street.<ref name=\"KB87\"/> On December 29, 1921, he became a city councilor and chaired the Office of Ground Construction. After a dispute at the municipal council, Bogdan Raczkowski was dismissed these positions in April 1934: he then became an appraiser at the Bydgoszcz branch of [[Bank Gospodarstwa Krajowego]]. On her side, Maria was active in Bydgoszcz branch of the [[Polish Red Cross|Polish White Cross]], the social movement created in February 1918 by [[Helena Paderewska]], second wife of [[Ignacy Jan Paderewski]].<ref>The [[International Committee of the Red Cross]] did not allow the use of its name for Poland since as the country did not officially exist</ref>\n\nFleeing the Nazi invasion, the Raczkowski's left Bydgoszcz and moved to Marie's family estate in [[Kutno]] in September for one month.\nWhen they came back, their [[Kopernika Street in Bydgoszcz#House at 1 Asnyka street, corner with Kopernika street|house]] at 1, Asnyka street was occupied by a German officer: hence they moved to live at a cousin's flat, Stefan Je\u017cowski, on [[Adam Mickiewicz Alley in Bydgoszcz|Weyssenhoff Square]].\n[[Nazi Germany|Nazi authorities]] arranged for them to pick up few of their belonging from their former house on October 2, in the afternoon: when Bogdan and his daughter went to collect their belongings, they found the villa surrounded by the [[Gestapo]]. Both of them, together with Maria were arrested and shot on October 4, 1939, in the forest, north of Bydgoszcz ({{lang-pl|Las Gda\u0144ski}}). Only their son Zdzis\u0142aw escaped the round up, as he stayed with friends at that time. He quickly left Bydgoszcz and hid for the entire period of the war under the name of Zbigniew Ko\u017amian.<ref name=\"KB87\"/>\nTo make matter worse, Tadeusz, Bogdan's brother, was executed at the [[Valley of Death (Bydgoszcz)|Valley of Death]] in late October 1939.\n\nBogdan Raczkowski also painted pictures: landscapes of places he visited ([[Zakopane]], [[Ciechocinek]], [[Hel Peninsula|Hel]], [[Or\u0142owo, Inowroc\u0142aw County|Or\u0142owo]], [[Kharkiv]], Rostov, [[Sevastopol]], [[Capri]], [[Rome]]). From 1931 onward, he had been a board member of the Society of Friends of Fine Arts in Bydgoszcz.\n\n==Professional career==\nIn 1921, Bogdan supported an urban development plan in the area delimited by streets Mo\u015bcicki (now Sportowa), Chopina and Moniuszki. \nHis family lived in one of the houses of the project, located at 3 Moniuszki street.<ref>{{cite book |last=S. Nowakowski |first=K. Fiedler |date= |title=Polska Bydgoszcz. 1920-1930 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Wydanie jubileuszowe Komitetu Obchod\u00f3w-Olecia oswobodzenia miasta Bydgoszczy |page=61 }}</ref>\n[[File:1908 PHARUS sielanka.jpg|thumb|Map of Sielanka, 1908]]\nMore broadly, Bogdan Raczkowski carried on the urbanization of ''Sielanka'' ({{lang-en|Idyll}}) district,<ref>Delineated by [[Ossoli\u0144ski Alley]], [[Adam Mickiewicz Alley]] and [[Markwarta street in Bydgoszcz|Markwarta]], [[Staszica and Paderewskiego Streets in Bydgoszcz|Paderewskiego and Staszica streets]]</ref> initiated before the first World War. \nIn the [[1920s]], 50 plots for building were defined with stringent building guidances regarding the height and width of the houses, number of their rooms, even the type of fence. The 50 houses were built by the end of the [[1930s]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Derkowska-Kostkowska |first=Bogna |date=1999 |title=O za\u0142o\u017ceniu Sielanki-bydgoskiego miasta-ogrodu |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Materia\u0142y do dziej\u00f3w kultury i sztuki Bydgoszczy i regionu. Tom 4 |pages=72\u201385}}</ref>\nAt the same time, Raczkowski prepared an expansion project to give an area further north (''Skrzetusko'') an homogeneous character (sector defined by streets P\u0142ocka, Chodkiewicza, Su\u0142kowskiego and Kozietulskiego). First realizations include today's houses at 5/7/11 P\u0142ocka street.\n\n===1926-1936 Bydgoszcz development program<ref name=\"KB26\"/>===\nBogdan Raczkowski devised a grand urbanization project for the city, intending to support private construction initiatives and identifying specific areas to be developped. In addition to ''Sielanka'' and ''Skrzetusko'' districts, he focused his attention to streets Czarna Droga, Dwernickiego, [[Gimnazjalna, Libelta and Szwalbego streets in Bydgoszcz|Libelta]], Niemcewicza and Piotrowskiego. \n[[File:Bdg Szwederowo 1 06-2014.jpg|thumb|View of ''Szwederowo'' district]]\nHis idea was to assign districts purposes:\n* residential for  ''[[:pl:Bielawy (Bydgoszcz)|Bielawy]]'', ''[[:pl:Skrzetusko|Skrzetusko]]'', ''[[:pl:Szwederowo|Szwederowo]]'', ''[[:pl:Bielice (Bydgoszcz)|Bielice]]'', ''[[:pl:Wilczak (Bydgoszcz)|Wilczak]]'' and ''[[:pl:Okole (Bydgoszcz)|Okole]]'';\n* worker's dwellings for ''[[:pl:Miedzy\u0144|Miedzy\u0144]]'' and ''[[:pl:Jachcice|Jachcice]]''; \n* factories at ''[[:pl:Kapu\u015bciska|Kapu\u015bciska]]'', ''[[:pl:Zimne Wody (Bydgoszcz)|Zimne Wody]]'', ''[[:pl:\u0141\u0119gnowo|\u0141\u0119gnowo]]'', ''[[:pl:Siernieczek|Siernieczek]]''.\n\nThe last chapter of this extensive project was aiming at planning the urbanization of ''[[:pl:Osiedle Le\u015bne (Bydgoszcz)|Le\u015bny]]'' district, so as to become a showcase of Bydgoszcz for people entering the city from the north. With that ambition, in October 1933, the architect divided the {{convert|30|ha|m2}} area into 9 plots. This project was completed only on the eastern side of [[Gda\u0144ska Street in Bydgoszcz|Gda\u0144ska Street]], as the Ministry of Military Affairs did not allowed the development on the western part.\n\n==Works in [[Bromberg|Bydgoszcz]]==\nBogdan Raczkowski's education at the faculty of [[Lviv]] gave him the taste for new trends in architecture. At a time when [[Neoclassical architecture in Poland|neoclassicism]] was declining, technical and industrial progress opened up building potentials, with state-of-the-art materials ([[steel]] and [[glass]]) and innovative methods. In addition to the following realizations, Raczkowski also conceived habitations at Babia Wie\u015b (1926-1927), at 22-38 \u017bwirki i Wigury street (1930) and prepared in the early 1920s a project -never carried out- for the [[St. Vincent de Paul Basilica Minor in Bydgoszcz|basilica of St. Vincent de Paul in Bydgoszcz]].\n\n===Building at 13 Piotrowskiego, 1923-1925===\nThis tenement displays classical shapes on a 4-storey fa\u00e7ade, topped by [[rosette (design)|rosette]]s. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:13 Piotrowskiego, Bydgoszcz.jpg|Tenement at 13, Piotrowskiego\n</gallery>\n\n===[[:pl:Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 \u015bw. Stanis\u0142awa Biskupa i M\u0119czennika w Bydgoszczy|Saint Stanislaus Church in Bydgoszcz]], 1923-1925===\nRegistered on '''[[Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship]] Heritage List''' (No.601224, A/858/1-2) June 28, 1995<ref name=\"Heritage\">{{cite book |date=1 March 2014|title=POWIATOWY PROGRAM OPIEKI NAD ZABYTKAMI POWIATU BYDGOSKIEGO NA LATA 2013-2016 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Kujawsko-pomorskie}}</ref>\nLocated at 1, Kaplicznej street, the church is dedicated to [[Stanislaus of Szczepan\u00f3w]].\nThe City Council donated the plot where a former police station stood: works of demolition of the latter started in June 1923.\n\nThe funds for the construction were gathered by Bydgoszcz citizens. The church [[steeple]] was completed on May 18, 1924, and the formal consecration took place on May 21, 1925. The design refers to [[Wooden churches of Southern Lesser Poland|Polish wooden churches]]. The stained glasses in the [[chancel]] dating back to the inception of the church (1924) have been funded by Bydgoszcz [[Mayor#Poland|mayor]] Bernard \u015aliwi\u0144ski and city councelor Arthur Franke.<ref>{{cite book |last=Parucka  |first=Krystyna |date=2008 |title=Zabytki Bydgoszczy \u2013 minikatalog |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Tifen |pages=}}</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Bdg kscswStanislawa 15 07-2013.jpg|View of the church from the street\nFile:Bdg kscswStanislawa 6 07-2013.jpg|Detail of the steeple\nFile:Bdg kscswStanislawa 13 07-2013.jpg|Chancel and [[stained glass]]es \n</gallery>\n\n===Building at 45 Grudzi\u0105dzka street, 1927===\nThe edifice has been designed to accommodate old people,<ref>{{cite book |last=wk|first=|date=19 June 1927 |title=Budowa domu d\u0142a starc\u00f3w w Bydgoszczy |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Dziennik Bydgoski. Nr 138 |page=10}}</ref> augmenting the capacity of an existing facility at 1 Szubi\u0144ska street. \nThe previous and outdated house was put into service on December 9, 1885, as an element of [[:pl:Kujawsko-Pomorskie Centrum Pulmonologii w Bydgoszczy|one of the first hospital ensemble in Bydgoszcz]] funded by a donation of Ludwika Giese-Rafalska, the owner of an estate in the south-east of the city.<ref>{{cite book |last=Boguszy\u0144ski |first=Mieczys\u0142aw |date=2008 |title=Od warsztatu balwierskiego do szpitala klinicznego |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy |isbn=978-83-926423-0-5 |page=}}</ref>\n\nRaczkowski's edifice could host 80 residents in a variety of rooms and included a [[chapel]], a large dining-room, a [[terrace (building)|terrace]]d garden and [[attic]] rooms for servants or workshops. The building was inaugurated on July 29, 1928, by the President of the Republic of Poland, [[Ignacy Mo\u015bcicki]].\nNowadays, the building houses the fifth Department of the District Court of Bydgoszcz, in charge of Family and juveniles affairs. It has been renovated in late 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl/bydgoszcz/7,48722,22603301,wypieknial-budynek-sadu-przy-ul-grudziadzkiej-zdjecia.html |title=Wypi\u0119knia\u0142 budynek s\u0105du przy ul. Grudzi\u0105dzkiej |last=mc |first= |date=4 November 2017 |website=bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.wyborcza |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:45 Grudziadzka - Domu dla starcow Bydgoszcz 1927.jpg|Article relating the building in 1927\nFile:Building at 45 Grudziadzka Bydgoszcz.jpg|View from Grudzi\u0105dzka street\nFile:Buidling at 45 Grudziadzka 2.jpg|Side view from the parking lot\n</gallery>\n\n===[[Polonia Bydgoszcz Stadium]], 1924-1929===\nRaczkowski designed the edifice, unveiled on August 3, 1924.<ref>{{cite book |last=Jastrz\u0119bski|first=W\u0142odzimierz |date=2011 |title=Encyklopedia Bydgoszczy, t. 1 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy |isbn=978-83-926423-3-6 |page=266}}</ref> Conceived as an athletics facility, the architect also supervised the following additions: a football pitch (1926), a cycling track (1927), reinforced concrete 200-seat [[grandstand]] (April 1928) and athletics equipment with 6 training pitches (1929).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl/bydgoszcz/1,35591,20751557,stadion-polonii-znowu-z-nazwa-patronem-jozef-pilsudski.html#indeks_news |title=Stadion Polonii znowu z nazw\u0105. Patronem: J\u00f3zef Pi\u0142sudski |last=bor |first= |date=27 September 2016 |website=bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.wyborcza |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Today, it is used mostly for [[Motorcycle speedway|speedway]] fixtures. It is home stadium of [[Polonia Bydgoszcz]] sport club. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Stadion Polonii Bydgoszcz 2.jpg|Global view\n</gallery>\n\n===Tenement at [[Adam Mickiewicz Alley in Bydgoszcz#Tenement at J\u00f3zef Weyssenhoff Square No.2|2 Weyssenhoffa square]], 1927===\nThe building was realized as an element of the ''Sielanka'' housing estate project. Located on the south-west side of the square, its shape sticks to the gentle arc of the bordering avenue ([[Ossoli\u0144ski Alley in Bydgoszcz]]). It boasts a mix of [[Functionalism (architecture)|functionalist]] style (left side) and [[Eclecticism in architecture|eclectic]] forms (right side) with a [[loggia]] and [[Mansard]] roof, so as to mirror the adjacent front facade of the eclectic building with Art Nouveau decoration (erected in 1906-1908).\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Plac Weysesenhoff N2 corner.jpg|General view of frontages\nFile:Plac Weysesenhoff N2.jpg|Functionalist facade\nFile:Plac Weysesenhoff N2 door.jpg|Detail of portal decoration\n</gallery>\n\n===Tenement at 5 [[Gimnazjalna, Libelta and Szwalbego streets in Bydgoszcz|Libelta street]], 1928-1929===\nThis four-storey residential building displays early [[Modern architecture|modernist style]], as one can find also at [[Jagiello\u0144ska street in Bydgoszcz|Jagiello\u0144ska street]] No.51/57 and 107.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl/bydgoszcz/1,48722,18929357,jest-moda-na-modernizm-oto-bydgoskie-budynki-w-tym-stylu.html |title=Jest moda na modernizm. Oto bydgoskie budynki w tym stylu |last=bj |first= |date=29 September 2015 |website=bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.wyborcza |access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn one of the flats lived [[:pl:Adam Grzyma\u0142a-Siedlecki|Adam Grzyma\u0142a-Siedlecki]] (1876\u20131967), a Polish literary and theater critic, playwright, translator, writer and director, who in this flat at No.5. He bequeathed to the city of Bydgoszcz all his manuscripts, his private library (more than 300 works) which  were moved to the Municipal Library. The institution still tends his last place as a small museum in his memory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://biblioteka.bydgoszcz.pl/biblioteka-glowna/izba-pamieci-adama-grzymaly-siedleckiego/|title=Izba Pami\u0119ci A. G. Siedleckiego \u2013 Pracownia Teatrologiczna|date=2016 |website=biblioteka.bydgoszcz.pl |publisher=biblioteka.bydgoszcz |access-date=6 November 2016}}</ref>\nOn the frontage has been unveiled in 1988 a commemorative plaque.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Libelta 5 1929.jpg|The tenement in 1929\nFile:Bdg ulLibelta&Kollotaja 2 07-2013.jpg|Current front view\nFile:Tablica Adama Grzyma Krasinskiego 7.jpg|In memoriam plaque\n</gallery>\n\n===Villa at 1 Asnyka street, 1932===\nThis villa, where Bogdan Raczkowski and his family lived, is designed in the [[Functionalism (architecture)|Functionalist]] style. The house was occupied by [[Nazi]] officials after the [[invasion of Poland]] in 1939.\nThe neighbouring villa at 1A Asnyka -on a Bogdan's design- was built shortly before the outbreak of World War II.<ref name=\"KB26\"/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Asnyka 1.jpg|View from [[Kopernika Street in Bydgoszcz|Kopernika Street]]\nFile:Asnyka 1 corner.jpg|Facade onto Asnyka street\n</gallery>\n\n===Building at 12 Poniatowskiego street, 1933===\nThe edifice has always been used for educational purposes. It was designed by Raczkowski with engineer Kazimierz Micha\u0142 Orlicz and built in 1 year, a record at a time of economic crisis,<ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl/bydgoszcz/1,128852,15304731,Wzorowa_szkola_stanela_na_Bielawach.html |title=Wzorowa szko\u0142a stan\u0119\u0142a na Bielawach |last=jk |first= |date=20 January 2014 |website=bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.wyborcza |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> to host ''[[Ewaryst Estkowski]] Public School''. \nThe first building stage included among others:<ref>{{cite book |last=|first=|date=27 January 1933 |title=Po\u015bwiecenie nowej szko\u0142y na Bielawkach. |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Dziennik Bydgoski. Nr 22 |page=8}}</ref>\n* a basement with three rooms for manual work;\n* a ground floor with manager's and teacher's room, plus 3 classrooms; \n* a first floor with a doctor's office and 4 classrooms;\n* a second floor with a lounge and 4 classrooms;\n* a third floor comprising a drawing room and a space for scientific collections.\nThe outbreak of [[World War II]] prevented the implementation of the 2nd stage of building expansion, which caused to realize two separate facilities one for girls and one for boys.<ref>{{cite book |last=Perli\u0144ska |first=Anna |date=2003 |title=Szko\u0142a z ciemno czerwonymi pulpitami. Wspomnienie na 70-lecie Wszechnicy na Bielawkach. Kronika Bydgoska 24 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142osnikow Miasta Bydgoszczy-Bydgoskie Towarzystwo Naukowe |pages=369\u2013375 |language=pl}}</ref>\nAfter a thorough refurbishing in 2014, the building houses today the Institute of Political Sciences of [[Kazimierz Wielki University in Bydgoszcz|Bydgoszcz University]]. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Dzk Bki 1933 N22-page-008.jpg|1933 local newspaper article relating the erection of school at 12 Poniatowskiego]]\nFile:Bdg UKW Wydz Humanist 2 5-2015.jpg|View from Poniatowskiego street \nFile:Bdg UKW Wydz Humanist 1 5-2015.jpg|One of the facade onto Poniatowskiego street\n</gallery>\n\n===''[[Antoni Jurasz]]'' university hospital, 9 Marii Curie-Sk\u0142odowskiej street, 1938===\nThe work began in July 1928, after a blessing of the foundation stone. Raczkowski, together with his collegue Kazimierz Skici\u0144ski, contracted engineer Antoni Jaworski to carry out the building. The construction was stopped during winter 1928\u20131929, then it slowed down and came almost to a stop in 1930, due to city financial problems. Finally, on December 13, 1937, only the west wing and the central part were officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jurasza.umk.pl/historia-szpitala/#! |title=Historia Szpitala |last= |first= |date=2015 |website=jurasza.umk.pl |publisher=jurasza.pl |language=pl |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>  \nIt was the largest hospital built in the [[Second Polish Republic|interwar period]] in Poland, with 600 beds, gathering almost all departments under the same roof at a time when [[pavilion]]s structure organization was more popular in hospital construction.<ref name=\"KB26\"/>\n\nAfter Nazi invasion, the facility served as a military field hospital until August 1940. After this date, it became a civilian structure, ''Dr. Staemmler Krankenhaus hospital'', staffed by German practitioners from [[Gda\u0144sk]]. The entire hospital project was completed during German occupation.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Jurasza Hospital 1943.jpg|View of the hospital in 1943\nFile:Szpital Uniwersytecki Jurasza Bydgoszcz 3.jpg|Main entry\nFile:Bydgoszcz - szpital uniwersytecki im. Jurasza nr 1 (3).JPG|One of the historical buildings\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Bogdan Raczkowski}}\n* [[Bydgoszcz]]\n* [[Bydgoszcz Architects (1850-1970s)]]\n* [[Fritz Weidner (architect)|Fritz Weidner]]\n* [[Rudolf Kern (architect)|Rudolf Kern]]\n* [[J\u00f3zef \u015awi\u0119cicki]]\n* [[Anton Hoffmann]]\n* [[Jan Kossowski]]\n* [[Polonia Bydgoszcz Stadium]]\n* [[:pl::Szpital Uniwersytecki nr 1 im. Antoniego Jurasza w Bydgoszczy|Jurasza University hospital]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.parafiaswstanislawa.pl/ Parish of Saint Stanislaus Church in Bydgoszcz] {{in lang|pl}}\n* [http://btzpolonia.pl/ Polonia Stadium] {{in lang|pl}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080912154129/http://www.ukw.edu.pl/pokazStrone.php?idPoz=bde849b8dc5a60b7ffab Official website (English version)]\n* [http://jurasza.umk.pl/en/ Jurasza University Hospital (English version)]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Wysocka |first=Agnieszka |date=2004 |title=Bogdan Raczkowski - architekt i urbanista mi\u0119dzywojennej Bydgoszczy. Kronika Bydgoska 26 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142osnikow Miasta Bydgoszczy - Bydgoskie Towarzystwo Naukowe |pages=465\u2013485|language=pl}}\n* {{cite book |last=B\u0142a\u017cejewski |first=Stanis\u0142aw, Kutta Janusz, Romaniuk Marek |date=1997 |title=Bydgoski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny. Tom IV |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Kujawsko-Pomorskie Towarzystwo Kulturalne |isbn=83-85327-42-8 |pages=84\u201386|language=pl}}\n\n{{portal bar|Architecture|Biography|Poland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raczkowski, Bogdan}}\n[[Category:19th-century Polish architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish architects]]\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Bogdan Feliks Raczkowski\n| image                 = File:B Raczkowski by Piotr Chmura 1935.jpg\n| image_size            = 200px\n| alt                   = \n| caption               = Bogdan Raczkowski by Piotr Chmura, ca. 1935\n| birth_name            = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date|1888|03|12}}\n| birth_place           = [[Pozna\u0144|Posen]], [[Kingdom of Prussia]] \n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|1939|10|04|1888|03|12}}                      \n| death_place           = [[Bydgoszcz]], [[Poland]]\n| other_names           = \n| nationality           = Polish\n| alma_mater            = \n| occupation            = [[architect]], [[engineer]]\n| spouse                = Maria Raczkowski n\u00e9e Zawadzkie (1895-1939)\n| partner               = \n| children              = Danuta Walentyna, Zdzis\u0142aw \n| parents               = Walentyna Raczkowski n\u00e9e D\u0105browska and Feliks Raczkowski\n| awards                = \n| signature             = \n| website               = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Bogdan Feliks Raczkowski''' (1888-1939) was an influential [[engineer]], builder and [[urbanism|urbanist]] in [[Bydgoszcz]], from the [[1920s]] till the outbreak of [[WWII]].\n\n==Personal Life==\n===Early life===\nBogdan was born in [[Pozna\u0144]] on March 12, 1888 from Feliks and Walentyna nee Dabrowska.<ref name=\"KB87\">{{cite book |last=Jastrz\u0119bski |first=W\u0142odzimierz |author-link= |date=1987 |title=Tragedia rodziny Raczkowskich. Kalendarz Bydgoszki |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy |pages=70-73 |isbn=}}</ref> He graduated from the [[Saint Mary Magdalene High School in Pozna\u0144]] ({{lang-pl|Liceum Og\u00f3lnokszta\u0142c\u0105ce \u015bw. Marii Magdaleny}}), like his older brother Tadeusz Jan who later became an [[agronomy|agronomist]] and head of the School of the [[Institutes of Agriculture of Bydgoszcz|Chamber of Agriculture in Bydgoszcz]].<ref name=\"BSB\">{{cite book |last=B\u0142a\u017cejewski |first=Stanis\u0142aw, Kutta Janusz, Romaniuk Marek |date=1997 |title=Bydgoski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny. Tom IV |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Kujawsko-Pomorskie Towarzystwo Kulturalne |isbn=83-85327-42-8 |pages=84-86|language=pl}}</ref> \n\nHe then carried on his studies at the [[Lviv Polytechnic|faculty of architecture]] of [[Lviv]] university. There, he rubbed shoulders with students, some of whom outstanding engineers or architects:  \n* [[Jan Sas Zubrzycki]] (1860-1935)\n* {{in lang|pl}} [[:pl:Witold Minkiewicz|Witold Minkiewicz]] (1880-1961);\n* {{in lang|pl}} [[:pl:Jan Bagie\u0144ski|Jan Bagie\u0144ski]] (1883-1967);\n* {{in lang|pl}} [[:pl:Tadeusz Obmi\u0144ski|Tadeusz Obmi\u0144ski]] (1874-1932).\nShortly before the outbreak of [[WWI|First World War]], Bogdan Raczkowski, as a young graduated engineer, moved to [[Kharkiv]] to handle the construction of his first project. There, he met and married on August 24, 1917, Maria Zawadzkie, born on February 23, 1895, the daughter of a railway official. \nAs a result of the Russian [[October Revolution]] the same year, the couple fled Russia by boat across the Black Sea and got back home to Pozna\u0144 after a journey through [[Romania]], [[Hungary]] and [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref name=\"KB26\">{{cite book |last=Wysocka |first=Agnieszka |date=2004 |title=Bogdan Raczkowski - architekt i urbanista mi\u0119dzywojennej Bydgoszczy. Kronika Bydgoska 26 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142osnikow Miasta Bydgoszczy - Bydgoskie Towarzystwo Naukowe |pages=465\u2013485|language=pl}}</ref> In Pozna\u0144, their daughter Danuta Walentyna was born on May 23, 1920.\n\n===Life in Bydgoszcz===\nThe family settled in Bydgoszcz in spring 1921 at 3, [[Stanis\u0142aw Moniuszko]] street.<ref name=\"KB87\"/> On December 29, 1921, he became a city councilor and chaired the Office of Ground Construction. After a dispute at the municipal council, Bogdan Raczkowski was dismissed these positions in April 1934: he then became an appraiser at the Bydgoszcz branch of [[Bank Gospodarstwa Krajowego]]. On her side, Maria was active in Bydgoszcz branch of the [[Polish Red Cross|Polish White Cross]], the social movement created in February 1918 by [[Helena Paderewska]], second wife of [[Ignacy Jan Paderewski]]. <ref>The [[International Committee of the Red Cross]] did not allow the use of its name for Poland since as the country did not officially exist</ref>\n\nFleeing the Nazi invasion, the Raczkowski's left Bydgoszcz and moved to Marie's family estate in [[Kutno]] in September for one month.\nWhen they came back, their [[Kopernika_Street_in_Bydgoszcz#House_at_1_Asnyka_street%2C_corner_with_Kopernika_street|house]] at 1, Asnyka street was occupied by a German officer: hence they moved to live at a cousin's flat, Stefan Je\u017cowski, on [[Adam Mickiewicz Alley in Bydgoszcz|Weyssenhoff Square]].\n[[Nazi Germany|Nazi authorities]] arranged for them to pick up few of their belonging from their former house on October 2, in the afternoon: when Bogdan and his daughter went to collect their belongings, they found the villa surrounded by the [[Gestapo]]. Both of them, together with Maria were arrested and shot on October 4, 1939, in the forest, north of Bydgoszcz ({{lang-pl|Las Gda\u0144ski}}). Only their son Zdzis\u0142aw escaped the round up, as he stayed with friends at that time. He quickly left Bydgoszcz and hid for the entire period of the war under the name of Zbigniew Ko\u017amian.<ref name=\"KB87\"/>\nTo make matter worse, Tadeusz, Bogdan's brother, was executed at the [[Valley of Death (Bydgoszcz)|Valley of Death]] in late October 1939.\n\nBogdan Raczkowski also painted pictures: landscapes of places he visited ([[Zakopane]], [[Ciechocinek]], [[Hel Peninsula|Hel]], [[Or\u0142owo, Inowroc\u0142aw County|Or\u0142owo]], [[Kharkiv]], Rostov, [[Sevastopol]], [[Capri]], [[Rome]]). From 1931 onward, he had been a board member of the Society of Friends of Fine Arts in Bydgoszcz.\n\n==Professional career==\nIn 1921, Bogdan supported an urban development plan in the area delimited by streets Mo\u015bcicki (now Sportowa), Chopina and Moniuszki. \nHis family lived in one of the houses of the project, located at 3 Moniuszki street.<ref>{{cite book |last=S. Nowakowski |first=K. Fiedler |date= |title=Polska Bydgoszcz. 1920-1930 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Wydanie jubileuszowe Komitetu Obchod\u00f3w-Olecia oswobodzenia miasta Bydgoszczy |page=61 }}</ref>\n[[File:1908 PHARUS sielanka.jpg|thumb|Map of Sielanka, 1908]]\nMore broadly, Bogdan Raczkowski carried on the urbanization of ''Sielanka'' ({{lang-en|Idyll}}) district<ref>Delineated by [[Ossoli\u0144ski Alley]], [[Adam Mickiewicz Alley]] and [[Markwarta street in Bydgoszcz|Markwarta]], [[Staszica and Paderewskiego Streets in Bydgoszcz|Paderewskiego and Staszica streets]]</ref>, initiated before the first World War. \nIn the [[1920s]], 50 plots for building were defined with stringent building guidances regarding the height and width of the houses, number of their rooms, even the type of fence. The 50 houses were built by the end of the [[1930s]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Derkowska-Kostkowska |first=Bogna |date=1999 |title=O za\u0142o\u017ceniu Sielanki-bydgoskiego miasta-ogrodu |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Materia\u0142y do dziej\u00f3w kultury i sztuki Bydgoszczy i regionu. Tom 4 |pages=72-85}}</ref>\nAt the same time, Raczkowski prepared an expansion project to give an area further north (''Skrzetusko'') an homogeneous character (sector defined by streets P\u0142ocka, Chodkiewicza, Su\u0142kowskiego and Kozietulskiego). First realizations include today's houses at 5/7/11 P\u0142ocka street.\n\n===1926-1936 Bydgoszcz development program<ref name=\"KB26\"/>===\nBogdan Raczkowski devised a grand urbanization project for the city, intending to support private construction initiatives and identifying specific areas to be developped. In addition to ''Sielanka'' and ''Skrzetusko'' districts, he focused his attention to streets Czarna Droga, Dwernickiego, [[Gimnazjalna, Libelta and Szwalbego streets in Bydgoszcz|Libelta]], Niemcewicza and Piotrowskiego. \n[[File:Bdg Szwederowo 1 06-2014.jpg|thumb|View of ''Szwederowo'' district]]\nHis idea was to assign districts purposes:\n* residential for  ''[[:pl:Bielawy (Bydgoszcz)|Bielawy]]'', ''[[:pl:Skrzetusko|Skrzetusko]]'', ''[[:pl:Szwederowo|Szwederowo]]'', ''[[:pl:Bielice (Bydgoszcz)|Bielice]]'', ''[[:pl:Wilczak (Bydgoszcz)|Wilczak]]'' and ''[[:pl:Okole (Bydgoszcz)|Okole]]'';\n* worker's dwellings for ''[[:pl:Miedzy\u0144|Miedzy\u0144]]'' and ''[[:pl:Jachcice|Jachcice]]''; \n* factories at ''[[:pl:Kapu\u015bciska|Kapu\u015bciska]]'', ''[[:pl:Zimne Wody (Bydgoszcz)|Zimne Wody]]'', ''[[:pl:\u0141\u0119gnowo|\u0141\u0119gnowo]]'', ''[[:pl:Siernieczek|Siernieczek]]''.\n\nThe last chapter of this extensive project was aiming at planning the urbanization of ''[[:pl:Osiedle Le\u015bne (Bydgoszcz)|Le\u015bny]]'' district, so as to become a showcase of Bydgoszcz for people entering the city from the north. With that ambition, in October 1933, the architect divided the {{convert|30|ha|m2}} area into 9 plots. This project was completed only on the eastern side of [[Gda\u0144ska Street in Bydgoszcz|Gda\u0144ska Street]], as the Ministry of Military Affairs did not allowed the development on the western part.\n\n==Works in [[Bromberg|Bydgoszcz]]==\nBogdan Raczkowski's education at the faculty of [[Lviv]] gave him the taste for new trends in architecture. At a time when [[Neoclassical architecture in Poland|neoclassicism]] was declining, technical and industrial progress opened up building potentials, with state-of-the-art materials ([[steel]] and [[glass]]) and innovative methods. In addition to the following realizations, Raczkowski also conceived habitations at Babia Wie\u015b (1926-1927), at 22-38 \u017bwirki i Wigury street (1930) and prepared in the early 1920s a project -never carried out- for the [[St. Vincent de Paul Basilica Minor in Bydgoszcz|basilica of St. Vincent de Paul in Bydgoszcz]].\n\n===Building at 13 Piotrowskiego, 1923-1925===\nThis tenement displays classical shapes on a 4-storey fa\u00e7ade, topped by [[rosette (design)|rosette]]s. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:13 Piotrowskiego, Bydgoszcz.jpg|Tenement at 13, Piotrowskiego\n</gallery>\n\n===[[:pl:Ko\u015bci\u00f3\u0142 \u015bw. Stanis\u0142awa Biskupa i M\u0119czennika w Bydgoszczy|Saint Stanislaus Church in Bydgoszcz]], 1923-1925===\nRegistered on '''[[Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship]] Heritage List''' (No.601224, A/858/1-2) June 28, 1995<ref name=\"Heritage\">{{cite book |date=1 March 2014|title=POWIATOWY PROGRAM OPIEKI NAD ZABYTKAMI POWIATU BYDGOSKIEGO NA LATA 2013-2016 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Kujawsko-pomorskie}}</ref>\nLocated at 1, Kaplicznej street, the church is dedicated to [[Stanislaus of Szczepan\u00f3w]].\nThe City Council donated the plot where a former police station stood: works of demolition of the latter started in June 1923.\n\nThe funds for the construction were gathered by Bydgoszcz citizens. The church [[steeple]] was completed on May 18, 1924, and the formal consecration took place on May 21, 1925. The design refers to [[Wooden churches of Southern Lesser Poland|Polish wooden churches]]. The stained glasses in the [[chancel]] dating back to the inception of the church (1924) have been funded by Bydgoszcz [[Mayor#Poland|mayor]] Bernard \u015aliwi\u0144ski and city councelor Arthur Franke.<ref>{{cite book |last=Parucka  |first=Krystyna |date=2008 |title=Zabytki Bydgoszczy \u2013 minikatalog |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Tifen |pages=}}</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Bdg kscswStanislawa 15 07-2013.jpg|View of the church from the street\nFile:Bdg kscswStanislawa 6 07-2013.jpg|Detail of the steeple\nFile:Bdg kscswStanislawa 13 07-2013.jpg|Chancel and [[stained glass]]es \n</gallery>\n\n===Building at 45 Grudzi\u0105dzka street, 1927===\nThe edifice has been designed to accommodate old people<ref>{{cite book |last=wk|first=|date=19 June 1927 |title=Budowa domu d\u0142a starc\u00f3w w Bydgoszczy |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Dziennik Bydgoski. Nr 138 |page=10}}</ref>, augmenting the capacity of an existing facility at 1 Szubi\u0144ska street. \nThe previous and outdated house was put into service on December 9, 1885, as an element of [[:pl:Kujawsko-Pomorskie Centrum Pulmonologii w Bydgoszczy|one of the first hospital ensemble in Bydgoszcz]] funded by a donation of Ludwika Giese-Rafalska, the owner of an estate in the south-east of the city.<ref>{{cite book |last=Boguszy\u0144ski |first=Mieczys\u0142aw |date=2008 |title=Od warsztatu balwierskiego do szpitala klinicznego |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy |isbn=978-83-926423-0-5 |page=}}</ref>\n\nRaczkowski's edifice could host 80 residents in a variety of rooms and included a [[chapel]], a large dining-room, a [[terrace (building)|terrace]]d garden and [[attic]] rooms for servants or workshops. The building was inaugurated on July 29, 1928, by the President of the Republic of Poland, [[Ignacy Mo\u015bcicki]].\nNowadays, the building houses the fifth Department of the District Court of Bydgoszcz, in charge of Family and juveniles affairs. It has been renovated in late 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl/bydgoszcz/7,48722,22603301,wypieknial-budynek-sadu-przy-ul-grudziadzkiej-zdjecia.html |title=Wypi\u0119knia\u0142 budynek s\u0105du przy ul. Grudzi\u0105dzkiej |last=mc |first= |date=4 November 2017 |website=bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.wyborcza |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:45 Grudziadzka - Domu dla starcow Bydgoszcz 1927.jpg|Article relating the building in 1927\nFile:Building at 45 Grudziadzka Bydgoszcz.jpg|View from Grudzi\u0105dzka street\nFile:Buidling at 45 Grudziadzka 2.jpg|Side view from the parking lot\n</gallery>\n\n===[[Polonia Bydgoszcz Stadium]], 1924-1929===\nRaczkowski designed the edifice, unveiled on August 3, 1924.<ref>{{cite book |last=Jastrz\u0119bski|first=W\u0142odzimierz |date=2011 |title=Encyklopedia Bydgoszczy, t. 1 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Miasta Bydgoszczy |isbn=978-83-926423-3-6 |page=266}}</ref> Conceived as an athletics facility, the architect also supervised the following additions: a football pitch (1926), a cycling track (1927), reinforced concrete 200-seat [[grandstand]] (April 1928) and athletics equipment with 6 training pitches (1929). <ref>{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl/bydgoszcz/1,35591,20751557,stadion-polonii-znowu-z-nazwa-patronem-jozef-pilsudski.html#indeks_news |title=Stadion Polonii znowu z nazw\u0105. Patronem: J\u00f3zef Pi\u0142sudski |last=bor |first= |date=27 September 2016 |website=bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.wyborcza |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Today, it is used mostly for [[Motorcycle speedway|speedway]] fixtures. It is home stadium of [[Polonia Bydgoszcz]] sport club. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Stadion Polonii Bydgoszcz 2.jpg|Global view\n</gallery>\n\n===Tenement at [[Adam_Mickiewicz_Alley_in_Bydgoszcz#Tenement_at_J\u00f3zef_Weyssenhoff_Square_No.2|2 Weyssenhoffa square]], 1927===\nThe building was realized as an element of the ''Sielanka'' housing estate project. Located on the south-west side of the square, its shape sticks to the gentle arc of the bordering avenue ([[Ossoli\u0144ski Alley in Bydgoszcz|Ossoli\u0144ski Alley in Bydgoszcz]]). It boasts a mix of [[Functionalism (architecture)|functionalist]] style (left side) and [[Eclecticism in architecture|eclectic]] forms (right side) with a [[loggia]] and [[Mansard]] roof, so as to mirror the adjacent front facade of the eclectic building with Art Nouveau decoration (erected in 1906-1908).\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Plac Weysesenhoff N2 corner.jpg|General view of frontages\nFile:Plac Weysesenhoff N2.jpg|Functionalist facade\nFile:Plac Weysesenhoff N2 door.jpg|Detail of portal decoration\n</gallery>\n\n===Tenement at 5 [[Gimnazjalna, Libelta and Szwalbego streets in Bydgoszcz|Libelta street]], 1928-1929===\nThis four-storey residential building displays early [[Modern architecture|modernist style]], as one can find also at [[Jagiello\u0144ska street in Bydgoszcz|Jagiello\u0144ska street]] No.51/57 and 107.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl/bydgoszcz/1,48722,18929357,jest-moda-na-modernizm-oto-bydgoskie-budynki-w-tym-stylu.html |title=Jest moda na modernizm. Oto bydgoskie budynki w tym stylu |last=bj |first= |date=29 September 2015 |website=bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.wyborcza |access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn one of the flats lived [[:pl:Adam Grzyma\u0142a-Siedlecki|Adam Grzyma\u0142a-Siedlecki]] (1876\u20131967), a Polish literary and theater critic, playwright, translator, writer and director, who in this flat at No.5. He bequeathed to the city of Bydgoszcz all his manuscripts, his private library (more than 300 works) which  were moved to the Municipal Library. The institution still tends his last place as a small museum in his memory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://biblioteka.bydgoszcz.pl/biblioteka-glowna/izba-pamieci-adama-grzymaly-siedleckiego/|title=Izba Pami\u0119ci A. G. Siedleckiego \u2013 Pracownia Teatrologiczna|date=2016 |website=biblioteka.bydgoszcz.pl |publisher=biblioteka.bydgoszcz |access-date=6 November 2016}}</ref>\nOn the frontage has been unveiled in 1988 a commemorative plaque.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Libelta 5 1929.jpg|The tenement in 1929\nFile:Bdg ulLibelta&Kollotaja 2 07-2013.jpg|Current front view\nFile:Tablica Adama Grzyma Krasinskiego 7.jpg|In memoriam plaque\n</gallery>\n\n===Villa at 1 Asnyka street, 1932===\nThis villa, where Bogdan Raczkowski and his family lived, is designed in the [[Functionalism (architecture)|Functionalist]] style. The house was occupied by [[Nazi]] officials after the [[invasion of Poland]] in 1939.\nThe neighbouring villa at 1A Asnyka -on a Bogdan's design- was built shortly before the outbreak of World War II.<ref name=\"KB26\"/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Asnyka 1.jpg|View from [[Kopernika Street in Bydgoszcz|Kopernika Street]]\nFile:Asnyka 1 corner.jpg|Facade onto Asnyka street\n</gallery>\n\n===Building at 12 Poniatowskiego street, 1933===\nThe edifice has always been used for educational purposes. It was designed by Raczkowski with engineer Kazimierz Micha\u0142 Orlicz and built in 1 year, a record at a time of economic crisis,<ref> \n{{cite web |url=https://bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl/bydgoszcz/1,128852,15304731,Wzorowa_szkola_stanela_na_Bielawach.html |title=Wzorowa szko\u0142a stan\u0119\u0142a na Bielawach |last=jk |first= |date=20 January 2014 |website=bydgoszcz.wyborcza.pl |publisher=bydgoszcz.wyborcza |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> to host ''[[Ewaryst Estkowski]] Public School''. \nThe first building stage included among others:<ref>{{cite book |last=|first=|date=27 January 1933 |title=Po\u015bwiecenie nowej szko\u0142y na Bielawkach. |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Dziennik Bydgoski. Nr 22 |page=8}</ref>\n* a basement with three rooms for manual work;\n* a ground floor with manager's and teacher's room, plus 3 classrooms; \n* a first floor with a doctor's office and 4 classrooms;\n* a second floor with a lounge and 4 classrooms;\n* a third floor comprising a drawing room and a space for scientific collections.\nThe outbreak of [[World War II]] prevented the implementation of the 2nd stage of building expansion, which caused to realize two separate facilities one for girls and one for boys.<ref>{{cite book |last=Perli\u0144ska |first=Anna |date=2003 |title=Szko\u0142a z ciemno czerwonymi pulpitami. Wspomnienie na 70-lecie Wszechnicy na Bielawkach. Kronika Bydgoska 24 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142osnikow Miasta Bydgoszczy-Bydgoskie Towarzystwo Naukowe |pages=369\u2013375 |language=pl}}</ref>\nAfter a thorough refurbishing in 2014, the building houses today the Institute of Political Sciences of [[Kazimierz Wielki University in Bydgoszcz|Bydgoszcz University]]. \n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Dzk Bki 1933 N22-page-008.jpg|1933 local newspaper article relating the erection of school at 12 Poniatowskiego]]\nFile:Bdg UKW Wydz Humanist 2 5-2015.jpg|View from Poniatowskiego street \nFile:Bdg UKW Wydz Humanist 1 5-2015.jpg|One of the facade onto Poniatowskiego street\n</gallery>\n\n===''[[Antoni Jurasz]]'' university hospital, 9 Marii Curie-Sk\u0142odowskiej street, 1938=== \nThe work began in July 1928, after a blessing of the foundation stone. Raczkowski, together with his collegue Kazimierz Skici\u0144ski, contracted engineer Antoni Jaworski to carry out the building. The construction was stopped during winter 1928\u20131929, then it slowed down and came almost to a stop in 1930, due to city financial problems. Finally, on December 13, 1937, only the west wing and the central part were officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jurasza.umk.pl/historia-szpitala/#! |title=Historia Szpitala |last= |first= |date=2015 |website=jurasza.umk.pl |publisher=jurasza.pl |language=pl |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>  \nIt was the largest hospital built in the [[Second Polish Republic|interwar period]] in Poland, with 600 beds, gathering almost all departments under the same roof at a time when [[pavilion]]s structure organization was more popular in hospital construction.<ref name=\"KB26\"/>\n\nAfter Nazi invasion, the facility served as a military field hospital until August 1940. After this date, it became a civilian structure, ''Dr. Staemmler Krankenhaus hospital'', staffed by German practitioners from [[Gda\u0144sk]]. The entire hospital project was completed during German occupation.\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Jurasza Hospital 1943.jpg|View of the hospital in 1943\nFile:Szpital Uniwersytecki Jurasza Bydgoszcz 3.jpg|Main entry\nFile:Bydgoszcz - szpital uniwersytecki im. Jurasza nr 1 (3).JPG|One of the historical buildings\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Bogdan Raczkowski}}\n* [[Bydgoszcz]]\n* [[Bydgoszcz Architects (1850-1970s)]]\n* [[Fritz Weidner (architect)|Fritz Weidner]]\n* [[Rudolf Kern (architect)|Rudolf Kern]]\n* [[J\u00f3zef \u015awi\u0119cicki]]\n* [[Anton Hoffmann]]\n* [[Jan Kossowski]]\n* [[Polonia Bydgoszcz Stadium]]\n* [[:pl::Szpital Uniwersytecki nr 1 im. Antoniego Jurasza w Bydgoszczy|Jurasza University hospital]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.parafiaswstanislawa.pl/ Parish of Saint Stanislaus Church in Bydgoszcz] {{in lang|pl}}\n* [http://btzpolonia.pl/ Polonia Stadium] {{in lang|pl}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080912154129/http://www.ukw.edu.pl/pokazStrone.php?idPoz=bde849b8dc5a60b7ffab Official website (English version)]\n* [http://jurasza.umk.pl/en/ Jurasza University Hospital (English version)]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Wysocka |first=Agnieszka |date=2004 |title=Bogdan Raczkowski - architekt i urbanista mi\u0119dzywojennej Bydgoszczy. Kronika Bydgoska 26 |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Towarzystwo Mi\u0142osnikow Miasta Bydgoszczy - Bydgoskie Towarzystwo Naukowe |pages=465\u2013485|language=pl}}\n* {{cite book |last=B\u0142a\u017cejewski |first=Stanis\u0142aw, Kutta Janusz, Romaniuk Marek |date=1997 |title=Bydgoski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny. Tom IV |location=Bydgoszcz |publisher=Kujawsko-Pomorskie Towarzystwo Kulturalne |isbn=83-85327-42-8 |pages=84-86|language=pl}}\n\n{{portal bar|Architecture|Biography|Poland}}\n[[:Category:19th-century Polish architects]]\n[[:Category:20th-century Polish architects]]\n[[:Category:1888 births]]\n[[:Category:1939 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "uncategorized", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bogdan_Raczkowski"}
{"title_page": "Christina Milian (album)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Christina Milian\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Christina Milian]]\n| cover      = Christinamilian-christinamilian1.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 9, 2001 <small>(Europe)</small><br />January 15, 2002 <small>(Japan)</small><br/>August 31, 2002 <small>(Worldwide)\n| recorded   = 2000\u20132001\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"AMBio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/christina-milian-mn0000126168/biography|title=Christina Milian|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Bonacich|first=Drago|quote=her self-titled pop/R&B debut album in 2001|access-date=April 24, 2017}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 47:53\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Soul]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Bloodshy & Avant]]|[[Bryan-Michael Cox]]|[[Jermaine Dupri]]|[[Focus...]]|[[Murlyn Music Group|Fredro]]|[[Irv Gotti]]|[[Mark Hill (musician)|Mark Hill]]|[[Montell Jordan]]|[[Evan Rogers]]|[[Stargate (production team)|StarGate]]|[[Carl Sturken]]}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[It's About Time (Christina Milian album)|It's About Time]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Christina Milian\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[AM to PM]]\n | single1date = July 24, 2001\n | single2     = [[When You Look at Me]]\n | single2date = June 17, 2002\n}}\n}}\n'''''Christina Milian''''' is the self-titled debut studio album by American singer [[Christina Milian]] released by [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Soul Recordings]] on October 9, 2001.<ref name=\"milianbilldis\">{{cite web |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=christina milian|chart=all}} |title=Discography&nbsp;\u2013 Christina Milian&nbsp;\u2013 ''Christina Milian'' |accessdate=October 3, 2008 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> Its US release was postponed due to the [[September 11 attacks]], which occurred just weeks before its intended release date. Her label still opted to release it in Europe, but the album was never released in North America.<ref name=\"milianbiog2\"/>\n\nMilian made her first professional musical appearance on [[Ja Rule]]'s single \"[[Between Me and You]]\", which led to a record deal with [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Soul]] and [[The Inc. Records]] in 2000. Milian traveled to Sweden where she collaborated with several producers, most notably [[Bloodshy & Avant]], who helmed five tracks. Milian co-wrote eleven of the twelve songs on the album, taking inspiration from personal experiences. The album's musical style is mostly [[dance music|dance]] and [[contemporary R&B|R&B]], and critics noted similarities to her contemporaries [[Britney Spears]] and [[Christina Aguilera]]. Milian was displeased by Def Soul's portrayal of her image, which she felt was constantly changing and confusing the audience.\n\nThe critical response to ''Christina Milian'' was mixed; critics who gave a positive review enjoyed the catchy tracks and lead single \"[[AM to PM]]\", while others found that it lacked original ideas. The album peaked at number 23 in the UK, selling a total of 101,986 copies, and achieved Silver certification. Internationally, the album also charted in the Netherlands, Sweden and France. The album spawned two singles, \"AM to PM\" and \"[[When You Look at Me]]\", which charted worldwide.\n\n== Production and composition ==\nFollowing her collaboration with Ja Rule, Milian signed a deal with [[Island Def Jam Music Group]] in 2000.<ref name=\"peopmil\">{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1032818,00.html |title=Celeb Spotlight: Christina Milian |author=Kappes, Serena |date= March 2, 2005 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref> Milian traveled to Sweden and recorded her self-titled debut album,<ref name=\"releasemilian\"/> working with the popular producers of that time.<ref name=\"milianinterviewsongs\"/> Milian collaborated with [[Bloodshy & Avant]], [[Jermaine Dupri]], [[Bernard \"Focus...\" Edwards, Jr.|Focus]], [[Irv Gotti]], [[Artful Dodger (UK band)|Mark Hill]], [[Montell Jordan]] and [[Evan Rogers]].<ref name=\"allmusicmili\"/> Soren Baker of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' later suggested that instead of launching her career off the success of \"Between Me and You\", and by recording in Sweden without the \"platinum production touch\" of Irv Gotti, the owner of [[The Inc. Records]], the momentum created by the song had evaporated.<ref name=\"releasemilian\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/mar/03/news/wk-movies3|title= As this Moon she Rises Higher|accessdate=August 17, 2008 |author=Baker, Soren |date=March 3, 2005 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> Milian received writing credit for eleven of the twelve songs on the album.<ref name=\"allmusicmili\">{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r555823|pure_url=yes}} |title=''Christina Milian'' - Christina Milian |accessdate=May 2, 2010 |author=Kellman, Andy |publisher=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref> It was during the production of the album that Milian had first started to write songs, and wrote about things that she could relate to at the time.<ref name=\"musicmilianremedy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicremedy.com/c/Christina_Milian/album/So_Amazin-2530.html |title=Christina Milian ''So Amazin'' Album |accessdate=August 3, 2008 |work=Music Remedy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016210543/http://www.musicremedy.com/c/Christina_Milian/album/So_Amazin-2530.html |archivedate=October 16, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> \n\nMilian described the sound of the album as \"hip hop under-toned with nice, pop melodies\",<ref name=\"lindziinter\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lindzi.com/interviews/christinam.htm |title=Christina Milian |accessdate=December 14, 2008 |author=Scharf, Lindzi |website=Lindzi.com}}</ref> and later said the genre of the album was \"bubble-gum pop\".<ref name=\"milianfive\">{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1285/is_11_33/ai_111114514/pg_1?tag=artBody;col1 |title=Christina Milian: Don't Worry, J. Lo. This Singing Actress has a Different Career Path in Mind |accessdate=July 26, 2008 |author=Beale, Lewis |date=December 2003 |publisher=[[FindArticles]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210082852/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1285/is_11_33/ai_111114514/pg_1?tag=artBody%3Bcol1 |archivedate=December 10, 2008}}</ref> She described lead single \"AM to PM\" as a \"very pop\" and \"fun, party/club song\".<ref name=\"lindziinter\"/><ref name=\"milianimage\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1486894/20040507/milian_christina.jhtml |title=Christina Milian's Sexy New Look Comes In Flat Or Semigloss |accessdate=July 25, 2008 |author=Moss, Corey |date=May 7, 2004 |publisher=[[MTV]]}}</ref> The genre of the album was described by one critic as \"light-hearted, energetic R&B pop tunes\".<ref name=\"iereview\">{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.ie/album-review/Christina-Milian---Christina-Milian/1838.htm |title=Christina Milian - Christina Milian |accessdate=November 24, 2008 |author=Lynch, Andrew |date=January 25, 2002 |website=[[entertainment.ie]]}}</ref> Critics compared Milian to [[Janet Jackson]] and [[Aaliyah]].<ref name=\"iereview\"/> Sonically, the album was said to stick \"rigidly to the sherbert-snorting pop formula of [[Britney Spears]] and [[Christina Aguilera]]\".<ref name=\"nmereview\"/> One reviewer compared Milian to other singers of her generation, and found that \"while Spears has gone raunchy with '[[I Love Rock 'n' Roll#Britney Spears version|I Love Rock 'n' Roll]]', Christina Aguilera down and dirty on ''[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]'', and even clean-cut [[Mandy Moore]] has brashly cut her hair [[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]-style, Milian still seems young and real.\" The critic also compared Milian to [[Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]], \"while Beyonce is shaking her bootylicious body like crazy on '[[Crazy in Love (Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles song)|Crazy In Love]]', Milian is simply enjoying becoming a young star.\"<ref name=\"danwreview\"/>\n\nMany live instruments were used during the album's production, especially violin. Milian named \"You Make Me Laugh\" one of her favorite songs on the album. It was the first song written by Milian for the album, and she worked with [[Bloodshy & Avant|Bloodshy]] for the song's production.<ref name=\"lindziinter\"/> The album's second and final single, \"When You Look at Me\", was written by Milian. Using her school days as the inspiration for the song, Milian said that \"when I was growing up, I found people were always trying to label me. The first day of school it would be like 'Here comes this girl all dressed up. She thinks she's all that' and they didn't even know me. The message behind 'When You Look At Me' is never judge a book by its cover.\"<ref name=\"milianbbcwhen\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2057502.stm |title=Milian charts pop success |accessdate=September 13, 2008 |author=Mytton, Leigh |date=June 21, 2002|website=[[bbc.co.uk]]}}</ref> Milian asked Ja Rule to appear on her album, however she did not want to put him \"on just any song\", and wanted to make sure it was the right song for him.<ref name=\"lindziinter\"/> Milian hoped Ja Rule would appear on the track \"A Girl Like Me\", but he ended up rapping on \"Get Away\".<ref name=\"lindziinter\"/> Milian co-wrote the track \"Twitch\" with R&B singer [[Montell Jordan]], which explains that men have a certain twitch of their shoulders whenever they tell lies.<ref name=\"iereview\"/>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusicmili\"/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]''\n| rev2Score = Positive<ref name=\"danwreview\"/>\n| rev3 = [[entertainment.ie]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"iereview\"/>\n| rev4 = iafrica.com\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"milafrica\">{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.iafrica.com/music/archives/978239.htm |title=Christina Milian |accessdate=December 14, 2008 |author=Meyer, Carmen |date=June 13, 2002 |website=iafrica.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070812111737/http://entertainment.iafrica.com/music/archives/978239.htm |archive-date=August 12, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5Score = 7/10<ref name=\"nmereview\"/>\n}}\nThe album received mixed to positive reviews from music critics. Imran Ahmed of the ''[[NME|New Musical Express]]'' enjoyed \"genius single 'AM to PM'\", and praised the tracks \"Got to Have You\" and \"When You Look at Me\". Ahmed guessed that \"beneath the froth, there's a certain depth of soul\" in Milian, and thought \"Get Away\" had similar excellent results to her previous collaboration with Ja Rule, \"Between Me and You\". The reviewer also commended the lyrics of \"Twitch\", which he thought was \"remarkable for being what may be the first ever song about someone with a facial tic\". Ahmed was impressed that alongside the impressive production credit list, it was \"still Milian's name that tops the list of executive producers\", and predicted, \"genius can't be more than a few albums away\".<ref name=\"nmereview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews//6086 |title=Milian, Christina : ''Christina Milian'' |accessdate=January 31, 2009 |author=Ahmed, Imran |date=February 12, 2002 |work=[[NME]]}}</ref> Contrastingly, Andrew Lynch of [[entertainment.ie]] described the album as \"relentlessly ordinary\", and suggested that Milian needed original ideas. The reviewer felt that apart from \"AM to PM\" and \"You Make Me Laugh\" there was nothing above the average. Lynch said that if Milian \"really wants to compete with the big girls, she badly needs to spice up her tired formula.\"<ref name=\"iereview\"/> \n\nA reviewer for ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]'' commended the album for being \"full of danceable, likeable tracks, and even the occasional, successful ballad like 'Until I Get Over You'\". The reviewer called the album to be \"a refreshing change with its charming lyrics and teen outlook\". \"AM to PM\" was said to hint at \"quite a lot of talent\", and was praised for its \"slick lyrics, a fast pace, and a phat vibe\". The reviewer also praised \"When You Look at Me\", \"Get Away\", and \"Got to Have You\".<ref name=\"danwreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/weekly/review/archive/030925/review11.htm |title=Eight Days a Week |accessdate=December 15, 2008 |date=September 25, 2003 |work=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214005325/http://dawn.com/weekly/review/archive/030925/review11.htm |archivedate=December 14, 2007 }}</ref> Carmen Meyer of iafrica.com found the \"smooth, groovy and refreshing\" album to be filled \"with light-hearted and catchy tracks, which can be enjoyed either in a club, your car or even when chilling at home.\" She commented on the album's tracks, which ranged from \"melodic and heart-rending ballads to funky dance beats that are bound to keep you moving\". Meyer praised the \"infectious\" \"AM to PM\", the \"exciting\" \"A Girl Like Me\", and \"Till I Get Over You\", which is \"guaranteed to pull at your heartstrings and make you want to pull your loved ones closer\".<ref name=\"milafrica\"/>\n\n== Release and commercial performance ==\nThe album was released on 21 January 2002 in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Christina-Milian/dp/B00005PJAV |title=Christina Milian: Christina Milian: Music |accessdate=August 17, 2008 |website=[[Amazon.com]]}}</ref> It peaked at number 23 in the UK, selling a total of 101,986 copies, and achieved gold certification.<ref name=\"album sales\">{{cite web |url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=19806|title=Chili Peppers and Gnarls Barkley retain top positions|accessdate=September 12, 2008 |date=May 22, 2006 |work=[[Music Week]]}}</ref><ref name=\"miliansilver\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=30255 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208101514/http://www.bpi.co.uk:80/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=30255 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 8, 2008 |title=Platinum Awards Content |accessdate=October 3, 2008 |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]}} </ref> Internationally, the album peaked at number 36 in the Netherlands, 98 in Sweden, and 138 in France.<ref name=\"swi\">{{cite web|title=Christina Milian - ''Christina Milian'' (Album)|website=swisscharts.com|url=http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Christina+Milian&titel=Christina+Milian&cat=a|accessdate=July 20, 2008}}</ref> Two weeks before the album's release in the US, the September 11 attacks occurred and the release date was postponed,<ref name=\"milianbiog2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.herald-mail.com/?module=displaystory&story_id=89881&format=html|title=Christina Milian has her eyes on a Grammy and an Oscar|author=Antlfinger, Carrie|accessdate=July 26, 2008|date=September 19, 2004|work=[[Herald Mail]]}}</ref> eventually released internationally on August 31, 2002.<ref name=\"milianfifteenq\"/> The album's lead single, \"AM to PM\", peaked at number three in the UK, the top five in Denmark, the top 10 in the Netherlands, and the top 30 in Australia and the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"chartmilian1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/67226/chart-beat-bonus|title=Chart Beat Bonus|accessdate=July 23, 2008 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=July 23, 2004 }}</ref><ref name=\"milianamtopm\">{{cite web |title=Christina Milian&nbsp;\u2013 AM to PM |publisher=[[Swiss Hitparade]] |url=http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Christina+Milian&titel=AM+To+PM&cat=s |accessdate=July 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208120754/http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Christina+Milian&titel=AM+To+PM&cat=s |archivedate=December 8, 2008}}</ref> The album's second and final single, \"When You Look at Me\", reached number three in the UK and in the Netherlands,<ref name=\"chartmilian1\"/> the top 10 in Australia, and the top 20 in Denmark and France.<ref>{{cite web |title=Christina Milian&nbsp;\u2013 When You Look at Me |publisher=Swiss Hitparade |url=http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Christina+Milian&titel=When+You+Look+At+Me&cat=s |accessdate=July 23, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208120758/http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Christina+Milian&titel=When+You+Look+At+Me&cat=s |archivedate=December 8, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref> A music video for the track \"Get Away\" was filmed in Paris, although it was not officially released as a single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kovideo.net/music/video/Christina-Milian-ft-Ja-Rule---Get-Away/532.html |title=Christina Milian ft Ja Rule Get Away Video |accessdate=August 2, 2008 |publisher=KOvideo |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905074243/http://www.kovideo.net/music/video/Christina-Milian-ft-Ja-Rule---Get-Away/532.html |archivedate=September 5, 2008 }}</ref> To promote the album, Milian toured with [[NSYNC]], serving as the opening act.<ref name=\"milianfifteenq\">{{cite web |url=http://au.askmen.com/celebs/interview_250/293_christina_milian_interview.html |title=15 Questions With Christina Milian |accessdate=November 15, 2008 |author=Lightstone, Miranda |publisher=[[AskMen]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227024340/http://au.askmen.com/celebs/interview_250/293_christina_milian_interview.html |archive-date=December 27, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Band member [[JC Chasez]] said, \"she was like the cute, spunky kid sister. Not everyone could take [[Justin Timberlake|Justin]]'s practical jokes or my teasing.\"<ref name=\"peopmil\"/>\n\nMilian believed that the public expected \"a certain thing\" from her when she first appeared with Ja Rule, however she wanted to record the type of music she was signed to do. She said that \"AM to PM\" was a \"cool record\", but it was not what the public expected.<ref name=\"releasemilian\"/> Milian felt that her record label was confused as to how they wanted her image to be portrayed; one second she was young and singing \"AM to PM\", and next she was a grown woman singing \"Get Away\". She realized that the change confused the audience, and that \"nobody was buying it\".<ref name=\"milianinterviewsongs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mp3.com/features/stories/4636.html |title=Exclusive Interview with Christina Milian |accessdate=March 18, 2008 |author=Rolls, Chris |date=May 23, 2006 |website=[[MP3.com]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080314003917/http://www.mp3.com/features/stories/4636.html |archivedate=March 14, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> To explain that she was serious about her musical career, Milian approached the executives at Island Def Jam, and \"cussed them all out\", telling them that they were not listening to her.<ref name=\"releasemilian\"/>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length =\n| title1          = Get Away\n| note1           = featuring [[Ja Rule]]\n| writer1         = {{hlist|[[Irv Gotti|Irv Lorenzo]]|[[Ja Rule|Jeffery Atkins]]|[[Christina Milian]]}}\n| extra1          = [[Irv Gotti]]\n| length1         = 4:13\n\n| title2          = [[AM to PM]]\n| writer2         = {{hlist|Milian|[[Bloodshy and Avant|Christian \"Bloodshy\" Karlsson]]|[[Bloodshy and Avant|Pontus \"Avant\" Winberg]]}}\n| extra2          = {{hlist|Bloodshy and Avant}}\n| length2         = 3:52\n\n| title3          = [[When You Look at Me]]\n| writer3         = {{hlist|Milian|Karlsson|[[Nina Woodford]]|Fredrik \"Fredro\" Odesjo|[[Henrik Jonback]]}}\n| extra3          = {{hlist|Bloodshy and Avant}}\n| length3         = 3:43\n\n| title4          = Spending Time\n| note4           = featuring [[Charli Baltimore|Charli \"Chuck\" Baltimore]]\n| writer4         = {{hlist|Irv Lorenzo|Jeffery Atkins|Tiffany Lane}}\n| extra4          = Irv Gotti\n| length4         = 4:32\n\n| title5          = It Hurts When...\n| writer5         = {{hlist|Milian|[[Montell Jordan]]|[[Focus...|Bernard \"Focus...\" Edwards, Jr.]]}}\n| extra5          = Focus...\n| length5         = 4:02\n\n| title6          = You Make Me Laugh\n| writer6         = {{hlist|Milian|Karlsson|Odesjo}}\n| extra6          = {{hlist|Bloodshy|Fredro}}\n| length6         = 3:37\n\n| title7          = A Girl like Me\n| note7           = featuring [[Jermaine Dupri]]\n| writer7         = {{hlist|Milian|Jermaine Dupri|[[Bryan-Michael Cox]]}}\n| extra7          = {{hlist|Dupri|Cox (co.)}}\n| length7         = 4:00\n\n| title8          = Twitch\n| writer8         = {{hlist|Milian|[[Montell Jordan]]|Bernard Edwards, Jr.}}\n| extra8          = Focus...\n| length8         = 4:02\n\n| title9          = Until I Get Over You\n| writer9         = {{hlist|Milian|[[Carl Sturken and Evan Rogers|Evan Rogers]]|[[Carl Sturken and Evan Rogers|Carl Sturken]]}}\n| extra9          = {{hlist|Rogers|Sturken}}\n| length9         = 3:58\n\n| title10         = Satisfaction Guaranteed\n| writer10        = Milian, [[Mark Hill (musician)|Mark Hill]]\n| extra10         = Hill\n| length10        = 3:45\n\n| title11         = Got to Have You\n| writer11        = {{hlist|Milian|Karlsson|Winberg}}\n| extra11         = {{hlist|Bloodshy and Avant|Milian}}\n| length11        = 3:38\n\n| title12         = Thank You\n| writer12        = {{hlist|Milian|Rogers|Sturken}}\n| extra12         = {{hlist|Rogers|Sturken}}\n| length12        = 4:30\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length =\n| headline = European bonus track\n| collapsed = yes\n\n| title13         = Your Last Call\n| writer13        = {{hlist|Milian|Karlsson|Winberg|Jonback}}\n| extra13         = {{hlist|Bloodshy and Avant}}\n| length13        = 3:37\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length =\n| headline = Japanese bonus tracks\n| collapsed = yes\n\n| title13         = Let Go\n| writer13        = \n| extra13         = Bloodshy\n| length13        = 3:42\n\n| title14         = You Snooze, You Lose\n| writer14        = \n| extra14         = [[Stargate (production team)|StarGate]]\n| length14        = 3:32\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Executive producer]]s \u2013 Christina Milian, Jeff Fenster, Carmen Milian\n* Vocal assistance \u2013 [[Montell Jordan]], [[Jeanette Olsson]], Christina Milian\n* Vocal arrangements \u2013 Christina Milian, Bloodshy, Avant, Focus, Montell Jordan\n* Engineers \u2013 Joe Chiccarelli, Brian Frye, Al Hemberger, Glenn Matullo, Carlisle Young\n* Assistant engineers \u2013 Tom Bender, Stephanie Vonarx\n* Conductors \u2013 Janson & Janson\n* [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|Mixing]] \u2013 [[Mick Guzauski]], Tony Maserati, Peter Mokran, Brian Springer, Phil Tan\n* [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] \u2013 Hector \"Rick Boogie\" Aviles, Simon Collins, Jeff Fenster\n* Design \u2013 Shanna Busman\n* [[Art direction]] \u2013 Shanna Busman\n* Photography \u2013 Tony Duran\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Bass (instrument)|Bass]] \u2013 LaMarquis Mark Jefferson, Thomas Lindberg\n* Cello \u2013 Asa Forsberg\n* Guitar \u2013 Henrik Jonback \n* Viola \u2013 Hans Akeson, Elisabeth Arnberg Ranmo, Monika Stanikowska\n* Violin \u2013 Dag Alin, Torbjorn Bernhardsson, Hanna G\u00e4hran, Per Hammarstrom, Annette Mannheimer, Svein H. Martinsen, Martin Stensson\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chart (2001\u201302)\n! scope=\"col\" | Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{album chart|Netherlands|36|artist=Christina Milian|album=Christina Milian|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|France|138|artist=Christina Milian|album=Christina Milian|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Germany4|51|artist=Christina Milian|album=Christina Milian|id=4190|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Switzerland|98|artist=Christina Milian|album=Christina Milian|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UK2|23|date=20020630|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 4, 2018}}\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Japan|relyear=2002|certyear=2002|title=Christina Milian|artist=Christina Milian|type=album|award=Gold}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|relyear=2002|certyear=2013|title=Christina Milian|artist=Christina Milian|type=album|award=Gold}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Christina Milian}}\n\n[[Category:2001 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Carl Sturken and Evan Rogers]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bryan-Michael Cox]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bloodshy & Avant]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Irv Gotti]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jermaine Dupri]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Focus...]]\n[[Category:Albums with cover art by Tony Duran]]\n[[Category:Christina Milian albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Christina Milian\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Christina Milian]]\n| cover      = Christinamilian-christinamilian1.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 9, 2001 <small>(Europe)</small><br />January 15, 2002 <small>(Japan)</small><br/>August 31, 2002 <small>(Worldwide)\n| recorded   = 2000\u20132001\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Pop music|pop]]<ref name=\"AMBio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/christina-milian-mn0000126168/biography|title=Christina Milian|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Bonacich|first=Drago|quote=her self-titled R&B/pop debut album in 2001|access-date=April 24, 2017}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 47:53\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Soul]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Bloodshy & Avant]]|[[Bryan-Michael Cox]]|[[Jermaine Dupri]]|[[Focus...]]|[[Murlyn Music Group|Fredro]]|[[Irv Gotti]]|[[Mark Hill (musician)|Mark Hill]]|[[Montell Jordan]]|[[Evan Rogers]]|[[Stargate (production team)|StarGate]]|[[Carl Sturken]]}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[It's About Time (Christina Milian album)|It's About Time]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Christina Milian\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[AM to PM]]\n | single1date = July 24, 2001\n | single2     = [[When You Look at Me]]\n | single2date = June 17, 2002\n}}\n}}\n'''''Christina Milian''''' is the self-titled debut studio album by American singer [[Christina Milian]] released by [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Soul Recordings]] on October 9, 2001.<ref name=\"milianbilldis\">{{cite web |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=christina milian|chart=all}} |title=Discography&nbsp;\u2013 Christina Milian&nbsp;\u2013 ''Christina Milian'' |accessdate=October 3, 2008 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> Its US release was postponed due to the [[September 11 attacks]], which occurred just weeks before its intended release date. Her label still opted to release it in Europe, but the album was never released in North America.<ref name=\"milianbiog2\"/>\n\nMilian made her first professional musical appearance on [[Ja Rule]]'s single \"[[Between Me and You]]\", which led to a record deal with [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Soul]] and [[The Inc. Records]] in 2000. Milian traveled to Sweden where she collaborated with several producers, most notably [[Bloodshy & Avant]], who helmed five tracks. Milian co-wrote eleven of the twelve songs on the album, taking inspiration from personal experiences. The album's musical style is mostly [[dance music|dance]] and [[contemporary R&B|R&B]], and critics noted similarities to her contemporaries [[Britney Spears]] and [[Christina Aguilera]]. Milian was displeased by Def Soul's portrayal of her image, which she felt was constantly changing and confusing the audience.\n\nThe critical response to ''Christina Milian'' was mixed; critics who gave a positive review enjoyed the catchy tracks and lead single \"[[AM to PM]]\", while others found that it lacked original ideas. The album peaked at number 23 in the UK, selling a total of 101,986 copies, and achieved Silver certification. Internationally, the album also charted in the Netherlands, Sweden and France. The album spawned two singles, \"AM to PM\" and \"[[When You Look at Me]]\", which charted worldwide.\n\n== Production and composition ==\nFollowing her collaboration with Ja Rule, Milian signed a deal with [[Island Def Jam Music Group]] in 2000.<ref name=\"peopmil\">{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1032818,00.html |title=Celeb Spotlight: Christina Milian |author=Kappes, Serena |date= March 2, 2005 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=May 1, 2010}}</ref> Milian traveled to Sweden and recorded her self-titled debut album,<ref name=\"releasemilian\"/> working with the popular producers of that time.<ref name=\"milianinterviewsongs\"/> Milian collaborated with [[Bloodshy & Avant]], [[Jermaine Dupri]], [[Bernard \"Focus...\" Edwards, Jr.|Focus]], [[Irv Gotti]], [[Artful Dodger (UK band)|Mark Hill]], [[Montell Jordan]] and [[Evan Rogers]].<ref name=\"allmusicmili\"/> Soren Baker of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' later suggested that instead of launching her career off the success of \"Between Me and You\", and by recording in Sweden without the \"platinum production touch\" of Irv Gotti, the owner of [[The Inc. Records]], the momentum created by the song had evaporated.<ref name=\"releasemilian\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/mar/03/news/wk-movies3|title= As this Moon she Rises Higher|accessdate=August 17, 2008 |author=Baker, Soren |date=March 3, 2005 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> Milian received writing credit for eleven of the twelve songs on the album.<ref name=\"allmusicmili\">{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r555823|pure_url=yes}} |title=''Christina Milian'' - Christina Milian |accessdate=May 2, 2010 |author=Kellman, Andy |publisher=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref> It was during the production of the album that Milian had first started to write songs, and wrote about things that she could relate to at the time.<ref name=\"musicmilianremedy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicremedy.com/c/Christina_Milian/album/So_Amazin-2530.html |title=Christina Milian ''So Amazin'' Album |accessdate=August 3, 2008 |work=Music Remedy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016210543/http://www.musicremedy.com/c/Christina_Milian/album/So_Amazin-2530.html |archivedate=October 16, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> \n\nMilian described the sound of the album as \"hip hop under-toned with nice, pop melodies\",<ref name=\"lindziinter\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lindzi.com/interviews/christinam.htm |title=Christina Milian |accessdate=December 14, 2008 |author=Scharf, Lindzi |website=Lindzi.com}}</ref> and later said the genre of the album was \"bubble-gum pop\".<ref name=\"milianfive\">{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1285/is_11_33/ai_111114514/pg_1?tag=artBody;col1 |title=Christina Milian: Don't Worry, J. Lo. This Singing Actress has a Different Career Path in Mind |accessdate=July 26, 2008 |author=Beale, Lewis |date=December 2003 |publisher=[[FindArticles]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210082852/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1285/is_11_33/ai_111114514/pg_1?tag=artBody%3Bcol1 |archivedate=December 10, 2008}}</ref> She described lead single \"AM to PM\" as a \"very pop\" and \"fun, party/club song\".<ref name=\"lindziinter\"/><ref name=\"milianimage\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1486894/20040507/milian_christina.jhtml |title=Christina Milian's Sexy New Look Comes In Flat Or Semigloss |accessdate=July 25, 2008 |author=Moss, Corey |date=May 7, 2004 |publisher=[[MTV]]}}</ref> The genre of the album was described by one critic as \"light-hearted, energetic R&B pop tunes\".<ref name=\"iereview\">{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.ie/album-review/Christina-Milian---Christina-Milian/1838.htm |title=Christina Milian - Christina Milian |accessdate=November 24, 2008 |author=Lynch, Andrew |date=January 25, 2002 |website=[[entertainment.ie]]}}</ref> Critics compared Milian to [[Janet Jackson]] and [[Aaliyah]].<ref name=\"iereview\"/> Sonically, the album was said to stick \"rigidly to the sherbert-snorting pop formula of [[Britney Spears]] and [[Christina Aguilera]]\".<ref name=\"nmereview\"/> One reviewer compared Milian to other singers of her generation, and found that \"while Spears has gone raunchy with '[[I Love Rock 'n' Roll#Britney Spears version|I Love Rock 'n' Roll]]', Christina Aguilera down and dirty on ''[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]'', and even clean-cut [[Mandy Moore]] has brashly cut her hair [[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]-style, Milian still seems young and real.\" The critic also compared Milian to [[Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]], \"while Beyonce is shaking her bootylicious body like crazy on '[[Crazy in Love (Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles song)|Crazy In Love]]', Milian is simply enjoying becoming a young star.\"<ref name=\"danwreview\"/>\n\nMany live instruments were used during the album's production, especially violin. Milian named \"You Make Me Laugh\" one of her favorite songs on the album. It was the first song written by Milian for the album, and she worked with [[Bloodshy & Avant|Bloodshy]] for the song's production.<ref name=\"lindziinter\"/> The album's second and final single, \"When You Look at Me\", was written by Milian. Using her school days as the inspiration for the song, Milian said that \"when I was growing up, I found people were always trying to label me. The first day of school it would be like 'Here comes this girl all dressed up. She thinks she's all that' and they didn't even know me. The message behind 'When You Look At Me' is never judge a book by its cover.\"<ref name=\"milianbbcwhen\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2057502.stm |title=Milian charts pop success |accessdate=September 13, 2008 |author=Mytton, Leigh |date=June 21, 2002|website=[[bbc.co.uk]]}}</ref> Milian asked Ja Rule to appear on her album, however she did not want to put him \"on just any song\", and wanted to make sure it was the right song for him.<ref name=\"lindziinter\"/> Milian hoped Ja Rule would appear on the track \"A Girl Like Me\", but he ended up rapping on \"Get Away\".<ref name=\"lindziinter\"/> Milian co-wrote the track \"Twitch\" with R&B singer [[Montell Jordan]], which explains that men have a certain twitch of their shoulders whenever they tell lies.<ref name=\"iereview\"/>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusicmili\"/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]''\n| rev2Score = Positive<ref name=\"danwreview\"/>\n| rev3 = [[entertainment.ie]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"iereview\"/>\n| rev4 = iafrica.com\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"milafrica\">{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.iafrica.com/music/archives/978239.htm |title=Christina Milian |accessdate=December 14, 2008 |author=Meyer, Carmen |date=June 13, 2002 |website=iafrica.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070812111737/http://entertainment.iafrica.com/music/archives/978239.htm |archive-date=August 12, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5Score = 7/10<ref name=\"nmereview\"/>\n}}\nThe album received mixed to positive reviews from music critics. Imran Ahmed of the ''[[NME|New Musical Express]]'' enjoyed \"genius single 'AM to PM'\", and praised the tracks \"Got to Have You\" and \"When You Look at Me\". Ahmed guessed that \"beneath the froth, there's a certain depth of soul\" in Milian, and thought \"Get Away\" had similar excellent results to her previous collaboration with Ja Rule, \"Between Me and You\". The reviewer also commended the lyrics of \"Twitch\", which he thought was \"remarkable for being what may be the first ever song about someone with a facial tic\". Ahmed was impressed that alongside the impressive production credit list, it was \"still Milian's name that tops the list of executive producers\", and predicted, \"genius can't be more than a few albums away\".<ref name=\"nmereview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews//6086 |title=Milian, Christina : ''Christina Milian'' |accessdate=January 31, 2009 |author=Ahmed, Imran |date=February 12, 2002 |work=[[NME]]}}</ref> Contrastingly, Andrew Lynch of [[entertainment.ie]] described the album as \"relentlessly ordinary\", and suggested that Milian needed original ideas. The reviewer felt that apart from \"AM to PM\" and \"You Make Me Laugh\" there was nothing above the average. Lynch said that if Milian \"really wants to compete with the big girls, she badly needs to spice up her tired formula.\"<ref name=\"iereview\"/> \n\nA reviewer for ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]'' commended the album for being \"full of danceable, likeable tracks, and even the occasional, successful ballad like 'Until I Get Over You'\". The reviewer called the album to be \"a refreshing change with its charming lyrics and teen outlook\". \"AM to PM\" was said to hint at \"quite a lot of talent\", and was praised for its \"slick lyrics, a fast pace, and a phat vibe\". The reviewer also praised \"When You Look at Me\", \"Get Away\", and \"Got to Have You\".<ref name=\"danwreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/weekly/review/archive/030925/review11.htm |title=Eight Days a Week |accessdate=December 15, 2008 |date=September 25, 2003 |work=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214005325/http://dawn.com/weekly/review/archive/030925/review11.htm |archivedate=December 14, 2007 }}</ref> Carmen Meyer of iafrica.com found the \"smooth, groovy and refreshing\" album to be filled \"with light-hearted and catchy tracks, which can be enjoyed either in a club, your car or even when chilling at home.\" She commented on the album's tracks, which ranged from \"melodic and heart-rending ballads to funky dance beats that are bound to keep you moving\". Meyer praised the \"infectious\" \"AM to PM\", the \"exciting\" \"A Girl Like Me\", and \"Till I Get Over You\", which is \"guaranteed to pull at your heartstrings and make you want to pull your loved ones closer\".<ref name=\"milafrica\"/>\n\n== Release and commercial performance ==\nThe album was released on 21 January 2002 in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Christina-Milian/dp/B00005PJAV |title=Christina Milian: Christina Milian: Music |accessdate=August 17, 2008 |website=[[Amazon.com]]}}</ref> It peaked at number 23 in the UK, selling a total of 101,986 copies, and achieved gold certification.<ref name=\"album sales\">{{cite web |url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=19806|title=Chili Peppers and Gnarls Barkley retain top positions|accessdate=September 12, 2008 |date=May 22, 2006 |work=[[Music Week]]}}</ref><ref name=\"miliansilver\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=30255 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208101514/http://www.bpi.co.uk:80/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=30255 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 8, 2008 |title=Platinum Awards Content |accessdate=October 3, 2008 |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]}} </ref> Internationally, the album peaked at number 36 in the Netherlands, 98 in Sweden, and 138 in France.<ref name=\"swi\">{{cite web|title=Christina Milian - ''Christina Milian'' (Album)|website=swisscharts.com|url=http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Christina+Milian&titel=Christina+Milian&cat=a|accessdate=July 20, 2008}}</ref> Two weeks before the album's release in the US, the September 11 attacks occurred and the release date was postponed,<ref name=\"milianbiog2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.herald-mail.com/?module=displaystory&story_id=89881&format=html|title=Christina Milian has her eyes on a Grammy and an Oscar|author=Antlfinger, Carrie|accessdate=July 26, 2008|date=September 19, 2004|work=[[Herald Mail]]}}</ref> eventually released internationally on August 31, 2002.<ref name=\"milianfifteenq\"/> The album's lead single, \"AM to PM\", peaked at number three in the UK, the top five in Denmark, the top 10 in the Netherlands, and the top 30 in Australia and the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"chartmilian1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/67226/chart-beat-bonus|title=Chart Beat Bonus|accessdate=July 23, 2008 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=July 23, 2004 }}</ref><ref name=\"milianamtopm\">{{cite web |title=Christina Milian&nbsp;\u2013 AM to PM |publisher=[[Swiss Hitparade]] |url=http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Christina+Milian&titel=AM+To+PM&cat=s |accessdate=July 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208120754/http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Christina+Milian&titel=AM+To+PM&cat=s |archivedate=December 8, 2008}}</ref> The album's second and final single, \"When You Look at Me\", reached number three in the UK and in the Netherlands,<ref name=\"chartmilian1\"/> the top 10 in Australia, and the top 20 in Denmark and France.<ref>{{cite web |title=Christina Milian&nbsp;\u2013 When You Look at Me |publisher=Swiss Hitparade |url=http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Christina+Milian&titel=When+You+Look+At+Me&cat=s |accessdate=July 23, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208120758/http://swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Christina+Milian&titel=When+You+Look+At+Me&cat=s |archivedate=December 8, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref> A music video for the track \"Get Away\" was filmed in Paris, although it was not officially released as a single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kovideo.net/music/video/Christina-Milian-ft-Ja-Rule---Get-Away/532.html |title=Christina Milian ft Ja Rule Get Away Video |accessdate=August 2, 2008 |publisher=KOvideo |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905074243/http://www.kovideo.net/music/video/Christina-Milian-ft-Ja-Rule---Get-Away/532.html |archivedate=September 5, 2008 }}</ref> To promote the album, Milian toured with [[NSYNC]], serving as the opening act.<ref name=\"milianfifteenq\">{{cite web |url=http://au.askmen.com/celebs/interview_250/293_christina_milian_interview.html |title=15 Questions With Christina Milian |accessdate=November 15, 2008 |author=Lightstone, Miranda |publisher=[[AskMen]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227024340/http://au.askmen.com/celebs/interview_250/293_christina_milian_interview.html |archive-date=December 27, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Band member [[JC Chasez]] said, \"she was like the cute, spunky kid sister. Not everyone could take [[Justin Timberlake|Justin]]'s practical jokes or my teasing.\"<ref name=\"peopmil\"/>\n\nMilian believed that the public expected \"a certain thing\" from her when she first appeared with Ja Rule, however she wanted to record the type of music she was signed to do. She said that \"AM to PM\" was a \"cool record\", but it was not what the public expected.<ref name=\"releasemilian\"/> Milian felt that her record label was confused as to how they wanted her image to be portrayed; one second she was young and singing \"AM to PM\", and next she was a grown woman singing \"Get Away\". She realized that the change confused the audience, and that \"nobody was buying it\".<ref name=\"milianinterviewsongs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mp3.com/features/stories/4636.html |title=Exclusive Interview with Christina Milian |accessdate=March 18, 2008 |author=Rolls, Chris |date=May 23, 2006 |website=[[MP3.com]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080314003917/http://www.mp3.com/features/stories/4636.html |archivedate=March 14, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> To explain that she was serious about her musical career, Milian approached the executives at Island Def Jam, and \"cussed them all out\", telling them that they were not listening to her.<ref name=\"releasemilian\"/>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length =\n| title1          = Get Away\n| note1           = featuring [[Ja Rule]]\n| writer1         = {{hlist|[[Irv Gotti|Irv Lorenzo]]|[[Ja Rule|Jeffery Atkins]]|[[Christina Milian]]}}\n| extra1          = [[Irv Gotti]]\n| length1         = 4:13\n\n| title2          = [[AM to PM]]\n| writer2         = {{hlist|Milian|[[Bloodshy and Avant|Christian \"Bloodshy\" Karlsson]]|[[Bloodshy and Avant|Pontus \"Avant\" Winberg]]}}\n| extra2          = {{hlist|Bloodshy and Avant}}\n| length2         = 3:52\n\n| title3          = [[When You Look at Me]]\n| writer3         = {{hlist|Milian|Karlsson|[[Nina Woodford]]|Fredrik \"Fredro\" Odesjo|[[Henrik Jonback]]}}\n| extra3          = {{hlist|Bloodshy and Avant}}\n| length3         = 3:43\n\n| title4          = Spending Time\n| note4           = featuring [[Charli Baltimore|Charli \"Chuck\" Baltimore]]\n| writer4         = {{hlist|Irv Lorenzo|Jeffery Atkins|Tiffany Lane}}\n| extra4          = Irv Gotti\n| length4         = 4:32\n\n| title5          = It Hurts When...\n| writer5         = {{hlist|Milian|[[Montell Jordan]]|[[Focus...|Bernard \"Focus...\" Edwards, Jr.]]}}\n| extra5          = Focus...\n| length5         = 4:02\n\n| title6          = You Make Me Laugh\n| writer6         = {{hlist|Milian|Karlsson|Odesjo}}\n| extra6          = {{hlist|Bloodshy|Fredro}}\n| length6         = 3:37\n\n| title7          = A Girl like Me\n| note7           = featuring [[Jermaine Dupri]]\n| writer7         = {{hlist|Milian|Jermaine Dupri|[[Bryan-Michael Cox]]}}\n| extra7          = {{hlist|Dupri|Cox (co.)}}\n| length7         = 4:00\n\n| title8          = Twitch\n| writer8         = {{hlist|Milian|[[Montell Jordan]]|Bernard Edwards, Jr.}}\n| extra8          = Focus...\n| length8         = 4:02\n\n| title9          = Until I Get Over You\n| writer9         = {{hlist|Milian|[[Carl Sturken and Evan Rogers|Evan Rogers]]|[[Carl Sturken and Evan Rogers|Carl Sturken]]}}\n| extra9          = {{hlist|Rogers|Sturken}}\n| length9         = 3:58\n\n| title10         = Satisfaction Guaranteed\n| writer10        = Milian, [[Mark Hill (musician)|Mark Hill]]\n| extra10         = Hill\n| length10        = 3:45\n\n| title11         = Got to Have You\n| writer11        = {{hlist|Milian|Karlsson|Winberg}}\n| extra11         = {{hlist|Bloodshy and Avant|Milian}}\n| length11        = 3:38\n\n| title12         = Thank You\n| writer12        = {{hlist|Milian|Rogers|Sturken}}\n| extra12         = {{hlist|Rogers|Sturken}}\n| length12        = 4:30\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length =\n| headline = European bonus track\n| collapsed = yes\n\n| title13         = Your Last Call\n| writer13        = {{hlist|Milian|Karlsson|Winberg|Jonback}}\n| extra13         = {{hlist|Bloodshy and Avant}}\n| length13        = 3:37\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length =\n| headline = Japanese bonus tracks\n| collapsed = yes\n\n| title13         = Let Go\n| writer13        = \n| extra13         = Bloodshy\n| length13        = 3:42\n\n| title14         = You Snooze, You Lose\n| writer14        = \n| extra14         = [[Stargate (production team)|StarGate]]\n| length14        = 3:32\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Executive producer]]s \u2013 Christina Milian, Jeff Fenster, Carmen Milian\n* Vocal assistance \u2013 [[Montell Jordan]], [[Jeanette Olsson]], Christina Milian\n* Vocal arrangements \u2013 Christina Milian, Bloodshy, Avant, Focus, Montell Jordan\n* Engineers \u2013 Joe Chiccarelli, Brian Frye, Al Hemberger, Glenn Matullo, Carlisle Young\n* Assistant engineers \u2013 Tom Bender, Stephanie Vonarx\n* Conductors \u2013 Janson & Janson\n* [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|Mixing]] \u2013 [[Mick Guzauski]], Tony Maserati, Peter Mokran, Brian Springer, Phil Tan\n* [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] \u2013 Hector \"Rick Boogie\" Aviles, Simon Collins, Jeff Fenster\n* Design \u2013 Shanna Busman\n* [[Art direction]] \u2013 Shanna Busman\n* Photography \u2013 Tony Duran\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Bass (instrument)|Bass]] \u2013 LaMarquis Mark Jefferson, Thomas Lindberg\n* Cello \u2013 Asa Forsberg\n* Guitar \u2013 Henrik Jonback \n* Viola \u2013 Hans Akeson, Elisabeth Arnberg Ranmo, Monika Stanikowska\n* Violin \u2013 Dag Alin, Torbjorn Bernhardsson, Hanna G\u00e4hran, Per Hammarstrom, Annette Mannheimer, Svein H. Martinsen, Martin Stensson\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chart (2001\u201302)\n! scope=\"col\" | Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{album chart|Netherlands|36|artist=Christina Milian|album=Christina Milian|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|France|138|artist=Christina Milian|album=Christina Milian|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Germany4|51|artist=Christina Milian|album=Christina Milian|id=4190|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Switzerland|98|artist=Christina Milian|album=Christina Milian|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UK2|23|date=20020630|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 4, 2018}}\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Japan|relyear=2002|certyear=2002|title=Christina Milian|artist=Christina Milian|type=album|award=Gold}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|relyear=2002|certyear=2013|title=Christina Milian|artist=Christina Milian|type=album|award=Gold}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Christina Milian}}\n\n[[Category:2001 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Carl Sturken and Evan Rogers]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bryan-Michael Cox]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bloodshy & Avant]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Irv Gotti]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jermaine Dupri]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Focus...]]\n[[Category:Albums with cover art by Tony Duran]]\n[[Category:Christina Milian albums]]\n", "name_user": "109.144.219.82", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christina_Milian_(album)"}
{"title_page": "Metamorpho", "text_new": "{{short description|Fictional superhero}}\n{{Infobox comics character\n| character_name = Metamorpho\n| image = Nolan metamorpho.jpg\n| converted = y\n| caption = Metamorpho emerging from a periodic table on the cover to ''Metamorpho'' (Volume 2) #1 (August 1993), by [[Graham Nolan]]\n| alt = Metamorpho smiling and standing on a periodic table\n| publisher = [[DC Comics]]\n| debut = ''[[The Brave and the Bold]]'' #57 (January 1965)\n| creators = {{hlist|[[Bob Haney]]|[[Ramona Fradon]]}}\n| alter_ego = Rex Mason\n| alliances = [[Outsiders (comics)|Outsiders]]<br/>[[Justice League Europe]]<br/>[[Seven Soldiers of Victory]]<br/>[[Doom Patrol]]<br/>[[Stagg Enterprises]]<br/>Terrifics<br/>[[Justice League]]\n| aliases = The Element Man, Dyna-Man\n| species = [[Metahuman]]\n| powers = Elemental Shapeshifting <br> Super-Strength <br> Invulnerability \n| cat = super\n| subcat = DC Comics\n| hero = y\n| sortkey = Metamorpho\n}}\n'''Metamorpho''' (real name '''Rex Mason''', also called '''The Element Man''') is a [[fictional character|fictional]] [[superhero]] appearing in [[American comic books]] published by [[DC Comics]]. He was created in 1964 by writer [[Bob Haney]] and artist [[Ramona Fradon]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cowsill |first1=Alan |last2=Irvine |first2=Alex |last3=Korte |first3=Steve |last4=Manning |first4=Matt |last5=Wiacek |first5=Win |last6=Wilson |first6=Sven |title=The DC Comics Encyclopedia: The Definitive Guide to the Characters of the DC Universe |date=2016 |publisher=DK Publishing |isbn=978-1-4654-5357-0 |page=201}}</ref> \n\nMetamorpho is a founding member of the [[Outsiders (comics)|Outsiders]], and has also joined multiple incarnations of the [[Justice League]]. The character has been moderately popular since his introduction in 1965. Originally adventurer Rex Mason, he is converted into a man made of a shifting mass of chemicals after being cursed by an ancient artifact that he has retrieved.\n\n==Publication history==\nMetamorpho's creator, [[Bob Haney]], had seen success with DC Comics in 1963 with the titles ''[[Metal Men]]'' and ''[[Doom Patrol]]'', featuring bands of superheroes exhibiting fantastic powers. Under the editorial management of [[George Kashdan]], Haney was asked to capitalize on these titles' popularity with a similar character. Metamorpho, the Element Man, debuted in ''[[The Brave and the Bold]]'' #57 (January 1965).<ref>{{cite book| last= McAvennie |first= Michael| editor-last= Dolan| editor-first= Hannah |chapter= 1960s|title = DC Comics Year By Year A Visual Chronicle| publisher= [[Dorling Kindersley]] |year=2010 |isbn= 978-0-7566-6742-9 |page= 114 |quote = Scribe Bob Haney and artist Ramona Fradon were truly in their element...Haney and Fradon's collaborative chemistry resulted in [Rex] Mason becoming Metamorpho.}}</ref>\n\nAs first conceived, Metamorpho was a parody of the fantastic characters that populated comic books in the 1960s.<ref>{{cite book | last=Jones | first=Gerard |author2=Will Jacobs | title=The Comic Book Heroes | location=[[Rocklin, California]] | publisher=Prima Lifestyles | pages=76\u201377 | date=October 23, 1996 | isbn=978-0-7615-0393-4}}</ref> Artist [[Ramona Fradon]] was coaxed out of maternity retirement to illustrate Metamorpho's first appearances. The popularity of Metamorpho's appearances in ''The Brave and the Bold'' led to a 17-issue [[ongoing series]] between 1965 and 1968. Metamorpho also appeared during this time in two issues of ''Justice League of America'' (#42 and #44) and became the second superhero to decline an invitation to join that organization ([[Adam Strange]] being the first), though he did become a reservist, eventually being called in during a Justice League/Justice Society crossover to help find and rescue the Seven Soldiers of Victory.\n\nMetamorpho appears on the cover of ''Aquaman'' #30 as one of the pallbearers (along with Batman, Hawkman, and Superman) at the \"Sea King's Funeral\".<ref>{{cite web| url= http://comicvine.gamespot.com/aquaman-30-the-death-of-aquaman/4000-108970/ |title=Aquaman #30 - The Death of Aquaman |website=Comic Vine |access-date=15 April 2016}}</ref> Metamorpho also appears in a series of backup stories in ''[[Action Comics]]'' #413\u2013418 and ''[[World's Finest Comics]]'' #218\u2013220 and #229.<ref>{{cite journal|last = Stroud|first = Bryan|title = Metamorpho in ''Action Comics'' |journal= [[Back Issue!]] |issue = 64 |pages = 22\u201327| publisher = [[TwoMorrows Publishing]] |date = May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Metamorpho appeared in ''[[1st Issue Special]]'' #3, a brief anthology series consisting of one-shots. That issue was written by Bob Haney and illustrated by Ramona Fradon, Metamorpho's creators. Haney and Fradon had met at the 1974 [[San Diego Comic-Con]], and while reminiscing, it emerged that both of them regarded Metamorpho as one of the features they'd most enjoyed working on, leading them to ask DC if they could do one more Metamorpho story together.<ref name=\"back71\">{{cite journal|last=Abramowitz |first= Jack| title= 1st Issue Special: It Was No ''Showcase'' (But It Was Never Meant To Be)| journal= [[Back Issue!]]| issue=71 |page= 42| publisher= [[TwoMorrows Publishing]]| date= April 2014 |location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref> Fradon later commented, \"I think we both felt that Metamorpho was our baby. I never had an experience like I had working with Bob Haney on ''Metamorpho''. It was like our minds were in perfect synch ... it was one of those wonderful collaborations that doesn't happen very often.\"<ref name=\"back71\"/>\n\nAfter becoming a charter member of the Outsiders in 1983, and member of the European branch of the [[Justice League International]], Metamorpho received his own four-issue mini-series in 1993.\n\nIn 2005, DC Comics reprinted Metamorpho's early ''The Brave and the Bold'' appearances and the entirety of the 1965 series as one of the company's volumes of ''[[Showcase Presents]]''.\n\nIn 2007, [[Dan Jurgens]] launched the six-issue series ''Metamorpho: Year One''.\n\nAs part of a ''[[Wednesday Comics]]'', [[Neil Gaiman]] wrote a 12-page Metamorpho story that [[Mike Allred]] illustrated.<ref>{{cite web | first= Remy | last= Minnick | url= http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=19775 | title=Gaiman & Allred on Metamorpho | work=[[Comic Book Resources]] | date=January 30, 2009 | accessdate=January 31, 2009}}</ref> In 2016 he starred in a new comic book series titled DC's ''Legends of Tomorrow''.<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://comicvine.gamespot.com/articles/aaron-lopresti-talks-metamorpho-in-new-dcs-legends/1100-155102/ |title= Aaron Lopresti Talks Metamorpho in New DC's LEGENDS OF TOMORROW Series|work=Comic Vine |access-date= 2018-09-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Fictional character biography==\nRex Mason is an adventurer who is hired by [[Stagg Enterprises]] CEO, [[Simon Stagg]], to retrieve a rare [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptian]] artifact, the [[Orb of Ra]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Markstein |first1=Don |website=Don Markstein's Toonopedia |accessdate=2 April 2020  |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/metamor.htm |title=Metamorpho the Element Man}}</ref> Shortly after hiring him, Simon Stagg learns that Mason has been dating his daughter, [[Sapphire Stagg]]. This and other incidents begin to fuel in Stagg a dislike for Mason that ultimately leads to a plot to kill him.\n\nIn an [[Egyptian pyramids|Egyptian pyramid]], Rex Mason is knocked unconscious by Simon's brutish bodyguard [[Java (comics)|Java]] and is eventually exposed to a radioactive [[meteoroid|meteor]]ite from which the Orb of [[Ra]] was fashioned. A tremendous flare-up of its radiation transforms Mason into Metamorpho, the Element Man. He gains the ability to [[shapeshifting|shapeshift]] and change himself into any [[chemical element|element]] or combination of elements found in the human body. It is also established in his origin story in ''[[The Brave & The Bold]]'' #57 that Metamorpho is virtually invulnerable in his inert (untransformed) state, when Stagg, afraid that Rex is going to kill him, shoots him point-blank without effect. The Orb of Ra, however, has the same effect on Rex that [[kryptonite]] has on [[Superman]]. Thus Stagg continues to control Metamorpho using the Orb. Later, it is revealed that Mason is but one of many [[metamorphae]]. They were created by the sun god Ra, using the meteorite, to serve as warriors in his battle against the god [[Apep]], \"the serpent who never dies.\"<ref>{{cite book | title=The DC Comics Encyclopedia | last1=Beatty | first1=Scott | authorlink1=Scott Beatty | last2=Jimenez | first2=Phil | authorlink2=Phil Jimenez | date=October 4, 2004 | publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]] Limited | isbn=978-0-7566-0592-6 | page=202}}</ref>\n\nMetamorpho, unlike most super-humanoids described in DC Comics, cannot assume a normal, fully human appearance, being no longer composed of flesh, blood and bone. As such, he regards his metamorphic powers as a disease and seeks a cure for his condition. Because he considers himself a freak and wishes only to be restored to his former human state, he rejects an offer of membership from the [[Justice League of America]] in ''JLA'' #42. [[Green Lantern]] attempts to change him back using his power ring, but due to a \"yellow\" component of the meteorite radiation, is unable to make him normal again.\n\nMetamorpho briefly has a crimefighting partner named Urania \"Rainie\" Blackwell, a woman who deliberately exposed herself to the Orb to gain its powers. She calls herself [[Element Girl]] (nicknamed \"the Chemical Doll\") and works with him on a number of cases.\n\nIssues #16\u201317 were intended to show a new direction for the series, with Sapphire marrying a man named Wally Bannister and Metamorpho joining a mysterious Mr. Shadow to deal with an immortal queen. Bent on world conquest, the queen (an exact lookalike of Sapphire) marries Metamorpho. She later steps outside her mystic city and instantly ages 2,000 years. When Wally Bannister is murdered by Algon (a metamorph who has lived for centuries in a depowered state), Metamorpho is [[frame-up|framed]]. Instead of coming to his defense against the false accusations, Metamorpho's colleague Mr. Shadow comes forth as an enemy. It is revealed that Mr. Shadow was attempting to enslave Metamorpho all along. Metamorpho is tried and convicted by a jury of rabble and is then executed by [[absolute zero]]; the first of what will become a series of multiple if temporary deaths.\n\nElement Girl revives Metamorpho, and Algon, the real murderer, is killed by molten lava minerals in an attempt to regain his burned-out powers. It is later learned that Mr. Bannister's murder was actually engineered by the villainous Prosecutor, who is then killed by an [[insectoid]] villain in a cocoon. At this point, issue #17 ends, and the story is never continued.\n\nMetamorpho reappears years later in ''The Brave and the Bold'' #101 (April\u2013May 1972). It is revealed that Metamorpho had spent the period after the end of his own series immersed in a painful chemical bath concocted by Stagg in an attempt to cure his condition. Stagg retrieves him from this \"cure\" too early because he needs Mason to save his endangered daughter Sapphire. Metamorpho stars in a new backup series beginning in ''Action'' #413 (June 1972). There is no reference in this revival series to the events or characters of his previous two issues.\n\nUrania Blackwell, unreferenced since the end of the regular series, is later revealed to have ended her partnership with Metamopho when her unrequited attraction to him became too much for her. Blackwell's powers are removed at her own request by Ra, resulting in her death; the episode, in [[Neil Gaiman]]'s ''[[The Sandman (Vertigo)|Sandman]],'' involves [[Death (DC Comics)|Death]]. Death mentions Algon's death in passing, trying to convince Blackwell that she will not live forever.\n\n===Outsiders===\nMetamorpho spends some time working with the [[Outsiders (comics)|Outsiders]]. While in the [[despotism|despotically]] ruled nation Mozombia, Metamorpho is subdued and dissassembled. The tyrant's forces keep him inert with a constant application of radiation. He is freed by [[Katana (comics)|Katana's]] indestructible sword, which had been latched onto a live electrical wire. While leaving Mozombia, the Outsiders' plane is shot down by the [[Bad Samaritan]]. Metamorpho and the others spend some time stranded on a deserted island, simply too far away from land to rescue themselves.\n\nMetamorpho perishes for the second time during the ''[[Millennium (comics)|Millennium]]'' event.<ref name= outsiders27>{{Cite comic | writer=[[Mike W. Barr|Barr, Mike W.]] | artist=[[Erik Larsen|Larsen, Erik]] | story= Robot Tyrants of Kadeyland! | title=The Outsiders | volume=1 | issue=27 | date=January 1988 | publisher=DC Comics}}</ref> Doctor Jace, the scientific adviser to the Outsiders, has decided that life with the more logical [[Manhunters (DC Comics)|Manhunters]] is preferable and she betrays the team; they fight back, but Metamorpho has been brainwashed into assisting Jace. He is killed in the resulting battle.<ref name=outsiders27/> He is again revived during the ''[[Invasion! (DC Comics)|Invasion]]'' miniseries, when a gene-bomb set off by invading aliens affects his biomass.\n\n===Justice League===\nMetamorpho spends some time with the Justice League, including [[Justice League Europe]]. During this period he encounters Sapphire Stagg again. He becomes involved in a battle with the [[Metal Men]], who have been tricked by Simon Stagg. His League friends, [[Dimitri Pushkin|Rocket Red]] and [[Animal Man]], are at the site of the battle, but are being detained by Java. At the conclusion of the battle, Metamorpho learns he had a son with Sapphire. Unfortunately, the baby boy's touch harms all but Sapphire and Metamorpho. When Java holds the baby, his arms melt. Metamorpho hands the baby over to Simon, who immediately fears he will be affected like Java was moments before and die. However, something in his genetic structure protects him, just as it did with Sasphire. Simon's stance softens and everyone is set free. [[Will Magnus|Doc Magnus]], the leader of the Metal Men, offers his services in creating new arms for Java. On the way home, Metamorpho's friends are puzzled as to how he knew Simon would be unaffected by the child. Metamorpho indicates that he hoped the baby would kill Simon.\n\nLater, Metamorpho has a romantic relationship with [[Crimson Fox]], which is cut short by her apparent murder. His personal investigation of the incident uncovers multiple layers of lies and deceit. During his time with the team, while fighting the planet-smashing aliens called The Family, Metamorpho is hit by a powerful energy blast that destroys his body. He quickly re-forms in a totally different look. He will sport this new look until his next demise.\n\n===Second death===\nLater, the [[Hyperclan]] attacked the Justice League of America's [[Justice League Watchtower|orbiting base]], destroying it. Metamorpho protected three of his teammates, [[Albert Rothstein|Nuklon]], [[Obsidian (comics)|Obsidian]], and the original [[Icemaiden]], in a giant, fluid filled ball. The intent was for them to survive reentry into Earth's atmosphere. The three make it, injured but alive, but Metamorpho does not. He was buried with solemn honors. After a temporary resurrection by the wish-granting [[The Cathexis|Id]] (fundamentally flawed because the wisher, his son Joey, only wished for him to be ''back'' rather than to be ''alive''), he would return some time later.\n\n===Return===\nSapphire Stagg used the Orb of Ra to bring Metamorpho back to life, and he briefly joined the [[Doom Patrol]]. Shortly thereafter, an accident with one of Simon Stagg's experiments turned Simon, Sapphire, and Joey into an energy being, and caused Metamorpho to take on the form and personality of Java. \"Java\" kidnapped [[Black Canary]], asking for her help in rescuing the others. With Canary's help, he became Metamorpho again and managed to return the others to their normal forms.<ref>''[[Birds of Prey (comics)|Birds of Prey]]'' #51\u201352 (March\u2013April 2003)</ref>\n\n===Outsiders / \"Shift\"===\nAt the same time, Metamorpho had seemingly been appearing in the ''Outsiders'' (vol. 3) series, but Rex Mason informed the team that their \"Metamorpho\" is a regrown fragment of his own body.<ref>''Outsiders'' (vol. 3) #7 (February 2004)</ref> Rex attempts to reassimilate his \"twin\", but the Outsiders convinced him that the twin deserves the chance to lead his own life. This second Metamorpho chose the name \"Shift\" and developed a relationship with [[Indigo (comics)|Indigo]], becoming depressed over her death. After the events of ''[[One Year Later]]'', Shift willingly chose to be reassimilated into Metamorpho, because he had killed several people. Rex has stepped in to fill Shift's position in the Outsiders, while a full account of Shift's crimes is explained in the ''Outsiders'' (vol. 3) Annual; he had inadvertently killed 44 people during [[Black Lightning]]'s escape from [[Iron Heights Penitentiary]].\n\nMetamorpho continued to serve on the Outsiders when [[Batman]] took over, and following its further restructuring following Batman's apparent death. He was apparently killed alongside the rest of the team in a satellite explosion orchestrated by [[Talia al Ghul]].<ref>''[[Batman Incorporated]]: Leviathan Strikes''</ref>\n\n===The New 52===\nOn September 2011, [[The New 52]] rebooted DC's continuity. In this new timeline, an August 2013 story reveals that the Outsiders are revealed to have survived. It is mentioned that Metamorpho was able to save the team by using the same technique he used to rescue the Justice League during the Hyperclan's attack many years ago.<ref>''Batman Incorporated'' (vol. 2) #1</ref> He is also shown as one of the candidates for the new [[Justice League International]], but he is ultimately not chosen.<ref>''Justice League International'' (vol. 3) #1</ref>\n\n===DC Rebirth===\nIn the ''[[Watchmen]]'' sequel ''[[Doomsday Clock (comics)|Doomsday Clock]]'', Metamorpho is featured on the news as an example of the \"Superman Theory\" where the government has been experimenting on humans to give them superpowers.<ref>''Doomsday Clock'' #3 (January 2018). DC Comics.</ref>\n\nMetamorpho was transmuted into Nth Metal by Simon Stagg as part of his plot to open the portal to the Dark Multiverse. While trying to get Simon Stagg to close the portal with the help of Plastic Man, Mister Terrific is sucked in to the portal with Plastic Man and Metamorpho as Plastic Man shields them from the Dark Multiverse energy which he is immune to. Upon arriving on a lifeless world, they encounter Phantom Girl who has been trapped in her intangible form and had no knowledge of sending a signal. When the four of them find a computer in the gut of a dead giant creature, they are greeted by a hologram of Tom Strong who states that they are needed to save the universe.<ref>''The Terrifics'' #1. DC Comics.</ref> Mister Terrific, Plastic Man, and Metamorpho learn from Phantom Girl that she was stuck in intangible form since she was a child. After the four of them made it back to their world, Mister Terrific tries to leave the three of them at Simon Stagg's compound only to be drawn back to them.<ref>''The Terrifics'' #2. DC Comics.</ref> Due to the effects of the Dark Multiverse energy, Mister Terrific concludes that they can't go their separate ways due to this bond.<ref>''The Terrifics'' #3. DC Comics.</ref>\n\nStuck with the other heroes at Simon Stagg's residence, Metamorpho gives Sapphire an ultimatum to fully commit to their relationship after years of being duped by her father.<ref>''The Terrifics'' #3. DC Comics. </ref> She fires back with his physical insecurities, and the situation is unresolved along with Java adding tension.<ref>''The Terrifics'' #5. DC Comics. </ref> Simelatniously, the Terrifics take on fellow Element Man Algon, who wants to turn the world full of element people. In the process of defeating him by using the Orb of Ra, Rex is turned human again.<ref>''The Terrifics'' #6. DC Comics. </ref> After the Terrifics disband post - the reveal that Java was Doctor Dread all along, Rex slowly comes to realize how worthless and boring he is without his heroic duties. On purpose, Rex and Element Dog sneak into Stagg Industries and use the Orb of Ra to turn back into their elemental selves, before rejoining the other heroes in a fight against Doctor Dread's Dreadfuls. After this battle, Rex is made chief security officer at Stagg Industries, and his relationship with Sapphire is repaired.\n\n==Powers and abilities==\nMetamorpho can transmute his body to any of a wide variety of elemental compounds and form it to his will. Originally, he was limited to the elements which occur naturally in the human body. Over time, this limitation seems to have disappeared. He can alter the shapes and consistencies of these elements and combine them to form complex compounds. Rex can assume forms of gas, liquid or solid states.\n\nMetamorpho can also shape parts and portions of his body instead of the whole. He can form such complex shapes as a tank and a bicycle and such simple forms as a cloud or a spring.\n\nThe nature of Rex's body provides him with natural body armor, offering damage resistance from blunt attacks and energy attacks.\n\n==Other versions==\n===Justice===\nRex Mason/Metamorpho appears in the 12-issue mini-series ''[[Justice (DC Comics)|Justice]]'', as a member of the [[Justice League]].<ref>''Justice'' #7</ref>\n\n===JLA: The Nail===\nIn the ''[[Elseworlds]]'' story ''[[JLA: The Nail]]'', an unstable Metamorpho is forced to kill the [[Thinker (DC Comics)|Thinker]] by the [[Jimmy Olsen|unknown mastermind]] behind the recent anti-metahuman propaganda. He later attacks [[Lexcorp]] tower in [[Metropolis (comics)|Metropolis]], but [[J'onn J'onzz]] intercepts the attack, Metamorpho weakly explaining that someone forced him to kill by threatening his family, before he died as a result of their enemy's attempt to brainwash him.<ref>''JLA: The Nail'' #2</ref> In the sequel ''[[JLA: Another Nail]]'', the Outsiders are shown trying to find traces of his essence in the hope that he can be brought back to life, but they are interrupted by the current threat before they can determine if this is actually possible.\n\n===DC: The New Frontier===\nIn [[Darwyn Cooke]]'s 12-issue series, ''[[DC: The New Frontier]]'', Metamorpho appears with the rest of the Justice League at the end of the series.<ref>''DC: The New Frontier'' #12</ref>\n===Smallville===\nMetamorpho is featured in the ''[[Smallville|Smallville Season 11]]'' digital comic based on the [[Smallville|TV series]]. He is a member of the Outsiders.<ref>''Smallville Season 11: Continuity'' Vol 1 #4 (May 2015)</ref>\n\n===Batman: Arkham Knight===\nIn ''[[Batman: Arkham Knight]]'' prequel comic, Metamorpho was the result of a project named '''Project: Meta''', an attempt to turn mud obtained from [[Clayface]] into weaponry by [[Stagg Enterprises]]. The project's head scientist, upon seeing [[Batman]] and [[Deadshot]] snooping around his lab, opened fire on the pair with a laser rifle, hitting the tank storing Metamorpho and freeing it. After a brief fight, which resulted in Metamorpho escaping into Stagg Enterprises' parking lot, Batman was engulfed. Using his line launcher, Batman escaped and threw three sonic [[Batarangs]] into its body, which exploded inside it. Batman then took some samples for later study.\n\n===Injustice: Gods Among Us===\nMetamorpho appears in ''[[Injustice: Gods Among Us]]'''s prequel comic. He is depicted as a member of High Councillor Superman's Regime. In Year Four when [[Plastic Man]] breaks into the Regime's underwater prison to rescue his son, he is confronted by Metamorpho who is the prison warden. Before Metamorpho could act, Plastic Man teleports him, his son and all of the prison's inmates to a mirror dimension using some of [[Mirror Master]]'s technology. In Year Five after [[Deathstroke]] breaks into [[S.T.A.R. Labs]] to get the [[Mother Box]] for [[Batman]] and [[Lex Luthor]], he is greeted by Metamorpho before he can leave. This results in Metamorpho's death after a tense fight against Deathstroke.\n\n==In other media==\n===Television===\n====DC Animated Universe====\n[[File:metamorpho.jpg|150px|thumb|Metamorpho in ''[[Justice League Unlimited]]''.]]\n* Metamorpho appeared in the ''[[Justice League (TV series)|Justice League]]'' [[List of animated television series|animated series]], voiced by [[Tom Sizemore]]. Here, his origin has been altered: rather than his powers coming from the Orb of Ra, Rex Mason is exposed to a mutagen that transforms him into Metamorpho. He is also an old [[USMC|Marine]] friend of [[John Stewart (comics)|John Stewart]].\n* Metamorpho makes several non-speaking appearances in ''[[Justice League Unlimited]]''.\n\n====Other====\n* Metamorpho appears in ''[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]'', voiced by [[Scott Menville]]. This version is a teenager who was a member of the [[Outsiders (comics)|Outsiders]].\n* Metamorpho appears in ''[[Beware the Batman]]'', voiced by [[Adam Baldwin]].\n* In ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]]'', Metamorpho is name of a company located in [[Star City (comics)|Star City]]. According to John Diggle, it was condemned after the Glades earthquake, the man-made disaster that \"leveled\" the Glades.\n* Metamorpho is a background character in ''[[DC Super Hero Girls]]''.\n* Metamorpho appears in ''[[Young Justice: Outsiders]]'', voiced by [[Fred Tatasciore]] as a member of Batman Inc. Here, as a side-effect of his powers, he has constant pain racking his body every time he uses them; though he learned to live with it. He joined Batman and Katana on a mission to Santa Prisca to locate [[Terra (comics)|Terra]] for the Team, and though they got the information they needed, they were almost stopped by Bane, Deathstroke, and Lady Shiva. Despite the villains' best efforts, the heroes were able to escape with Oracle's help.\n\n===Film===\n* Metamorpho is one of several heroes at the end of ''[[Justice League: The New Frontier]]''.\n* Metamorpho appeared in ''[[Teen Titans Go! To the Movies]]''.\n\n===Miscellaneous===\n* Metamorpho appears in ''[[Justice League Unlimited]]'''s spin-off comic book, issue #31.\n* Metamorpho appears in the 1975 spin-off of the Justice League of America [[Peter Pan Records]] (Power Records) LP, in a solo audio action adventure called \"Metamorpho \u2014 The Element Man \u2014 Fumo, The Fire Giant\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dccomics.com/heroes_and_villains/?hv=origin_stories/metamorpho Metamorpho's secret origin] at DCcomics.com\n* [http://www.toonopedia.com/metamor.htm Metamorpho the Element Man] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/6fLnqZvtV Archived] from the original on February 17, 2016.\n\n{{Metamorpho}}\n{{Justice League}}\n{{Justice League characters}}\n\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1965]]\n[[Category:1965 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:DC Comics titles]]\n[[Category:Fictional archaeologists]]\n[[Category:DC Comics characters who are shapeshifters]]\n[[Category:Fictional soldiers]]\n[[Category:DC Comics metahumans]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with elemental transmutation abilities]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who can stretch themselves]]\n[[Category:Fictional alchemists]]\n[[Category:DC Comics characters with accelerated healing]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who can duplicate themselves]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Bob Haney]]\n[[Category:American comics characters]]\n[[Category:Male characters in comics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fictional superhero}}\n{{Infobox comics character\n| character_name = Metamorpho\n| image = Nolan metamorpho.jpg\n| converted = y\n| caption = Metamorpho emerging from a periodic table on the cover to ''Metamorpho'' (Volume 2) #1 (August 1993), by [[Graham Nolan]]\n| alt = Metamorpho smiling and standing on a periodic table\n| publisher = [[DC Comics]]\n| debut = ''[[The Brave and the Bold]]'' #57 (January 1965)\n| creators = {{hlist|[[Bob Haney]]|[[Ramona Fradon]]}}\n| alter_ego = Rex Mason\n| alliances = [[Outsiders (comics)|Outsiders]]<br/>[[Justice League Europe]]<br/>[[Seven Soldiers of Victory]]<br/>[[Doom Patrol]]<br/>[[Stagg Enterprises]]<br/>Terrifics<br/>[[Justice League]]\n| aliases = The Element Man, Dyna-Man\n| species = [[Metahuman]]\n| powers = Elemental Shapeshifting <br> Super-Strength <br> Invulnerability \n| cat = super\n| subcat = DC Comics\n| hero = y\n| sortkey = Metamorpho\n}}\n'''Metamorpho''' (real name '''Rex Mason''', also called '''The Element Man''') is a [[fictional character|fictional]] [[superhero]] appearing in [[American comic books]] published by [[DC Comics]]. He was created in 1964 by writer [[Bob Haney]] and artist [[Ramona Fradon]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cowsill |first1=Alan |last2=Irvine |first2=Alex |last3=Korte |first3=Steve |last4=Manning |first4=Matt |last5=Wiacek |first5=Win |last6=Wilson |first6=Sven |title=The DC Comics Encyclopedia: The Definitive Guide to the Characters of the DC Universe |date=2016 |publisher=DK Publishing |isbn=978-1-4654-5357-0 |page=201}}</ref> \n\nMetamorpho is a founding member of the [[Outsiders (comics)|Outsiders]], and has also joined multiple incarnations of the [[Justice League]]. The character has been moderately popular since his introduction in 1965. Originally adventurer Rex Mason, he is converted into a man made of a shifting mass of chemicals after being cursed by an ancient artifact that he has retrieved.\n\n==Publication history==\nMetamorpho's creator, [[Bob Haney]], had seen success with DC Comics in 1963 with the titles ''[[Metal Men]]'' and ''[[Doom Patrol]]'', featuring bands of superheroes exhibiting fantastic powers. Under the editorial management of [[George Kashdan]], Haney was asked to capitalize on these titles' popularity with a similar character. Metamorpho, the Element Man, debuted in ''[[The Brave and the Bold]]'' #57 (January 1965).<ref>{{cite book| last= McAvennie |first= Michael| editor-last= Dolan| editor-first= Hannah |chapter= 1960s|title = DC Comics Year By Year A Visual Chronicle| publisher= [[Dorling Kindersley]] |year=2010 |isbn= 978-0-7566-6742-9 |page= 114 |quote = Scribe Bob Haney and artist Ramona Fradon were truly in their element...Haney and Fradon's collaborative chemistry resulted in [Rex] Mason becoming Metamorpho.}}</ref>\n\nAs first conceived, Metamorpho was a parody of the fantastic characters that populated comic books in the 1960s.<ref>{{cite book | last=Jones | first=Gerard |author2=Will Jacobs | title=The Comic Book Heroes | location=[[Rocklin, California]] | publisher=Prima Lifestyles | pages=76\u201377 | date=October 23, 1996 | isbn=978-0-7615-0393-4}}</ref> Artist [[Ramona Fradon]] was coaxed out of maternity retirement to illustrate Metamorpho's first appearances. The popularity of Metamorpho's appearances in ''The Brave and the Bold'' led to a 17-issue [[ongoing series]] between 1965 and 1968. Metamorpho also appeared during this time in two issues of ''Justice League of America'' (#42 and #44) and became the second superhero to decline an invitation to join that organization ([[Adam Strange]] being the first), though he did become a reservist, eventually being called in during a Justice League/Justice Society crossover to help find and rescue the Seven Soldiers of Victory.\n\nMetamorpho appears on the cover of ''Aquaman'' #30 as one of the pallbearers (along with Batman, Hawkman, and Superman) at the \"Sea King's Funeral\".<ref>{{cite web| url= http://comicvine.gamespot.com/aquaman-30-the-death-of-aquaman/4000-108970/ |title=Aquaman #30 - The Death of Aquaman |website=Comic Vine |access-date=15 April 2016}}</ref> Metamorpho also appears in a series of backup stories in ''[[Action Comics]]'' #413\u2013418 and ''[[World's Finest Comics]]'' #218\u2013220 and #229.<ref>{{cite journal|last = Stroud|first = Bryan|title = Metamorpho in ''Action Comics'' |journal= [[Back Issue!]] |issue = 64 |pages = 22\u201327| publisher = [[TwoMorrows Publishing]] |date = May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Metamorpho appeared in ''[[1st Issue Special]]'' #3, a brief anthology series consisting of one-shots. That issue was written by Bob Haney and illustrated by Ramona Fradon, Metamorpho's creators. Haney and Fradon had met at the 1974 [[San Diego Comic-Con]], and while reminiscing, it emerged that both of them regarded Metamorpho as one of the features they'd most enjoyed working on, leading them to ask DC if they could do one more Metamorpho story together.<ref name=\"back71\">{{cite journal|last=Abramowitz |first= Jack| title= 1st Issue Special: It Was No ''Showcase'' (But It Was Never Meant To Be)| journal= [[Back Issue!]]| issue=71 |page= 42| publisher= [[TwoMorrows Publishing]]| date= April 2014 |location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref> Fradon later commented, \"I think we both felt that Metamorpho was our baby. I never had an experience like I had working with Bob Haney on ''Metamorpho''. It was like our minds were in perfect synch ... it was one of those wonderful collaborations that doesn't happen very often.\"<ref name=\"back71\"/>\n\nAfter becoming a charter member of the Outsiders in 1983, and member of the European branch of the [[Justice League International]], Metamorpho received his own four-issue mini-series in 1993.\n\nIn 2005, DC Comics reprinted Metamorpho's early ''The Brave and the Bold'' appearances and the entirety of the 1965 series as one of the company's volumes of ''[[Showcase Presents]]''.\n\nIn 2007, [[Dan Jurgens]] launched the six-issue series ''Metamorpho: Year One''.\n\nAs part of a ''[[Wednesday Comics]]'', [[Neil Gaiman]] wrote a 12-page Metamorpho story that [[Mike Allred]] illustrated.<ref>{{cite web | first= Remy | last= Minnick | url= http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=19775 | title=Gaiman & Allred on Metamorpho | work=[[Comic Book Resources]] | date=January 30, 2009 | accessdate=January 31, 2009}}</ref> In 2016 he starred in a new comic book series titled DC's ''Legends of Tomorrow''.<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://comicvine.gamespot.com/articles/aaron-lopresti-talks-metamorpho-in-new-dcs-legends/1100-155102/ |title= Aaron Lopresti Talks Metamorpho in New DC's LEGENDS OF TOMORROW Series|work=Comic Vine |access-date= 2018-09-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Fictional character biography==\nRex Mason is an adventurer who is hired by [[Stagg Enterprises]] CEO, [[Simon Stagg]], to retrieve a rare [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptian]] artifact, the [[Orb of Ra]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Markstein |first1=Don |website=Don Markstein's Toonopedia |accessdate=2 April 2020  |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/metamor.htm |title=Metamorpho the Element Man}}</ref> Shortly after hiring him, Simon Stagg learns that Mason has been dating his daughter, [[Sapphire Stagg]]. This and other incidents begin to fuel in Stagg a dislike for Mason that ultimately leads to a plot to kill him.\n\nIn an [[Egyptian pyramids|Egyptian pyramid]], Rex Mason is knocked unconscious by Simon's brutish bodyguard [[Java (comics)|Java]] and is eventually exposed to a radioactive [[meteoroid|meteor]]ite from which the Orb of [[Ra]] was fashioned. A tremendous flare-up of its radiation transforms Mason into Metamorpho, the Element Man. He gains the ability to [[shapeshifting|shapeshift]] and change himself into any [[chemical element|element]] or combination of elements found in the human body. It is also established in his origin story in ''[[The Brave & The Bold]]'' #57 that Metamorpho is virtually invulnerable in his inert (untransformed) state, when Stagg, afraid that Rex is going to kill him, shoots him point-blank without effect. The Orb of Ra, however, has the same effect on Rex that [[kryptonite]] has on [[Superman]]. Thus Stagg continues to control Metamorpho using the Orb. Later, it is revealed that Mason is but one of many [[metamorphae]]. They were created by the sun god Ra, using the meteorite, to serve as warriors in his battle against the god [[Apep]], \"the serpent who never dies.\"<ref>{{cite book | title=The DC Comics Encyclopedia | last1=Beatty | first1=Scott | authorlink1=Scott Beatty | last2=Jimenez | first2=Phil | authorlink2=Phil Jimenez | date=October 4, 2004 | publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]] Limited | isbn=978-0-7566-0592-6 | page=202}}</ref>\n\nMetamorpho, unlike most super-humanoids described in DC Comics, cannot assume a normal, fully human appearance, being no longer composed of flesh, blood and bone. As such, he regards his metamorphic powers as a disease and seeks a cure for his condition. Because he considers himself a freak and wishes only to be restored to his former human state, he rejects an offer of membership from the [[Justice League of America]] in ''JLA'' #42. [[Green Lantern]] attempts to change him back using his power ring, but due to a \"yellow\" component of the meteorite radiation, is unable to make him normal again.\n\nMetamorpho briefly has a crimefighting partner named Urania \"Rainie\" Blackwell, a woman who deliberately exposed herself to the Orb to gain its powers. She calls herself [[Element Girl]] (nicknamed \"the Chemical Doll\") and works with him on a number of cases.\n\nIssues #16\u201317 were intended to show a new direction for the series, with Sapphire marrying a man named Wally Bannister and Metamorpho joining a mysterious Mr. Shadow to deal with an immortal queen. Bent on world conquest, the queen (an exact lookalike of Sapphire) marries Metamorpho. She later steps outside her mystic city and instantly ages 2,000 years. When Wally Bannister is murdered by Algon (a metamorph who has lived for centuries in a depowered state), Metamorpho is [[frame-up|framed]]. Instead of coming to his defense against the false accusations, Metamorpho's colleague Mr. Shadow comes forth as an enemy. It is revealed that Mr. Shadow was attempting to enslave Metamorpho all along. Metamorpho is tried and convicted by a jury of rabble and is then executed by [[absolute zero]]; the first of what will become a series of multiple if temporary deaths.\n\nElement Girl revives Metamorpho, and Algon, the real murderer, is killed by molten lava minerals in an attempt to regain his burned-out powers. It is later learned that Mr. Bannister's murder was actually engineered by the villainous Prosecutor, who is then killed by an [[insectoid]] villain in a cocoon. At this point, issue #17 ends, and the story is never continued.\n\nMetamorpho reappears years later in ''The Brave and the Bold'' #101 (April\u2013May 1972). It is revealed that Metamorpho had spent the period after the end of his own series immersed in a painful chemical bath concocted by Stagg in an attempt to cure his condition. Stagg retrieves him from this \"cure\" too early because he needs Mason to save his endangered daughter Sapphire. Metamorpho stars in a new backup series beginning in ''Action'' #413 (June 1972). There is no reference in this revival series to the events or characters of his previous two issues.\n\nUrania Blackwell, unreferenced since the end of the regular series, is later revealed to have ended her partnership with Metamopho when her unrequited attraction to him became too much for her. Blackwell's powers are removed at her own request by Ra, resulting in her death; the episode, in [[Neil Gaiman]]'s ''[[The Sandman (Vertigo)|Sandman]],'' involves [[Death (DC Comics)|Death]]. Death mentions Algon's death in passing, trying to convince Blackwell that she will not live forever.\n\n===Outsiders===\nMetamorpho spends some time working with the [[Outsiders (comics)|Outsiders]]. While in the [[despotism|despotically]] ruled nation Mozombia, Metamorpho is subdued and dissassembled. The tyrant's forces keep him inert with a constant application of radiation. He is freed by [[Katana (comics)|Katana's]] indestructible sword, which had been latched onto a live electrical wire. While leaving Mozombia, the Outsiders' plane is shot down by the [[Bad Samaritan]]. Metamorpho and the others spend some time stranded on a deserted island, simply too far away from land to rescue themselves.\n\nMetamorpho perishes for the second time during the ''[[Millennium (comics)|Millennium]]'' event.<ref name= outsiders27>{{Cite comic | writer=[[Mike W. Barr|Barr, Mike W.]] | artist=[[Erik Larsen|Larsen, Erik]] | story= Robot Tyrants of Kadeyland! | title=The Outsiders | volume=1 | issue=27 | date=January 1988 | publisher=DC Comics}}</ref> Doctor Jace, the scientific adviser to the Outsiders, has decided that life with the more logical [[Manhunters (DC Comics)|Manhunters]] is preferable and she betrays the team; they fight back, but Metamorpho has been brainwashed into assisting Jace. He is killed in the resulting battle.<ref name=outsiders27/> He is again revived during the ''[[Invasion! (DC Comics)|Invasion]]'' miniseries, when a gene-bomb set off by invading aliens affects his biomass.\n\n===Justice League===\nMetamorpho spent some time with the Justice League, including [[Justice League Europe]]. There, he encounters Sapphire Stagg again. He becomes involved in a battle with the [[Metal Men]], who had been tricked by Simon. His League friends, [[Dimitri Pushkin|Rocket Red]] and [[Animal Man]], were at the site of the battle, but were being detained by Java. At the conclusion of the battle, Metamorpho learns he had a son with Sapphire. Unfortunately, the baby boy's touch harmed all but Sapphire and Metamorpho. When Java held the baby, Java's arms melted. Metamorpho handed the baby over to Simon, who became convinced he would die, harmed like Java had been moments ago. However, something in his genetic structure protected him, just as it did with the baby's mother. Simon's stance softened and everyone was set free. [[Will Magnus|Doc Magnus]], the leader of the Metal Men, offered his services in creating new arms for Java. On the way home, Metamorpho's friends were puzzled as to how he knew Simon would be unaffected by the child. Metamorpho indicates that he had hoped the baby would kill Simon.\n\nMetamorpho would later have a romantic relationship with [[Crimson Fox]], which was cut short by her apparent murder. His personal investigation of the incident uncovers multiple layers of lies and deceit. During his time with the team, while fighting the planet-smashing aliens called The Family, Metamorpho is hit by a powerful energy blast that destroys his body. He quickly re-forms in a totally different look. He will sport this new look until his next demise.\n\n===Second death===\nLater, the [[Hyperclan]] attacked the Justice League of America's [[Justice League Watchtower|orbiting base]], destroying it. Metamorpho protected three of his teammates, [[Albert Rothstein|Nuklon]], [[Obsidian (comics)|Obsidian]], and the original [[Icemaiden]], in a giant, fluid filled ball. The intent was for them to survive reentry into Earth's atmosphere. The three make it, injured but alive, but Metamorpho does not. He was buried with solemn honors. After a temporary resurrection by the wish-granting [[The Cathexis|Id]] (fundamentally flawed because the wisher, his son Joey, only wished for him to be ''back'' rather than to be ''alive''), he would return some time later.\n\n===Return===\nSapphire Stagg used the Orb of Ra to bring Metamorpho back to life, and he briefly joined the [[Doom Patrol]]. Shortly thereafter, an accident with one of Simon Stagg's experiments turned Simon, Sapphire, and Joey into an energy being, and caused Metamorpho to take on the form and personality of Java. \"Java\" kidnapped [[Black Canary]], asking for her help in rescuing the others. With Canary's help, he became Metamorpho again and managed to return the others to their normal forms.<ref>''[[Birds of Prey (comics)|Birds of Prey]]'' #51\u201352 (March\u2013April 2003)</ref>\n\n===Outsiders / \"Shift\"===\nAt the same time, Metamorpho had seemingly been appearing in the ''Outsiders'' (vol. 3) series, but Rex Mason informed the team that their \"Metamorpho\" is a regrown fragment of his own body.<ref>''Outsiders'' (vol. 3) #7 (February 2004)</ref> Rex attempts to reassimilate his \"twin\", but the Outsiders convinced him that the twin deserves the chance to lead his own life. This second Metamorpho chose the name \"Shift\" and developed a relationship with [[Indigo (comics)|Indigo]], becoming depressed over her death. After the events of ''[[One Year Later]]'', Shift willingly chose to be reassimilated into Metamorpho, because he had killed several people. Rex has stepped in to fill Shift's position in the Outsiders, while a full account of Shift's crimes is explained in the ''Outsiders'' (vol. 3) Annual; he had inadvertently killed 44 people during [[Black Lightning]]'s escape from [[Iron Heights Penitentiary]].\n\nMetamorpho continued to serve on the Outsiders when [[Batman]] took over, and following its further restructuring following Batman's apparent death. He was apparently killed alongside the rest of the team in a satellite explosion orchestrated by [[Talia al Ghul]].<ref>''[[Batman Incorporated]]: Leviathan Strikes''</ref>\n\n===The New 52===\nOn September 2011, [[The New 52]] rebooted DC's continuity. In this new timeline, an August 2013 story reveals that the Outsiders are revealed to have survived. It is mentioned that Metamorpho was able to save the team by using the same technique he used to rescue the Justice League during the Hyperclan's attack many years ago.<ref>''Batman Incorporated'' (vol. 2) #1</ref> He is also shown as one of the candidates for the new [[Justice League International]], but he is ultimately not chosen.<ref>''Justice League International'' (vol. 3) #1</ref>\n\n===DC Rebirth===\nIn the ''[[Watchmen]]'' sequel ''[[Doomsday Clock (comics)|Doomsday Clock]]'', Metamorpho is featured on the news as an example of the \"Superman Theory\" where the government has been experimenting on humans to give them superpowers.<ref>''Doomsday Clock'' #3 (January 2018). DC Comics.</ref>\n\nMetamorpho was transmuted into Nth Metal by Simon Stagg as part of his plot to open the portal to the Dark Multiverse. While trying to get Simon Stagg to close the portal with the help of Plastic Man, Mister Terrific is sucked in to the portal with Plastic Man and Metamorpho as Plastic Man shields them from the Dark Multiverse energy which he is immune to. Upon arriving on a lifeless world, they encounter Phantom Girl who has been trapped in her intangible form and had no knowledge of sending a signal. When the four of them find a computer in the gut of a dead giant creature, they are greeted by a hologram of Tom Strong who states that they are needed to save the universe.<ref>''The Terrifics'' #1. DC Comics.</ref> Mister Terrific, Plastic Man, and Metamorpho learn from Phantom Girl that she was stuck in intangible form since she was a child. After the four of them made it back to their world, Mister Terrific tries to leave the three of them at Simon Stagg's compound only to be drawn back to them.<ref>''The Terrifics'' #2. DC Comics.</ref> Due to the effects of the Dark Multiverse energy, Mister Terrific concludes that they can't go their separate ways due to this bond.<ref>''The Terrifics'' #3. DC Comics.</ref>\n\nStuck with the other heroes at Simon Stagg's residence, Metamorpho gives Sapphire an ultimatum to fully commit to their relationship after years of being duped by her father.<ref>''The Terrifics'' #3. DC Comics. </ref> She fires back with his physical insecurities, and the situation is unresolved along with Java adding tension.<ref>''The Terrifics'' #5. DC Comics. </ref> Simelatniously, the Terrifics take on fellow Element Man Algon, who wants to turn the world full of element people. In the process of defeating him by using the Orb of Ra, Rex is turned human again.<ref>''The Terrifics'' #6. DC Comics. </ref> After the Terrifics disband post - the reveal that Java was Doctor Dread all along, Rex slowly comes to realize how worthless and boring he is without his heroic duties. On purpose, Rex and Element Dog sneak into Stagg Industries and use the Orb of Ra to turn back into their elemental selves, before rejoining the other heroes in a fight against Doctor Dread's Dreadfuls. After this battle, Rex is made chief security officer at Stagg Industries, and his relationship with Sapphire is repaired.\n\n==Powers and abilities==\nMetamorpho can transmute his body to any of a wide variety of elemental compounds and form it to his will. Originally, he was limited to the elements which occur naturally in the human body. Over time, this limitation seems to have disappeared. He can alter the shapes and consistencies of these elements and combine them to form complex compounds. Rex can assume forms of gas, liquid or solid states.\n\nMetamorpho can also shape parts and portions of his body instead of the whole. He can form such complex shapes as a tank and a bicycle and such simple forms as a cloud or a spring.\n\nThe nature of Rex's body provides him with natural body armor, offering damage resistance from blunt attacks and energy attacks.\n\n==Other versions==\n===Justice===\nRex Mason/Metamorpho appears in the 12-issue mini-series ''[[Justice (DC Comics)|Justice]]'', as a member of the [[Justice League]].<ref>''Justice'' #7</ref>\n\n===JLA: The Nail===\nIn the ''[[Elseworlds]]'' story ''[[JLA: The Nail]]'', an unstable Metamorpho is forced to kill the [[Thinker (DC Comics)|Thinker]] by the [[Jimmy Olsen|unknown mastermind]] behind the recent anti-metahuman propaganda. He later attacks [[Lexcorp]] tower in [[Metropolis (comics)|Metropolis]], but [[J'onn J'onzz]] intercepts the attack, Metamorpho weakly explaining that someone forced him to kill by threatening his family, before he died as a result of their enemy's attempt to brainwash him.<ref>''JLA: The Nail'' #2</ref> In the sequel ''[[JLA: Another Nail]]'', the Outsiders are shown trying to find traces of his essence in the hope that he can be brought back to life, but they are interrupted by the current threat before they can determine if this is actually possible.\n\n===DC: The New Frontier===\nIn [[Darwyn Cooke]]'s 12-issue series, ''[[DC: The New Frontier]]'', Metamorpho appears with the rest of the Justice League at the end of the series.<ref>''DC: The New Frontier'' #12</ref>\n===Smallville===\nMetamorpho is featured in the ''[[Smallville|Smallville Season 11]]'' digital comic based on the [[Smallville|TV series]]. He is a member of the Outsiders.<ref>''Smallville Season 11: Continuity'' Vol 1 #4 (May 2015)</ref>\n\n===Batman: Arkham Knight===\nIn ''[[Batman: Arkham Knight]]'' prequel comic, Metamorpho was the result of a project named '''Project: Meta''', an attempt to turn mud obtained from [[Clayface]] into weaponry by [[Stagg Enterprises]]. The project's head scientist, upon seeing [[Batman]] and [[Deadshot]] snooping around his lab, opened fire on the pair with a laser rifle, hitting the tank storing Metamorpho and freeing it. After a brief fight, which resulted in Metamorpho escaping into Stagg Enterprises' parking lot, Batman was engulfed. Using his line launcher, Batman escaped and threw three sonic [[Batarangs]] into its body, which exploded inside it. Batman then took some samples for later study.\n\n===Injustice: Gods Among Us===\nMetamorpho appears in ''[[Injustice: Gods Among Us]]'''s prequel comic. He is depicted as a member of High Councillor Superman's Regime. In Year Four when [[Plastic Man]] breaks into the Regime's underwater prison to rescue his son, he is confronted by Metamorpho who is the prison warden. Before Metamorpho could act, Plastic Man teleports him, his son and all of the prison's inmates to a mirror dimension using some of [[Mirror Master]]'s technology. In Year Five after [[Deathstroke]] breaks into [[S.T.A.R. Labs]] to get the [[Mother Box]] for [[Batman]] and [[Lex Luthor]], he is greeted by Metamorpho before he can leave. This results in Metamorpho's death after a tense fight against Deathstroke.\n\n==In other media==\n===Television===\n====DC Animated Universe====\n[[File:metamorpho.jpg|150px|thumb|Metamorpho in ''[[Justice League Unlimited]]''.]]\n* Metamorpho appeared in the ''[[Justice League (TV series)|Justice League]]'' [[List of animated television series|animated series]], voiced by [[Tom Sizemore]]. Here, his origin has been altered: rather than his powers coming from the Orb of Ra, Rex Mason is exposed to a mutagen that transforms him into Metamorpho. He is also an old [[USMC|Marine]] friend of [[John Stewart (comics)|John Stewart]].\n* Metamorpho makes several non-speaking appearances in ''[[Justice League Unlimited]]''.\n\n====Other====\n* Metamorpho appears in ''[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]'', voiced by [[Scott Menville]]. This version is a teenager who was a member of the [[Outsiders (comics)|Outsiders]].\n* Metamorpho appears in ''[[Beware the Batman]]'', voiced by [[Adam Baldwin]].\n* In ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]]'', Metamorpho is name of a company located in [[Star City (comics)|Star City]]. According to John Diggle, it was condemned after the Glades earthquake, the man-made disaster that \"leveled\" the Glades.\n* Metamorpho is a background character in ''[[DC Super Hero Girls]]''.\n* Metamorpho appears in ''[[Young Justice: Outsiders]]'', voiced by [[Fred Tatasciore]] as a member of Batman Inc. Here, as a side-effect of his powers, he has constant pain racking his body every time he uses them; though he learned to live with it. He joined Batman and Katana on a mission to Santa Prisca to locate [[Terra (comics)|Terra]] for the Team, and though they got the information they needed, they were almost stopped by Bane, Deathstroke, and Lady Shiva. Despite the villains' best efforts, the heroes were able to escape with Oracle's help.\n\n===Film===\n* Metamorpho is one of several heroes at the end of ''[[Justice League: The New Frontier]]''.\n* Metamorpho appeared in ''[[Teen Titans Go! To the Movies]]''.\n\n===Miscellaneous===\n* Metamorpho appears in ''[[Justice League Unlimited]]'''s spin-off comic book, issue #31.\n* Metamorpho appears in the 1975 spin-off of the Justice League of America [[Peter Pan Records]] (Power Records) LP, in a solo audio action adventure called \"Metamorpho \u2014 The Element Man \u2014 Fumo, The Fire Giant\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dccomics.com/heroes_and_villains/?hv=origin_stories/metamorpho Metamorpho's secret origin] at DCcomics.com\n* [http://www.toonopedia.com/metamor.htm Metamorpho the Element Man] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/6fLnqZvtV Archived] from the original on February 17, 2016.\n\n{{Metamorpho}}\n{{Justice League}}\n{{Justice League characters}}\n\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1965]]\n[[Category:1965 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:DC Comics titles]]\n[[Category:Fictional archaeologists]]\n[[Category:DC Comics characters who are shapeshifters]]\n[[Category:Fictional soldiers]]\n[[Category:DC Comics metahumans]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with elemental transmutation abilities]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who can stretch themselves]]\n[[Category:Fictional alchemists]]\n[[Category:DC Comics characters with accelerated healing]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who can duplicate themselves]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Bob Haney]]\n[[Category:American comics characters]]\n[[Category:Male characters in comics]]\n", "name_user": "BPK2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJustice League", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metamorpho"}
{"title_page": "2019 in Ireland", "text_new": "{{For|Northern Ireland|2019 in Northern Ireland}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{YearInIrelandNav|2019}}\n\nEvents during the year '''[[2019]] in [[Ireland]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n[[File:Michael D. Higgins 2006.jpg|thumb|120px|upright|right|[[President of Ireland|President]] [[Michael D. Higgins]]]]\n* [[President of Ireland|President]]: [[Michael D. Higgins]] \n* [[Taoiseach]]: [[Leo Varadkar]] ([[Fine Gael|FG]])\n* [[T\u00e1naiste]]: [[Simon Coveney]] ([[Fine Gael|FG]])\n* [[Minister for Finance (Ireland)|Minister for Finance]]: [[Paschal Donohoe]] ([[Fine Gael|FG]])\n* [[Chief Justice of Ireland|Chief Justice]]: [[Frank Clarke (judge)|Frank Clarke]] \n* [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann|D\u00e1il]]: [[Members of the 32nd D\u00e1il|32nd]]\n* [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Seanad]]: [[Members of the 25th Seanad|25th]]\n\n== Events ==\n<!-- PLEASE PROVIDE PROPER CITATIONS FOR ALL ITEMS ADDED -->\n<!-- NOTE: Do not add national holidays (e.g Christmas, Easter) or anything that occurs every year (e.g Clocks go back) from this section -->\n\n=== January ===\n<!-- PLEASE PROVIDE PROPER CITATIONS FOR ALL ITEMS ADDED -->\n* 1 January \n** Abortion services became available in Ireland for the first time under the provisions of the [[Health (Regulation of Termination of Pregnancy) Act 2018]].<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2019/0101/1019777-abortion-services-ireland/ Abortion services to be provided in Ireland from today] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-01-01.</ref>\n** Two fast-food workers were shot by a raider at Edenmore Shopping Centre in [[Coolock]] shortly after the new year was rung in.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/2019/0101/1019776-shooting-takeaway-dublin/ Two men hospitalised after shooting in Dublin fast-food outlet] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-01-01.</ref>\n**Library fines were abolished to encourage library usage. <ref>[https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/libraries-nationwide-abolish-fines-for-overdue-items-895205.html] www.breakingnews.ie, 02/01/2019.</ref>\n* 2 January \u2013 New domestic violence legislation was enacted which included new crimes of coercive control.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/domestic-violence-law-to-cover-coercion-and-dates-895061.html Domestic violence law to cover coercion and dates] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-02.</ref>\n* 3 January \n** The [[Luas]] website went offline after a message was posted to it threatening to \"publish all data and send emails to your users\" unless \"1 bitcoin\" was paid in five days.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/news/luas-website-hack-likely-first-of-many-in-2019-security-experts-warn-37678171.html Luas website hack 'likely first of many in 2019', security experts warn] Irish Independent, 2019-01-03.</ref>\n** Contingency plans for a [[Brexit negotiations#The .22no deal.22 scenario|no-deal Brexit]] were discussed at the first [[31st Government of Ireland|Cabinet]] meeting of 2019.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/brexit/2019/0103/1020058-brexit-contingency-cabinet/ Cabinet discusses no-deal Brexit contingency plans] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-01-03.</ref>\n* 4 January \u2013 Former [[Seanad|Senator]] [[James Heffernan (Irish politician)|James Heffernan]] was found guilty of assaulting three garda\u00ed after he was arrested outside the [[Indiependence|Indiependence Music Festival]] in August 2016.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/former-senator-convicted-of-kicking-and-spitting-at-gardai-outside-of-music-festival-37681332.html Former Senator convicted of kicking and spitting at gardai outside of music festival] Irish Independent, 2019-01-04.</ref>\n* 5 January \u2013 Figures from [[Eurostat]] showed that the Irish police-to-population ratio was less than the European average with 278 Garda officers per 100,000 of the population.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/278-gardai-for-every-100000-people-irish-policing-figures-among-lowest-in-europe-895812.html 278 garda\u00ed for every 100,000 people; Irish policing figures among lowest in Europe] Irish Independent, 2019-01-05.</ref>\n* 6 January \u2013 Garda sources confirmed that a man named as having been captured in [[Syria]] by militias fighting against [[ISIS]] was a naturalised Irish citizen.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/irish-citizen-captured-in-syria-by-group-fighting-isis-37685164.html Irish citizen captured in Syria by group fighting ISIS] Irish Independent, 2019-01-06.</ref>\n* 7 January \u2013 A Garda investigation began after skeletal remains were found by a passerby in a ditch in the townland of Ballyandrew, [[County Wexford]].<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/garda-probe-after-skeletal-remains-found-in-wexford-37687870.html Garda probe after skeletal remains found in Wexford] Irish Independent, 2019-01-07.</ref>\n* 9 January \u2013 The Government offered protection to five unaccompanied child migrants who had been seeking refuge in [[Malta]] after being rescued from the Mediterranean.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/ireland-in-talks-to-take-migrants-from-ship-floating-off-maltas-coast-since-december-896562.html Ireland in talks to take migrants from ship floating off Malta's coast since December] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-09.</ref>\n* 10 January \u2013 A fire broke out at the Shannon Key West Hotel in [[Roosky]] which had been due to open as an accommodation centre for asylum seekers.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/fire-at-leitrim-hotel-earmarked-for-asylum-seeker-accommodation-896903.html Fire at Leitrim hotel earmarked for asylum seeker accommodation] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-10.</ref>\n* 11 January \u2013 17-year-old Adam Kelly from Skerries Community College was named the 55th [[BT Young Scientist|BT Young Scientist & Technologist of the Year]].<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/im-in-total-shock-adam-kelly-17-crowned-the-bt-young-scientist-winner-37703349.html 'I\u2019m in total shock' - Adam Kelly (17) crowned the BT Young Scientist winner] Irish Independent, 2019-01-11.</ref>\n* 12 January \u2013 One of the most senior figures in the Kinahan organised crime gang was arrested at [[Birmingham Airport]] in a joint operation between the Garda\u00ed and the [[National Crime Agency|NCA]].<ref>[https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/british-police-questioning-senior-kinahan-figure-after-arrest-897223.html British police questioning senior Kinahan figure after arrest] Breaking News, 2019-01-12.</ref>\n* 13 January \u2013 [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] announced plans to reintroduce a Bill to the Seanad which aims to protect and give official recognition to the [[Amhr\u00e1n na bhFiann|National Anthem]].<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/fianna-fail-reintroducing-bill-to-give-national-anthem-official-recognition-897256.html Fianna F\u00e1il reintroducing Bill to give National Anthem official recognition] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-13.</ref>\n* 15 January \u2013 [[County Galway|Galway]]-based [[Supermac's]] won its long-running case against fast food giant [[McDonald's]] to have the use of the [[Big Mac]] trademark cancelled.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/the-end-of-the-mcbully-supermacs-welcomes-big-mac-trademark-win-over-mcdonalds-897789.html 'The end of the McBully': Supermacs welcomes 'Big Mac' trademark win over McDonald's] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-15.</ref>\n* 16 January \u2013 The [[Paschal Donohoe|Finance Minister]] ordered a new economic assessment for the country after a [[British House of Commons|parliamentary]] defeat for the [[British Government]]'s [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]].<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/paschal-donohoe-orders-economic-assessment-given-increased-risk-of-no-deal-brexit-898040.html Paschal Donohoe orders economic assessment given increased risk of no-deal Brexit] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-16.</ref>\n* 17 January \n**[[Aer Lingus]] unveiled its new brand livery which included a new shamrock logo, a new font, and teal as the main colour on the undercarriage, tail and engines of its planes.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/life/travel/travel-news/aer-lingus-reveals-first-brand-makeover-in-20-years-37721325.html Aer Lingus reveals first brand makeover in 20 years] Irish Independent, 2019-01-17.</ref>\n**The D\u00e1il was told that a woman carrying a baby diagnosed with a fatal foetal abnormality was not granted a termination at the [[Coombe Women & Infants University Hospital|Coombe Hospital]] in [[Dublin]].<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/health/woman-refused-abortion-at-dublin-hospital-dil-is-told-37721832.html Woman refused abortion at Dublin hospital, D\u00e1il is told] Irish Independent, 2019-01-17.</ref>\n**A 22-year-old man died after being shot in the head and chest in a car park outside a gym in [[Swords, County Dublin|Swords]] in Dublin.<ref>[https://www.thejournal.ie/shooting-swords-4446288-Jan2019/ One person shot dead and another seriously injured outside gym in Swords, Co Dublin] The Journal, 2019-01-17.</ref>\n* 18 January \u2013 A man is shot dead and a woman injured at a house in [[Warrenpoint]], [[County Down]].\n* 19 January \u2013 \n**Hundreds of young people attended a protest at [[Leinster House]] calling on the Government to do more to tackle climate change.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/children-gather-on-streets-of-dublin-for-climate-change-protest-898695.html Children gather on streets of Dublin for climate change protest] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-14.</ref>\n**A car bomb exploded outside a courthouse in [[Derry]]. The [[New IRA]] are believed to be responsible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/police-arrest-further-two-men-in-connection-with-londonderry-car-bomb-attack-37729490.html|title=Police arrest further two men in connection with Londonderry car bomb attack|publisher=|via=www.belfasttelegraph.