right--dublin/407249|title=The death has occurred of Barbara Wright (n\u00e9e Robinson)|publisher=rip.ie|date=16 December 2019|accessdate=17 December 2019|first=|last=}}</ref>\n* 17 December \u2013 [[Con Hartnett]], 68, Gaelic footballer, ([[Millstreet GAA|Millstreet]], [[Cork GAA|Cork]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.echolive.ie/corksport/The-late-All-Ireland-winner-Con-Hartnett-showed-his-talent-by-playing-five-years-in-a-row-at-minor-for-Millstreet-a5c43b55-cdc4-4c52-987e-2fbc8e1a89f9-ds|title=The late All-Ireland winner Con Hartnett showed his talent by playing five years in a row at minor for Millstreet|publisher=The Echo|date=18 December 2019|accessdate=18 December 2019|first=John|last=Tarrant}}</ref>\n* 21 December \u2013 [[Frankie Kennedy (Gaelic footballer)|Frankie Kennedy]], 78, Gaelic footballer, ([[Drumlane GAA|Drumlane]], [[Cavan GAA|Cavan]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hoganstand.com/Article/Index/306996|title=Cavan GAA pay tribute to the late Frankie Kennedy|publisher=Hogan Stand|date=22 December 2019|accessdate=22 December 2019|first=|last=}}</ref>\n* 28 December \u2013 Jean Costello, 76, actress (''[[Fair City]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2019/1228/1103378-jean-costello/|title=Fair City actress Jean Costello dies, aged 76|publisher=RT\u00c9 News|date=28 December 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019|first=|last=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n{{Commonscat|2019 in Ireland}}\n{{Wikinews|Category: Ireland}}\n* [[2019 European Parliament election]]\n\n{{Portal bar |Ireland|Current events|Europe|EU|Politics|History|Business|Countries|Science|Technology}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Ireland}}\n{{Year in Europe|2019}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|Northern Ireland|2019 in Northern Ireland}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{YearInIrelandNav|2019}}\n\nEvents during the year '''[[2019]] in [[Ireland]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n[[File:Michael D. Higgins 2006.jpg|thumb|120px|upright|right|[[President of Ireland|President]] [[Michael D. Higgins]]]]\n* [[President of Ireland|President]]: [[Michael D. Higgins]] \n* [[Taoiseach]]: [[Leo Varadkar]] ([[Fine Gael|FG]])\n* [[T\u00e1naiste]]: [[Simon Coveney]] ([[Fine Gael|FG]])\n* [[Minister for Finance (Ireland)|Minister for Finance]]: [[Paschal Donohoe]] ([[Fine Gael|FG]])\n* [[Chief Justice of Ireland|Chief Justice]]: [[Frank Clarke (judge)|Frank Clarke]] \n* [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann|D\u00e1il]]: [[Members of the 32nd D\u00e1il|32nd]]\n* [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Seanad]]: [[Members of the 25th Seanad|25th]]\n\n== Events ==\n<!-- PLEASE PROVIDE PROPER CITATIONS FOR ALL ITEMS ADDED -->\n<!-- NOTE: Do not add national holidays (e.g Christmas, Easter) or anything that occurs every year (e.g Clocks go back) from this section -->\n\n=== January ===\n<!-- PLEASE PROVIDE PROPER CITATIONS FOR ALL ITEMS ADDED -->\n* 1 January \n** Abortion services became available in Ireland for the first time under the provisions of the [[Health (Regulation of Termination of Pregnancy) Act 2018]].<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2019/0101/1019777-abortion-services-ireland/ Abortion services to be provided in Ireland from today] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-01-01.</ref>\n** Two fast-food workers were shot by a raider at Edenmore Shopping Centre in [[Coolock]] shortly after the new year was rung in.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/2019/0101/1019776-shooting-takeaway-dublin/ Two men hospitalised after shooting in Dublin fast-food outlet] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-01-01.</ref>\n**Library fines were abolished to encourage library usage. <ref>[https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/libraries-nationwide-abolish-fines-for-overdue-items-895205.html] www.breakingnews.ie, 02/01/2019.</ref>\n* 2 January \u2013 New domestic violence legislation was enacted which included new crimes of coercive control.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/domestic-violence-law-to-cover-coercion-and-dates-895061.html Domestic violence law to cover coercion and dates] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-02.</ref>\n* 3 January \n** The [[Luas]] website went offline after a message was posted to it threatening to \"publish all data and send emails to your users\" unless \"1 bitcoin\" was paid in five days.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/news/luas-website-hack-likely-first-of-many-in-2019-security-experts-warn-37678171.html Luas website hack 'likely first of many in 2019', security experts warn] Irish Independent, 2019-01-03.</ref>\n** Contingency plans for a [[Brexit negotiations#The .22no deal.22 scenario|no-deal Brexit]] were discussed at the first [[31st Government of Ireland|Cabinet]] meeting of 2019.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/brexit/2019/0103/1020058-brexit-contingency-cabinet/ Cabinet discusses no-deal Brexit contingency plans] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-01-03.</ref>\n* 4 January \u2013 Former [[Seanad|Senator]] [[James Heffernan (Irish politician)|James Heffernan]] was found guilty of assaulting three garda\u00ed after he was arrested outside the [[Indiependence|Indiependence Music Festival]] in August 2016.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/former-senator-convicted-of-kicking-and-spitting-at-gardai-outside-of-music-festival-37681332.html Former Senator convicted of kicking and spitting at gardai outside of music festival] Irish Independent, 2019-01-04.</ref>\n* 5 January \u2013 Figures from [[Eurostat]] showed that the Irish police-to-population ratio was less than the European average with 278 Garda officers per 100,000 of the population.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/278-gardai-for-every-100000-people-irish-policing-figures-among-lowest-in-europe-895812.html 278 garda\u00ed for every 100,000 people; Irish policing figures among lowest in Europe] Irish Independent, 2019-01-05.</ref>\n* 6 January \u2013 Garda sources confirmed that a man named as having been captured in [[Syria]] by militias fighting against [[ISIS]] was a naturalised Irish citizen.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/irish-citizen-captured-in-syria-by-group-fighting-isis-37685164.html Irish citizen captured in Syria by group fighting ISIS] Irish Independent, 2019-01-06.</ref>\n* 7 January \u2013 A Garda investigation began after skeletal remains were found by a passerby in a ditch in the townland of Ballyandrew, [[County Wexford]].<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/garda-probe-after-skeletal-remains-found-in-wexford-37687870.html Garda probe after skeletal remains found in Wexford] Irish Independent, 2019-01-07.</ref>\n* 9 January \u2013 The Government offered protection to five unaccompanied child migrants who had been seeking refuge in [[Malta]] after being rescued from the Mediterranean.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/ireland-in-talks-to-take-migrants-from-ship-floating-off-maltas-coast-since-december-896562.html Ireland in talks to take migrants from ship floating off Malta's coast since December] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-09.</ref>\n* 10 January \u2013 A fire broke out at the Shannon Key West Hotel in [[Roosky]] which had been due to open as an accommodation centre for asylum seekers.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/fire-at-leitrim-hotel-earmarked-for-asylum-seeker-accommodation-896903.html Fire at Leitrim hotel earmarked for asylum seeker accommodation] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-10.</ref>\n* 11 January \u2013 17-year-old Adam Kelly from Skerries Community College was named the 55th [[BT Young Scientist|BT Young Scientist & Technologist of the Year]].<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/im-in-total-shock-adam-kelly-17-crowned-the-bt-young-scientist-winner-37703349.html 'I\u2019m in total shock' - Adam Kelly (17) crowned the BT Young Scientist winner] Irish Independent, 2019-01-11.</ref>\n* 12 January \u2013 One of the most senior figures in the Kinahan organised crime gang was arrested at [[Birmingham Airport]] in a joint operation between the Garda\u00ed and the [[National Crime Agency|NCA]].<ref>[https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/british-police-questioning-senior-kinahan-figure-after-arrest-897223.html British police questioning senior Kinahan figure after arrest] Breaking News, 2019-01-12.</ref>\n* 13 January \u2013 [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] announced plans to reintroduce a Bill to the Seanad which aims to protect and give official recognition to the [[Amhr\u00e1n na bhFiann|National Anthem]].<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/fianna-fail-reintroducing-bill-to-give-national-anthem-official-recognition-897256.html Fianna F\u00e1il reintroducing Bill to give National Anthem official recognition] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-13.</ref>\n* 15 January \u2013 [[County Galway|Galway]]-based [[Supermac's]] won its long-running case against fast food giant [[McDonald's]] to have the use of the [[Big Mac]] trademark cancelled.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/the-end-of-the-mcbully-supermacs-welcomes-big-mac-trademark-win-over-mcdonalds-897789.html 'The end of the McBully': Supermacs welcomes 'Big Mac' trademark win over McDonald's] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-15.</ref>\n* 16 January \u2013 The [[Paschal Donohoe|Finance Minister]] ordered a new economic assessment for the country after a [[British House of Commons|parliamentary]] defeat for the [[British Government]]'s [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]].<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/paschal-donohoe-orders-economic-assessment-given-increased-risk-of-no-deal-brexit-898040.html Paschal Donohoe orders economic assessment given increased risk of no-deal Brexit] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-16.</ref>\n* 17 January \n**[[Aer Lingus]] unveiled its new brand livery which included a new shamrock logo, a new font, and teal as the main colour on the undercarriage, tail and engines of its planes.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/life/travel/travel-news/aer-lingus-reveals-first-brand-makeover-in-20-years-37721325.html Aer Lingus reveals first brand makeover in 20 years] Irish Independent, 2019-01-17.</ref>\n**The D\u00e1il was told that a woman carrying a baby diagnosed with a fatal foetal abnormality was not granted a termination at the [[Coombe Women & Infants University Hospital|Coombe Hospital]] in [[Dublin]].<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/health/woman-refused-abortion-at-dublin-hospital-dil-is-told-37721832.html Woman refused abortion at Dublin hospital, D\u00e1il is told] Irish Independent, 2019-01-17.</ref>\n**A 22-year-old man died after being shot in the head and chest in a car park outside a gym in [[Swords, County Dublin|Swords]] in Dublin.<ref>[https://www.thejournal.ie/shooting-swords-4446288-Jan2019/ One person shot dead and another seriously injured outside gym in Swords, Co Dublin] The Journal, 2019-01-17.</ref>\n* 18 January \u2013 A man is shot dead and a woman injured at a house in [[Warrenpoint]], [[County Down]].\n* 19 January \u2013 \n**Hundreds of young people attended a protest at [[Leinster House]] calling on the Government to do more to tackle climate change.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/children-gather-on-streets-of-dublin-for-climate-change-protest-898695.html Children gather on streets of Dublin for climate change protest] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-14.</ref>\n**A car bomb exploded outside a courthouse in [[Derry]]. The [[New IRA]] are believed to be responsible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/police-arrest-further-two-men-in-connection-with-londonderry-car-bomb-attack-37729490.html|title=Police arrest further two men in connection with Londonderry car bomb attack|publisher=|via=www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n* 20 January \u2013 A commemoration was held to mark the 100th anniversary of the [[Soloheadbeg Ambush]], which is considered to have started the [[Irish War of Independence|War of Independence]].<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/incoming/there-was-never-any-intention-to-kill-them-thousands-gather-in-soloheadbeg-to-commemorate-centenary-of-ambush-that-sparked-war-of-independence-37729724.html 'There was never any intention to kill them' - thousands gather in Soloheadbeg to commemorate centenary of ambush that sparked War of Independence] Irish Independent, 2019-01-20.</ref>\n* 21 January \u2013 The centenary of the [[First D\u00e1il]] was commemorated with a joint sitting of the [[D\u00e1il]] and [[Seanad]] in the round room of the [[Mansion House, Dublin|Mansion House]] in Dublin.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/100-years-today-since-first-dail-sat-898940.html 100 years today since first D\u00e1il sat] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-21.</ref>\n* 22 January \u2013 [[European Commission]] spokesman [[Margaritis Schinas]] said Ireland would see a new \"[[Irish border question|hard border]]\" if the UK failed to approve a Brexit withdrawal deal.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/brexit/2019/0122/1024720-brexit/  'Difficult' to prevent border infrastructure without withdrawal agreement] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-01-22.</ref>\n* 23 January \u2013 Garda\u00ed seized almost \u20ac1 million worth of cannabis in [[Drogheda]].<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/2019/0123/1025106-cannabis-drogheda/ Garda\u00ed seize cannabis worth almost \u20ac1 million in Louth] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-01-23.</ref>\n* 24 January \u2013 The Government published legislation that would underpin Ireland's plan to deal with a no-deal Brexit.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/2019/0124/1025281-plans-for-brexit/ Government publishes plans for no-deal Brexit] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-01-24.</ref>\n* 25 January \u2013 The Taoiseach warned of the prospect of \"a police presence, or an army presence\" at the border in a worst-case Brexit.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/business/brexit/we-may-need-a-police-presence-an-army-presence-taoiseach-warns-of-troops-on-border-37748541.html 'We may need a police presence, an army presence' - Taoiseach warns of troops on border] Irish Indepdendent, 2019-01-25.</ref>\n* 26 January \u2013 Up to 1,500 people attended a protest on the old Dublin road near Carrickcaron, [[County Louth]] to demonstrate against a hard Brexit.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/2019/0126/1025639-brexit-protest-border/ Protests, conference held over Brexit risks and Stormont delays] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-01-26.</ref>\n* 27 January \u2013 Four men in their early twenties were killed in a road accident near [[Gort an Choirce]], [[County Donegal]].<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/four-young-men-killed-in-devastating-car-crash-in-co-donegal-named-locally-37755049.html Four young men killed in 'devastating' car crash in Co Donegal named locally] Irish Independent, 2019-01-27.</ref>\n* 28 January \u2013 Former [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]] [[Peadar T\u00f3ib\u00edn]] launched a new political party called [[Aont\u00fa]].<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/peadar-toibin-reveals-his-new-political-party-will-be-named-aont-37759442.html Peadar Toibin reveals his new political party will be named Aont\u00fa] Irish Independent, 2019-01-28.</ref>\n* 29 January \u2013 The Cabinet agreed to hold a referendum which, if passed, would delete a [[Bunreacht na h\u00c9ireann|Constitutional]] clause requiring a mandatory period of separation before divorce.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/divorce-referendum-to-ask-voters-if-politicians-should-have-power-to-decide-on-pause-period-37760776.html Divorce referendum 'to ask voters if politicians should have power to decide on 'pause period'] ''Irish Independent'', 2019-01-29.</ref>\n* 30 January \u2013 Hospital and community care services were severely disrupted by the first 24-hour nurses' strike in 20 years.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/examviral/sights-and-sounds-from-todays-nurses-strike-901141.html Sights and sounds from today's historic nurses' strike] Irish Examiner, 2019-01-30.</ref>\n\n===February===\n* 1 February \u2013 Skeletal remains and a ring fort, believed to date back to the [[Bronze Age]], were discovered on land where former Taoiseach [[Liam Cosgrave]] lived in Dublin.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/skeletal-remains-believed-to-be-from-bronze-age-discovered-at-former-home-of-late-taoiseach-901693.html Skeletal remains believed to be from Bronze Age discovered at former home of late Taoiseach] Irish Examiner, 2019-02-01.</ref>\n* 2 February \u2013 The chairman of the [[New children's hospital|National Children's Hospital Development]] board Tom Costello resigned following the controversy over the spiralling costs of the project.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/chair-of-childrens-hospital-development-board-tom-costello-resigns-901843.html Chair of Children's Hospital development board Tom Costello resigns] Irish Examiner, 2019-02-02.</ref>\n* 3 February \u2013 [[Damian Foxall]] made a 400-metre descent on skis from the summit of Ireland's highest mountain, [[Carrauntoohil]].<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/munster/2019/0203/1027268-damian-foxhall-carrauntoohil/ Renowned sailor completes descent of Carrauntoohil on skis] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-02-03.</ref><ref>[https://www.facebook.com/damian.foxall/videos/10156912380038764/ Summit video] Damian Foxall, 2019-02-03.</ref><ref>[https://www.facebook.com/damian.foxall/videos/10156912395168764/ Descent video] Damian Foxall, 2019-02-03.</ref>\n* 4 February \u2013 The [[Central Bank of Ireland|Central Bank]] announced that \u20ac674m was paid by banks in redress, compensation and costs to customers caught up in the tracker mortgage controversy.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/business/2019/0204/1027409-central-bank-tracker-examination/ \u20ac647m paid out to 39,800 affected tracker mortgage customers] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-02-04.</ref>\n* 5 February \u2013 Nearly 40,000 nurses and midwives undertook a second day of strike action in an ongoing dispute over pay and retention issues.<ref>[https://www.thejournal.ie/were-just-run-off-our-feet-nealry-40000-nurses-and-midwives-begin-second-day-of-strike-action-2-4477389-Feb2019/ 'We're just run off our feet': Nearly 40,000 nurses and midwives begin second day of strike action] The Journal, 2019-02-05.</ref>\n* 6 February \u2013 [[European Commission President]] [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] said Ireland will not be left alone and the EU is ready to assist Ireland in the event of a no-deal Brexit.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/2019/0206/1027940-juncker-varadkar-brexit/ EU ready to assist Ireland in no-deal Brexit scenario -Juncker] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-02-06.</ref>\n* 7 February \u2013 More than 35,000 nurses took to the picket line for the third time in nine days causing widespread chaos in hospitals and in the community.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/health/labour-court-may-step-in-to-try-resolve-nurses-strike-37794107.html Labour court may step in to try resolve nurses' strike] Irish Independent, 2019-02-07.</ref>\n* 8 February\n**A 39-year-old man died after being shot a number of times after leaving his home for work in [[Darndale]].<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/man-killed-in-dublin-gun-attack-named-as-gardai-work-to-establish-motive-903081.html Man killed in Dublin gun attack named as garda\u00ed work to establish motive] Irish Examiner, 2019-02-08.</ref>\n**The Taoiseach met each of the five main [[Stormont Estate|Stormont]] parties in [[Belfast]] before hosting discussions with [[British Prime Minister]] [[Theresa May]] at [[Farmleigh]].<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/brexit/2019/0208/1028244-brexit/ Varadkar meets main Stormont parties in Belfast] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-02-08.</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/no-breakthrough-on-brexit-deal-as-varadkar-and-may-meet-in-dublin-37798007.html 'No breakthrough' on Brexit deal as Varadkar and May meet in Dublin] Irish Independent, 2019-02-08.</ref>\n* 9 February\n**Tens of thousands of people took part in a rally in support of nurses and midwives who are involved in a dispute over pay and staffing levels.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/health/thousands-take-part-in-support-rally-for-nurses-as-pay-talks-set-to-resume-37798669.html Thousands take part in support rally for nurses as pay talks set to resume] Irish Independent, 2019-02-09.</ref>\n**The [[SDLP]] voted by more than two to one to back a new partnership with Fianna F\u00e1il.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2019/0209/1028583-sdlp-linkup-fianna-fail/ SDLP votes in favour of partnership with Fianna F\u00e1il] RT\u00c9 News, 2019-02-09.</ref>\n* 10 February \n**The [[Minister for Health (Ireland)|Health Minister]] [[Simon Harris (politician)|Simon Harris]] and his family were trapped in their home as up to 20 people arrived outside, claiming to be \"against austerity\".<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/completely-and-utterly-unacceptable-protest-outside-health-ministers-family-home-is-criticised-37800967.html 'Completely and utterly unacceptable' - protest outside Health Minister's family home is criticised] Irish Independent, 2019-02-10.</ref>\n**It was later announced that Harris will apologise to the D\u00e1il over information he provided on the cost of the new National Children's Hospital.<ref>[https://www.thejournal.ie/simon-harris-national-childrens-hospital-2-4486595-Feb2019/ Harris to apologise over children's hospital overrun as Sinn F\u00e9in denies wanting to trigger election] Irish Examiner, 2019-02-10.</ref>\n* 11 February \n**President Higgins began a three-day visit to [[England]], during which he is expected to call for ties between Ireland and the UK to remain strong after Brexit.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/president-higgins-visits-birmingham-at-start-of-three-day-visit-to-england-903600.html President Higgins visits Birmingham at start of three-day visit to England] Irish Examiner, 2019-02-11.</ref>\n**After discussions at the Labour Court, the [[Irish Nurses and Midwives Organisation|INMO]] and the Psychiatric Nurses Associat