orksport/The-late-All-Ireland-winner-Con-Hartnett-showed-his-talent-by-playing-five-years-in-a-row-at-minor-for-Millstreet-a5c43b55-cdc4-4c52-987e-2fbc8e1a89f9-ds|title=The late All-Ireland winner Con Hartnett showed his talent by playing five years in a row at minor for Millstreet|publisher=The Echo|date=18 December 2019|accessdate=18 December 2019|first=John|last=Tarrant}}</ref>\n* 21 December \u2013 [[Frankie Kennedy (Gaelic footballer)|Frankie Kennedy]], 78, Gaelic footballer, ([[Drumlane GAA|Drumlane]], [[Cavan GAA|Cavan]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hoganstand.com/Article/Index/306996|title=Cavan GAA pay tribute to the late Frankie Kennedy|publisher=Hogan Stand|date=22 December 2019|accessdate=22 December 2019|first=|last=}}</ref>\n* 28 December \u2013 Jean Costello, 76, actress (''[[Fair City]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2019/1228/1103378-jean-costello/|title=Fair City actress Jean Costello dies, aged 76|publisher=RT\u00c9 News|date=28 December 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019|first=|last=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n{{Commonscat|2019 in Ireland}}\n{{Wikinews|Category: Ireland}}\n* [[2019 European Parliament election]]\n\n{{Portal bar |Ireland|Current events|Europe|EU|Politics|History|Business|Countries|Science|Technology}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Ireland}}\n{{Year in Europe|2019}}\n", "name_user": "Bygmester", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJanuary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_in_Ireland"}
{"title_page": "Anina", "text_new": "{{About|the Romanian city}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Cara\u0219-Severin\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Cara\u0219-Severin County\n|official_name=Anina\n|image_shield=ROU CS Anina CoA.png\n|image_map=Anina jud Caras-Severin.png\n|image_skyline=Uzinele de fier Anina.JPG\n|image_caption=Anina Iron Works\n|leader_name=Gheorghe Rom\u00e2nu<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=PNL\n|area_total_km2=145.53\n|coordinates    = {{coord|45|5|30|N|21|51|12|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website=\n}}\n\n'''Anina''' ({{IPA-ro|'anina}};<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c4Tph88uNiE#t=29m19s|title=Anina 2017, ora\u0219ul mort, uitat \u0219i s\u0103r\u0103cit odat\u0103 cu \u00eenchiderea minei}}</ref> [[German language|German]]: ''Steierdorf''; [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]: ''St\u00e1jerlakanina'') is a town in southwestern  [[Romania]], in [[Cara\u0219-Severin County]], with a population of 10,886 in 2000. The town administers one village, Steierdorf (German: ''Steierdorf'', Hungarian: ''St\u00e1jerlak'').\n\n==Geology==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1956 |11837\n|1966 |14063\n|1977 |11478\n|1992 |11329\n|2002 |10594\n|2011 |7485\n}}\n\nIn 2002, the oldest modern human remains in [[Europe]] were discovered in a cave near Anina. Nicknamed ''\"Ion din Anina\"'' ([[John of Anina]]), the remains (the lower jaw) are some 40,000 years old.\n\nAnina represents one of the most important localities in the South Carpathians for Jurassic fossils, both plants and animals, as the geological heritage here is particularly diverse and well preserved (Popa, 2001, 2005). Anina is a fossile-Lagerstatte for Early Jurassic biota, the Hettangian-Sinemurian terrestrial Steierdorf Formation recording an extremely rich floral association, vertebrate and invertebrate tracks, traces and burrows. This paleontological heritage was uncovered also by significant mining works, such as underground mines and open cast mines, such works permitting the three-dimensional studies of the continental deposits, a unique opportunity in Europe and in the world, until the unfortunate closing of the last major mine in 2006. Still, the sterile dumps of the former mines and the former open cast mines of Ponor and Colonia Ceha very are rich in plant material, and they represent the subject of local conservation, as preserved sites or Sites of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI). \n[[File:Anina-Oravita 03 2010.jpg|thumb|left|225px|View from Oravi\u021ba - Anina [[mountain railway]] in 2010]]\n\nThe Early Jurassic (Hettangian - Sinemurian) flora is represented by Bryophytes (Hepaticae), Pteridophytes (Filicopsida, Sphenopsida, Lycopsida) and Gymnosperms (Pteridospermopsida, Ginkgopsida, Cycadopsida, Coniferopsida), with numerous coal generators (Givulescu, 1998, Popa and Van Konijnenburg - Van Cittert, 2005). Very rare vertebrate tunnels were recently described (Popa and Kedzior, 2006), such burrows being formerly reported only from three occurrences in the world (South Africa, Arizona and Argentina), tetrapod tracks such as ''Batrachopus'' cf. ''deweyi'' (Popa, 2000), and sauropod tracks of ''Parabrontopodus'' sp. type (Pienkowski et al., 2009).\n\nThe Middle Jurassic marine formations are also extremely rich in marine invertebrates and drifted floral remains, while the Upper Jurassic and Lower Cretaceous units display basinal and carbonate platform features (Bucur, 1997).\n\nThe coal mining industrial heritage is also significant, with Austrian industrial architecture and pits still preserved, such as the Northern Pit (Anina Pit I), Pit II, Pit IV (next to the Terezia Valley). Coal mining activities began in 1792, after the first coal outcrop was discovered by Matthew Hammer.\n\nThe Anina-Oravita railway built in 1863, it is still in use today for touristic purposes. It is one of the most beautiful railways in Europe due to very picturesque landscapes, viaducts and long tunnels. The railway preserves many aspects of the original  design and, as such, it does not comply with many [[International Union of Railways|UIC]] standards and it needs special, more powerful locomotives and shorter rail coaches to operate.\n\nAnina occurs between Cheile Nerei-Beusnita National Park and Semenic-Cheile Carasului National Park, and due to its natural and industrial heritage deserves the status of a geopark, a much needed status for such an important geological and historical area.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pe\u0219tera Muierilor]]\n* [[Pe\u0219tera cu Oase]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Wikivoyage|Anina}}\n{{Commons category|Anina}}\n* Bucur, I.I., 1997. Formatiunile mesozoice din zona Resita-Moldova Noua, Cluj-Napoca, 214 pp.\n* Givulescu, R., 1998. Flora fosila a Jurasicului inferior de la Anina. Editura Academiei Romane, Bucuresti, 90 pp.\n* Pienkowski, G., Popa, M.E. and Kedzior, A., 2009. [http://mepopa.com/Pdfs/Pdf%20Mihai/pienkowskietal2010.pdf Early Jurassic sauropod footprints of the Southern Carpathians, Romania: palaeobiological and palaeogeographical significance]. Geological Quarterly, 53(4): 461\u2013470.\n* Popa, M.E., 2000. [http://mepopa.com/Pdfs/Pdf%20Mihai/popa_1999b.pdf First find of Mesozoic tetrapod tracks in Romania]. Acta Palaeontologica Romaniae, 2: 387\u2013390.\n* Popa, M.E., 2001. Ponor SSSI (Site of Special Scientific Interest). Lower Jurassic Paleoflora. In: I.I. Bucur, Filipescu, S., Sasaran, E. (Editor), Algae and carbonate platforms in western part of Romania. Field trip guidebook. Babes-Bolyai University, Cluj-Napoca, pp.&nbsp;167\u2013171.\n* Popa, M.E., 2005. [http://mepopa.com/Pdfs/Pdf%20Mihai/popa_2005.pdf Aspects of Romanian Early Jurassic Palaeobotany and Palynology. Part VI. Anina, an exceptional locality]. Acta Palaeontologica Romaniae, 5: 375\u2013378.\n* Popa, M.E. and Kedzior, A., 2006. [http://mepopa.com/Pdfs/Pdf%20Mihai/popa_2005.pdf Preliminary ichnological results on the Steierdorf Formation in Anina, Romania]. In: Z. Csiki (Editor), Mesozoic and Cenozoic vertebrates and paleoenvironments, Bucuresti, pp.&nbsp;197\u2013201.\n* Popa, M.E. and Van Konijnenburg - Van Cittert, J.H.A., 2006. [http://mepopa.com/Pdfs/Pdf%20Mihai/popa_vkvc_2006.pdf Aspects of Romanian Early - Middle Jurassic palaeobotany and palynology. Part VII. Successions and floras]. Progress in Natural Sciences, 16: 203\u2013212.\n\n{{Cara\u015f-Severin County}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Cara\u0219-Severin County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Mining communities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Monotowns in Romania]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Romanian city}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Cara\u0219-Severin\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Cara\u0219-Severin County\n|official_name=Anina\n|image_shield=ROU CS Anina CoA.png\n|image_map=Anina jud Caras-Severin.png\n|image_skyline=Uzinele de fier Anina.JPG\n|image_caption=Anina Iron Works\n|leader_name=Gheorghe Rom\u00e2nu\n|leader_party=PNL\n|area_total_km2=145.53\n|coordinates    = {{coord|45|5|30|N|21|51|12|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website=\n}}\n\n'''Anina''' ({{IPA-ro|'anina}};<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c4Tph88uNiE#t=29m19s|title=Anina 2017, ora\u0219ul mort, uitat \u0219i s\u0103r\u0103cit odat\u0103 cu \u00eenchiderea minei}}</ref> [[German language|German]]: ''Steierdorf''; [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]: ''St\u00e1jerlakanina'') is a town in southwestern  [[Romania]], in [[Cara\u0219-Severin County]], with a population of 10,886 in 2000. The town administers one village, Steierdorf (German: ''Steierdorf'', Hungarian: ''St\u00e1jerlak'').\n\n==Geology==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1956 |11837\n|1966 |14063\n|1977 |11478\n|1992 |11329\n|2002 |10594\n|2011 |7485\n}}\n\nIn 2002, the oldest modern human remains in [[Europe]] were discovered in a cave near Anina. Nicknamed ''\"Ion din Anina\"'' ([[John of Anina]]), the remains (the lower jaw) are some 40,000 years old.\n\nAnina represents one of the most important localities in the South Carpathians for Jurassic fossils, both plants and animals, as the geological heritage here is particularly diverse and well preserved (Popa, 2001, 2005). Anina is a fossile-Lagerstatte for Early Jurassic biota, the Hettangian-Sinemurian terrestrial Steierdorf Formation recording an extremely rich floral association, vertebrate and invertebrate tracks, traces and burrows. This paleontological heritage was uncovered also by significant mining works, such as underground mines and open cast mines, such works permitting the three-dimensional studies of the continental deposits, a unique opportunity in Europe and in the world, until the unfortunate closing of the last major mine in 2006. Still, the sterile dumps of the former mines and the former open cast mines of Ponor and Colonia Ceha very are rich in plant material, and they represent the subject of local conservation, as preserved sites or Sites of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI). \n[[File:Anina-Oravita 03 2010.jpg|thumb|left|225px|View from Oravi\u021ba - Anina [[mountain railway]] in 2010]]\n\nThe Early Jurassic (Hettangian - Sinemurian) flora is represented by Bryophytes (Hepaticae), Pteridophytes (Filicopsida, Sphenopsida, Lycopsida) and Gymnosperms (Pteridospermopsida, Ginkgopsida, Cycadopsida, Coniferopsida), with numerous coal generators (Givulescu, 1998, Popa and Van Konijnenburg - Van Cittert, 2005). Very rare vertebrate tunnels were recently described (Popa and Kedzior, 2006), such burrows being formerly reported only from three occurrences in the world (South Africa, Arizona and Argentina), tetrapod tracks such as ''Batrachopus'' cf. ''deweyi'' (Popa, 2000), and sauropod tracks of ''Parabrontopodus'' sp. type (Pienkowski et al., 2009).\n\nThe Middle Jurassic marine formations are also extremely rich in marine invertebrates and drifted floral remains, while the Upper Jurassic and Lower Cretaceous units display basinal and carbonate platform features (Bucur, 1997).\n\nThe coal mining industrial heritage is also significant, with Austrian industrial architecture and pits still preserved, such as the Northern Pit (Anina Pit I), Pit II, Pit IV (next to the Terezia Valley). Coal mining activities began in 1792, after the first coal outcrop was discovered by Matthew Hammer.\n\nThe Anina-Oravita railway built in 1863, it is still in use today for touristic purposes. It is one of the most beautiful railways in Europe due to very picturesque landscapes, viaducts and long tunnels. The railway preserves many aspects of the original  design and, as such, it does not comply with many [[International Union of Railways|UIC]] standards and it needs special, more powerful locomotives and shorter rail coaches to operate.\n\nAnina occurs between Cheile Nerei-Beusnita National Park and Semenic-Cheile Carasului National Park, and due to its natural and industrial heritage deserves the status of a geopark, a much needed status for such an important geological and historical area.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pe\u0219tera Muierilor]]\n* [[Pe\u0219tera cu Oase]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Wikivoyage|Anina}}\n{{Commons category|Anina}}\n* Bucur, I.I., 1997. Formatiunile mesozoice din zona Resita-Moldova Noua, Cluj-Napoca, 214 pp.\n* Givulescu, R., 1998. Flora fosila a Jurasicului inferior de la Anina. Editura Academiei Romane, Bucuresti, 90 pp.\n* Pienkowski, G., Popa, M.E. and Kedzior, A., 2009. [http://mepopa.com/Pdfs/Pdf%20Mihai/pienkowskietal2010.pdf Early Jurassic sauropod footprints of the Southern Carpathians, Romania: palaeobiological and palaeogeographical significance]. Geological Quarterly, 53(4): 461\u2013470.\n* Popa, M.E., 2000. [http://mepopa.com/Pdfs/Pdf%20Mihai/popa_1999b.pdf First find of Mesozoic tetrapod tracks in Romania]. Acta Palaeontologica Romaniae, 2: 387\u2013390.\n* Popa, M.E., 2001. Ponor SSSI (Site of Special Scientific Interest). Lower Jurassic Paleoflora. In: I.I. Bucur, Filipescu, S., Sasaran, E. (Editor), Algae and carbonate platforms in western part of Romania. Field trip guidebook. Babes-Bolyai University, Cluj-Napoca, pp.&nbsp;167\u2013171.\n* Popa, M.E., 2005. [http://mepopa.com/Pdfs/Pdf%20Mihai/popa_2005.pdf Aspects of Romanian Early Jurassic Palaeobotany and Palynology. Part VI. Anina, an exceptional locality]. Acta Palaeontologica Romaniae, 5: 375\u2013378.\n* Popa, M.E. and Kedzior, A., 2006. [http://mepopa.com/Pdfs/Pdf%20Mihai/popa_2005.pdf Preliminary ichnological results on the Steierdorf Formation in Anina, Romania]. In: Z. Csiki (Editor), Mesozoic and Cenozoic vertebrates and paleoenvironments, Bucuresti, pp.&nbsp;197\u2013201.\n* Popa, M.E. and Van Konijnenburg - Van Cittert, J.H.A., 2006. [http://mepopa.com/Pdfs/Pdf%20Mihai/popa_vkvc_2006.pdf Aspects of Romanian Early - Middle Jurassic palaeobotany and palynology. Part VII. Successions and floras]. Progress in Natural Sciences, 16: 203\u2013212.\n\n{{Cara\u015f-Severin County}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Cara\u0219-Severin County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Mining communities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Monotowns in Romania]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anina"}
{"title_page": "2018\u20132020 UK higher education strikes", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n[[File:2018 UK higher education strike placards .jpg|thumb|2018 UK higher education strike placards]]\nThe [[University and College Union]] (UCU), a trade union representing 110,000 staff at UK universities,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/1685/About-UCU|title=About UCU|website=www.ucu.org.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> ran a major series of connected strikes in 2018, 2019, and 2020. The action has been characterised as \"something of a milestone\" for \"impending service sector strikes of the 21st century\".\n\nIn 2018, the dispute concerned proposed changes to the [[Universities Superannuation Scheme]] (USS).<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9242/UCU-announces-14-strike-dates-at-61-universities-in-pensions-row|title=UCU announces 14 strike dates at 61 universities in pensions row|website=www.ucu.org.uk|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305150446/https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9242/UCU-announces-14-strike-dates-at-61-universities-in-pensions-row|archivedate=5 March 2018|access-date=12 March 2018}}</ref> In 2019\u201320, strike action on USS continued, and action on a parallel dispute over pay equality, workload, casualisation, and pay levels was added.<ref name=\"Bethan Staton 2019\">Bethan Staton, '[https://www.ft.com/content/ca606a64-ffe8-11e9-b7bc-f3fa4e77dd47 Universities face 8-day strike as disputes rumble on]', ''Financial Times'' (5 November 2019).</ref>\n\nThe first strike began in February 2018. This strike escalated over fourteen strike days between 22 February and 20 March, and took place at sixty-four universities across the UK, represented by [[Universities UK]] (UUK).<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43140729 |title=University strike: What's it all about? |last=Burns |first=Judith |date=21 February 2018 |work=BBC News|access-date=12 March 2018 |language=en-GB |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227005517/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43140729 |archivedate=27 February 2018 }}</ref> This was the longest ever strike in UK higher-education history.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/ |title=WIRED UK - Future Science, Culture & Technology News and Reviews |website=www.wired.co.uk|access-date=20 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226094835/http://www.wired.co.uk/ |archivedate=26 February 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/university-lecturers-to-strike-as-students-sit-summer-exams-2jmmxlsbx|title=University lecturers to strike as students sit summer exams|last=Woolcock|first=Nicola|date=9 March 2018|work=The Times|language=en|issn=0140-0460|access-date=12 March 2018}}</ref> The [[Office for National Statistics]] found that in 2018, 66% of all working days lost to strike action were accounted for by the education sector, \"due mainly to disputes involving employees of universities\".<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20191021101946/https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/workplacedisputesandworkingconditions/articles/labourdisputes/2018 Labour disputes in the UK: 2018]\" (17 May 2019).</ref> An estimated 42,000 staff<ref name=\":12\" /> went on strike with 575,000 teaching hours being lost.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/pensions-strike-forces-uk-universities-reset-examinations|title=Pensions strike forces UK universities to reset examinations|date=2018-03-28|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2018-03-28|language=en}}</ref> By 28 March, over 700 external examiners had also recorded their resignations in a UCU document.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/university-strikes-pensions-dispute-lecturers-students-ucu-college-union-uuk-a8278486.html|title=New university strike dates announced|date=2018-03-28|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-03-28|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nAs of 28 March 2018, more than a million students were estimated to have been affected,<ref name=\":13\" /> with 126,000 students signing petitions calling for fee refunds.<ref name=\":101\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43295334|title=University talks resume after Twitter row|last=Burns|first=Judith|date=6 March 2018|work=BBC News|language=en-GB|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312192658/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43295334|archivedate=12 March 2018|url-status=live|access-date=12 March 2018}}</ref> Students also occupied campus buildings in support of striking staff at more than a dozen universities.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43295334|title=University strike talks resume after Twitter skirmishes|last=Burns|first=Judith|date=6 March 2018|work=BBC News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305225924/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43295334|archivedate=5 March 2018|url-status=live|access-date=6 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">Thomas Hale, '[https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2018/02/22/2198956/the-strange-economics-of-the-university-strikes/ The strange economics of the university strikes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309054440/https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2018/02/22/2198956/the-strange-economics-of-the-university-strikes/|date=9 March 2018}}', ''Financial Times'' (22 February 2018).</ref>\n\nFrom 25 November to 4 December 2019, and on fourteen days between 20 February and 13 March 2020, UCU undertook further strikes, partly in a continuation of the pensions dispute which triggered the strikes in 2018, and partly in a parallel dispute over pay equality, workload, casualisation, and pay levels. In this second dispute, universities were represented by the [[Universities and Colleges Employers Association]] (UCEA).<ref name=\"Bethan Staton 2019\"/>\n\nDuring the period covered by this article, strikes also took place on local disputes at individual universities, covered in the table of all strike action below.\n\n==Background to the strikes==\n[[File:Non-staff costs as a proportion of universities' total expenditure UK average 2006-15, according to Higher Education Statistics Agency.svg|thumb|Non-staff costs as a proportion of universities' total expenditure: UK average 2006\u201315, rising from around 42% to around 45%, according to the [[Higher Education Statistics Agency]].]]\n[[File:UK university pay and student income, inflation-adjusted to 2017 prices, 2006-16.svg|thumb|UK university pay and student income, 2006\u201316, inflation-adjusted to 2017 prices. Over the period, total spending per student rises by around \u00a32000; vice-chancellors' remuneration rises by \u00a321873; professors' pay falls by \u00a37544; and average pay across all academic staff falls by \u00a34304.]]\nThe United Kingdom has 130 universities.<ref name=\":5\" /> Staff at 68 universities founded before 1992 are members of the USS pension scheme.<ref name=\":5\" /> (Most academic staff at institutions which became universities ''after'' 1992 are members of the Teachers' Pension Scheme, which is unaffected by this dispute.)<ref name=\":5\" /> In January 2018, UCU members at 61 universities (initially) balloted in favour of action over the proposed pension changes.<ref name=\"auto8\" />\n\nAs reporting, both in the UK and abroad, noted, the strikes took place in the context of other tensions over higher education and pension provision in the UK, as follows.<ref name=\"auto2\">'[https://www.ft.com/content/4671a4c0-163d-11e8-9376-4a6390addb44 Striking dons add to UK students\u2019 resentments] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225072257/https://www.ft.com/content/4671a4c0-163d-11e8-9376-4a6390addb44 |date=25 February 2018 }}', ''The Financial Times'' (20 February 2018).</ref><ref>Richard Adams, '[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/feb/16/theresa-may-details-tuition-fee-overhaul Theresa May to reveal details of tuition fee overhaul on Monday] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227001156/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/feb/16/theresa-may-details-tuition-fee-overhaul |date=27 February 2018 }}', ''The Guardian'' (16 February 2018).</ref><ref>Sebastian Borger, '[www.fr.de/wissen/grossbritannien-professoren-wollen-universitaeten-lahmlegen-a-1452510 Professoren wollen Universit\u00e4ten lahmlegen]', ''Frankfurther Rundschau'', 74.44 (21 February 2018), p. 23.</ref><ref>Daniel Zylbersztajn, '[http://www.taz.de/Professoren-Streik-in-Grossbritannien/!5484269/ Stillstand an den Unis] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222211945/http://taz.de/Professoren-Streik-in-Grossbritannien/!5484269/ |date=22 February 2018 }}', ''Taz'' (22 February 2018).</ref><ref>Steven Parfitt, '[https://jacobinmag.com/2018/02/britain-university-strike-pensions Lecturers on Strike] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312173520/https://www.jacobinmag.com/2018/02/britain-university-strike-pensions |date=12 March 2018 }}', ''Jacobin'' (21 February 2018).</ref>\n\n===National UK higher education policy===\n\n* Debates about [[Tuition fees in the United Kingdom|tuition fee]] levels and the mechanisms for paying them. In particular, on 19 February 2018, the UK Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] had announced an official review of UK higher education funding.<ref>Sean Coughlan, '[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43106736 Theresa May's university review will not scrap fees] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226002838/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43106736 |date=26 February 2018 }}', BBC News (19 February 2018).</ref>\n* The increasingly corporate and privatised character of higher education institutions. For example, universities, whose capital expenditure had traditionally been funded to a significant extent by government funding, were increasingly borrowing from private capital markets, making them concerned about their credit ratings, and with uncertain consequences for their finances and governance.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>Thomas Hale, '[https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2018/03/06/2199103/universities-and-the-allure-of-capital-markets/ Universities and the allure of capital markets] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307090725/https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2018/03/06/2199103/universities-and-the-allure-of-capital-markets/ |date=7 March 2018 }}', ''Financial Times'' (6 March 2018).</ref><ref>Rosemary Bennett, Nicola Woolcock and Ryan Watts, 'University debt: credit crunch looms as debt spirals', <nowiki>''</nowiki>The Times<nowiki>''</nowiki> (3 January 2019), <nowiki>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/university-debt-credit-crunch-looms-as-debt-spirals</nowiki>.</ref>\n* The creation of the [[Office for Students]] on 1 January 2018, whose powers came into force 1 April 2018. For example, on 28 February 2018, the OFS said that \"universities that fail to mitigate the impact of the strikes would open themselves up to regulatory intervention\".<ref>Harry Yorke, 'Universities told they face fines if strikes harm students', ''The Daily Telegraph'' (27 February 2018), 2.</ref>\n\n===Pensions===\n====The USS pension scheme====\n\nThe USS scheme was created in 1974 to provide sector-wide pensions for UK university staff (focusing on academic staff).<ref name=\"Logan1985\">Douglas Logan, ''The Birth of a Pension Scheme. A History of the Universities Superannuation Scheme'' (Liverpool University Press 1985).</ref> Its terms changed little until 2011, when major reforms were implemented, followed by further changes in 2014\u201315.<ref name=\"Platanakis2015\">Emmanouil Platanakis and Charles Sutcliffe, 'Asset\u2013Liability Modelling and Pension Schemes: The Application of Robust Optimization to USS', ''The European Journal of Finance'' (2015), 1-29, [[Digital object identifier|doi]]:[https://doi.org/10.1080%2F1351847X.2015.1071714 10.1080/1351847X.2015.1071714].</ref><ref name=\"Platanakis2018\">Emmanouil Platanakis and Charles Sutcliffe, 'Pension Schemes, Taxation and Stakeholder Wealth: The USS Rule Changes', ICMA Centre, Discussion Paper Number: ICM-2017-08 (23 January 2018): https://ssrn.com/abstract=3039364; {{DOI|10.2139/ssrn.3039364}}.</ref><ref name=\"TimesGrove2015\">Jack Grove, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/new-uss-pension-reform-plans-to-be-put-to-union-vote/2017987.article New USS Pension Reform Plans to be Put to Union Vote] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215143632/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/new-uss-pension-reform-plans-to-be-put-to-union-vote/2017987.article |date=15 February 2018 }}', ''Times Higher Education'' (15 January 2015).</ref> These changes left scheme members markedly worse off: one academic study concluded that the reduced wealth of post-2011 entrants was equivalent to an 11% drop in their total compensation or a 13% drop in their salaries.<ref name=\"Platanakis2016\">Emmanouil Platanakis and Charles Sutcliffe, 'Pension Scheme Redesign and Wealth Redistribution Between the Members and Sponsor: The USS Rule Change in October 2011', ''Insurance: Mathematics and Economics'', 69 (2016), 14\u201328. {{DOI|10.1016/j.insmatheco.2016.04.001}}</ref>{{rp|25}}\n\nBy 2017, the USS scheme had over 400,000 members.<ref name=\"Economist2017\">'[https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21725794-their-position-independent-institutions-funded-public-cash-awkward-one-universities Universities\u2019 main pension pot faces the biggest deficit of any British fund] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215204047/https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21725794-their-position-independent-institutions-funded-public-cash-awkward-one-universities |date=15 February 2018 }}', ''The Economist'' (3 August 2017).</ref>\n\n====Wider UK pensions====\n\n* The UK [[Pensions Act 2004]] had placed stringent requirements on private-sector pensions to ensure that their liabilities could be met even if all their member organisations collapsed at once\u2014which in the context of USS would entail the whole University system going bust, an event deemed unlikely by many. Over 2006\u201317, the proportion of UK private-sector defined-benefit schemes open to new joiners declined from 43% to 14%.<ref name=\"ucu.org.uk\">'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/media/9556/Backing-for-defined-benefit-pension-scheme-bucks-trend-Financial-Times---27-Sep-2018/pdf/Backing_for_defined_benefit_pension_scheme_bucks_trend___Financial_Times.pdf Backing for defined benefit pension scheme bucks trend]', ''The Financial Times'' (5 October 2018).</ref> In the analysis of [[Mervyn King, Baron King of Lothbury|Mervyn King]] and [[John Kay (economist)|John Kay]], 'The 2004 Pensions Act is a prime, but by no means unique, example of well-intentioned but inept financial regulation. Over-prescriptive, it has led to the demise of the defined benefit schemes that it was designed to protect. If proposed changes to the USS are implemented, there will be no defined benefit schemes of any significant size outside the public sector open to new members'.<ref name=\"timeshighereducation.com\">Mervyn King and John Kay, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/features/uss-crisis-can-pension-system-be-reformed USS crisis: can the pension system be reformed?]', ''Times Higher Education'' (6 September 2018), https://www.johnkay.com/2018/09/06/uss-crisis-can-the-pension-system-be-reformed/.</ref>\n* Similar or even more dramatic proposed pension cuts for universities' non-academic staff.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pensions-expert.com/DB-Derisking/Southampton-uni-s-DB-closure-proposal-poorly-timed-experts-say?ct=true |title=Southampton uni's DB closure proposal poorly timed, experts say |last=Imeson |first=Sophia |date=16 January 2018 |work=Pensions Expert|access-date=18 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319085008/http://www.pensions-expert.com/DB-Derisking/Southampton-uni-s-DB-closure-proposal-poorly-timed-experts-say?ct=true|archive-date=19 March 2018|url-status=live }}</ref> For example, in January 2018, [[University of Southampton|Southampton University]] began consultations on closing its defined-benefits pension scheme for non-academic staff,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.professionalpensions.com/professional-pensions/news/3024438/southampton-uni-support-staff-face-two-thirds-pension-cut |title=Southampton Uni support staff 'face two-thirds pension cut' |last=Phillips |first=James |date=15 January 2018 |work=Professional Pensions|access-date=18 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115162756/https://www.professionalpensions.com/professional-pensions/news/3024438/southampton-uni-support-staff-face-two-thirds-pension-cut|archive-date=15 January 2018|url-status=live }}</ref> and in March 2018, [[Staffordshire University]] began consultations on moving support staff from the defined-benefit local government scheme to a local defined-contribution scheme.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/stoke-on-trent-news/hundreds-university-staff-braced-pension-1329336 |title=Hundreds of university staff braced for pension changes |last=McInnes |first=Kathie |date=12 March 2018 |work=The Sentinel|access-date=18 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319213536/https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/stoke-on-trent-news/hundreds-university-staff-braced-pension-1329336|archive-date=19 March 2018|url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Worsening outlooks for pension provision across the UK, in the context of rising remuneration for fund managers and increasing integration of pension funds into speculative financial markets.<ref>E.g. Christine Berry, '[https://www.opendemocracy.net/neweconomics/uss-tip-iceberg-pensions-system-hot-mess/ USS is the tip of the iceberg. Our pensions system is a hot mess] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316071735/https://www.opendemocracy.net/neweconomics/uss-tip-iceberg-pensions-system-hot-mess/ |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''OpenDemocracy'' (1 March 2018).</ref> For example, it was noted that pay for USS's chief executive rose from \u00a3484,000 in 2017 to \u00a3566,000 in 2018, while two staff members earned over \u00a31m, and running costs stood at \u00a3125m per annum.<ref>Sean Coughlan, '[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43157711 University pension boss's \u00a382,000 pay rise]', ''BBC News'' (22 February 2018).</ref>\n\n===Pay and conditions===\n\n* Public concern about rapidly rising pay for University senior management, particularly [[Vice-chancellor]]s.<ref name=\"auto3\">Phoebe Braithwaite, '[https://www.wired.co.uk/article/university-pensions-ucu-uss-academics-strike The university pensions strike is a last resort for STEM academics] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307043115/http://www.wired.co.uk/article/university-pensions-ucu-uss-academics-strike |date=7 March 2018 }}', ''Wired'' (23 February 2018).</ref><ref>Sally Weale, \"[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/mar/01/universities-government-scrutiny-policy-exchange Universities brace for government scrutiny after Policy Exchange report]\", ''The Guardian'' (1 Mar 2020).</ref> In particular, on 26 February 2018, the Channel 4 investigative journalism programme ''Dispatches'' broadcast an expos\u00e9 of vice-chancellors' expenses claims.<ref>Jamie Doward, '[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/feb/24/vice-chancellors-expenses-scandal-channel-4-dispatches-universities Revealed: British university vice-chancellors\u2019 five-star expenses] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226114015/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/feb/24/vice-chancellors-expenses-scandal-channel-4-dispatches-universities |date=26 February 2018 }}', ''The Guardian'' (24 February 2018).</ref>\n* Concern among university staff about falling real-terms pay for most staff.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> Moreover, the pay projections assumed in USS's 2017 valuation and used to argue for reducing pensions assumed an increase in general pay growth: rather than assuming pay would keep up with inflation (as measured by the [[consumer price index]]), USS assumed pay growth one percent above inflation (as measured, more generously, by the [[retail price index]]).<ref>D. Spiegelhalter and others, '[https://www.ft.com/content/810aa034-9c79-11e7-8cd4-932067fbf946 Examining the Numbers on Pension Valuation]', ''The Financial Times'' (19 September 2017); available at https://www.dannydorling.org/?p=6109 and http://www.dannydorling.org/wp-content/files/dannydorling_publication_id6103.pdf.</ref> On 16 April 2018, staff were actually offered a payrise of 1.7%, below both CPI inflation (then 2.7%) and RPI (then 3.6%).<ref>Jack Grove, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/uk-university-staff-offered-17-cent-pay-rise-2018-19 UK university staff offered 1.7 per cent pay rise for 2018-19]', ''Times Higher Education'' (16 April 2016).</ref>\n* Growing numbers of academic staff were on [[Precarity|precarious]] short-term or zero-hours contracts \u2013 in 2018\u201319, 34% of academic staff were employed on short-term contracts and 13% were paid by the hour.<ref name=\":24\">\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-51533712 Students hit by 14-day university lecturers strike]\", ''BBC News'' (20 February 2020).</ref><ref>\"[https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/23-01-2020/sb256-higher-education-staff-statistics Higher Education Staff Statistics: UK, 2018/19]\", Statistical Bulletin SB256 (23 January 2020).</ref> In March, UCU argued on the basis of data from a [[Freedom of information in the United Kingdom|freedom of information]] request that an average of 27% UK university teaching hours were delivered by such staff.<ref>Sophie Inge, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/uk-universities-rely-casual-staff-half-teaching UK universities rely on casual staff \u2018for up to half of teaching\u2019] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321192832/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/uk-universities-rely-casual-staff-half-teaching |date=21 March 2018 }}', ''Times Higher Education'' (6 March 2016).</ref> The issue of casualisation became increasingly prominent in UCU members' understanding of the strikes as they developed.<ref name=\"auto4\">Sophie Inge, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/genie-out-bottle-casualisation-after-pension-strikes \u2018Genie out of the bottle\u2019 on casualisation after pension strikes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321192830/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/genie-out-bottle-casualisation-after-pension-strikes |date=21 March 2018 }}', ''Times Higher Education'' (21 March 2018).</ref>\n* Similar concerns were reflected by strike action around the same time more widely in UK professional classes: junior doctors undertook [[Junior doctors contract dispute in England, 2015|their first strikes]] in the history of the [[National Health Service (England)]] in 2015\u201316, while barristers began strike action on 1 April 2018.<ref>'[https://economist.com/news/britain/21741202-barristers-lecturers-and-doctors-are-among-those-feeling-pinch-british-professionals-revolt British professionals revolt as austerity hits the middle class]', ''The Economist'' (26 April 2018).</ref>\n\n==2018 USS pension negotiations, and associated strike action==\n\n===Prior to industrial action===\n\nIn July 2017, USS reported a technical deficit (i.e. a gap between the fund's assets and its liabilities) of \u00a317.5&nbsp;billion, reported as the largest [[UK pensions#Underfunding|such shortfall]] in the UK at that time.<ref name=\"Economist2017\" /> USS's deficit evaluation was based on suggestions that although the fund's [[assets]] had grown (reaching \u00a360&nbsp;billion, a one-fifth increase on the previous year), its [[Liability (financial accounting)|liabilities]] had also grown (reaching \u00a378&nbsp;billion, a one-third increase over the previous year).<ref name=\"FT2017\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ft.com/content/914d9cba-7232-11e7-aca6-c6bd07df1a3c |title=University pension fund deficit soars to \u00a317.5bn |last=Gordon |first=Sarah |date=28 July 2017 |website=[[Financial Times]] |accessdate=29 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729214315/https://www.ft.com/content/914d9cba-7232-11e7-aca6-c6bd07df1a3c |archivedate=29 July 2017 }}</ref> Following negotiations regarding the calculation of the deficit, the USS Joint Negotiating Committee accepted a technical deficit of \u00a36.1&nbsp;billion in November 2017.\n\nThe key change proposed by UUK was to close USS's [[Defined benefit pension plan|defined benefit scheme]] (possibly temporarily), replacing it with a [[Defined contribution plan|defined contribution scheme]].<ref name=\"auto5\">Ben Chu, '[https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/university-lecturers-strike-economics-pensions-a8227421.html If you look at the economics, it's completely reasonable for university lecturers to strike over pension changes]', ''The Independent'' (25 February 2018).</ref>\n\nSpecifically, the USS Joint Negotiating Committee therefore made the following proposals, to be introduced after 1 April 2019:<ref>'[https://web.archive.org/web/20180203011521/https://www.uss.co.uk/how-uss-is-run/valuation/2017-valuation-updates/proposed-changes-to-future-uss-benefits Proposed changes to future USS benefits]'.</ref>\n\n* Closing of the defined benefits section of the scheme (though mentioning the possibility of reintroducing it), with all future benefits (apart from death in service and ill health retirement benefits) being transferred to the defined contribution scheme.\n* Contributions would remain 8% for members and 18% for employers (of which 13.25% contributes directly to pensions, the rest being used for management and running costs, etc.).\n* Members would be enabled to pay only 4% while still receiving the usual employer contribution, while the option of paying an extra 1%, matched by the employer, would be removed.\n* Members' 8% (or 4%) would include a contribution to partly finance death in service and ill health retirement benefits.\n\nThe closure of defined benefits was presented as a red line by UCU, which argued in favour of finding ways to sustain defined benefits, or to introduce a [[collective defined contribution scheme]]<ref name=\"auto5\" /><ref>Christine Berry, '[https://www.opendemocracy.net/neweconomics/uss-tip-iceberg-pensions-system-hot-mess/ USS is the tip of the iceberg. Our pensions system is a hot mess] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316071735/https://www.opendemocracy.net/neweconomics/uss-tip-iceberg-pensions-system-hot-mess/ |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''OpenDemocracy'' (1 March 2018).</ref><ref name=\":300\">{{cite web |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-social-media-has-collapsed-case-pension-cuts |title=USS strike: social media has collapsed the case for pension cuts |date=12 March 2018 |work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=12 March 2018 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312125218/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-social-media-has-collapsed-case-pension-cuts |archivedate=12 March 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> (the primary legislation for which was introduced in the UK in 2015, but which had not as of March 2018 been advanced to secondary legislation).<ref>'[https://www.pensions-expert.com/DB-Derisking/UUK-and-UCU-strike-pensions-deal UUK and UCU strike pensions deal]', ''Pensions Expert'' (12 March 2018).</ref>\n\n====Arguments for the changes====\nUSS argued that market conditions had simply proven less favourable than previous valuations had assumed, with the chief executive, Bill Galvin, arguing that 'the unavoidable fact is that market conditions have changed since 2014. Real interest rates have fallen since 2014, relative to inflation, and asset prices have soared ... We are now having to pay more \u2013 to get less in return \u2013 than we expected in the past'. Moreover, USS emphasised that its room for manoeuvre was constrained by [[the Pensions Regulator]].<ref>Bill Galvin, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-we-cant-ignore-reality-our-deficit-says-pensions-boss USS strike: we can\u2019t ignore reality of our deficit, says pensions boss] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322143304/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-we-cant-ignore-reality-our-deficit-says-pensions-boss |date=22 March 2018 }}', ''Times Higher Education'' (19 March 2018).</ref>\n\nIn theory, the deficit could have been resolved through higher contribution rates. However, UUK argued that defined benefit schemes were becoming prohibitively expensive.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/mar/12/striking-lecturer-slow-death-public-education |title=Why I'm a striking lecturer: I want to stop the slow death of public education {{!}} Becky Gardiner|last=Gardiner|first=Becky|date=12 March 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=12 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312110529/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/mar/12/striking-lecturer-slow-death-public-education|archivedate=12 March 2018}}</ref> They said they had a legal duty to put in place a credible plan to reduce the deficit by the summer of 2018. Otherwise, pension contributions from employers and staff would have to sharply increase, potentially resulting in redundancies and cuts to other areas of teaching, research and student support.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"auto6\">Alistair Jarvis, '[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/universities-uk-chief-alistair-jarvis-unions-pension-demands-will-cost-1bn-a-year-fb8v05jhs Universities UK chief Alistair Jarvis: union\u2019s pension demands will cost \u00a31bn a year]', ''The Sunday Times'' (18 March 2018), accessed from {{cite web|url=http://www.universitiesuk.ac.uk/blog/Pages/uss-pensions-update.aspx|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320052813/http://www.universitiesuk.ac.uk/blog/Pages/uss-pensions-update.aspx|archivedate=20 March 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=21 March 2018}}.</ref> UUK stated the defined contributions proposal would compare well with private-sector competitors, with employer contributions double the private sector average.<ref name=\":500\" />\n\nUSS had a legal responsibility to satisfy the UK pensions regulator that the scheme was sound, and the regulator was requiring change.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\n====Arguments against the changes====\nUCU stated that UUK's proposal would \"leave a typical lecturer almost \u00a310,000 a year worse off in retirement than under the current set-up\",<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/mar/05/university-pension-strike-listening |title=The university pension strike will only end when we're listened to {{!}} Sally Hunt|last=Hunt|first=Sally|date=5 March 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=12 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180311132107/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/mar/05/university-pension-strike-listening|archivedate=11 March 2018}}</ref> with younger staff the worst affected, with some losing up to half their anticipated pensions.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nCritics of the changes offered the following main arguments against implementing the changes to the scheme promoted by UUK.\n\n* UUK's assessment of the health of the higher education sector after a 2015/16 report by [[Higher Education Funding Council for England|the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE)]] found the sector was financially sound.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hefce.ac.uk/analysis/HEinEngland/finhealth/ |title=Financial health overview - Higher Education Funding Council for England |last=England |first=Higher Education Funding Council for |website=www.hefce.ac.uk |language=en|access-date=12 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312105935/http://www.hefce.ac.uk/analysis/HEinEngland/finhealth/ |archivedate=12 March 2018 }}</ref> Independent analyses undertaken by [[University of Warwick]] economist Dennis Leech and [[University College London|UCL]] academic Sean Wallis argued that UUK used a \"flawed valuation model\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n* The proposed USS changes were shaped by the demand of the UK pensions regulator that USS should be made less risky to employers than USS's actuaries had wished. It was argued, however, that in view of the exceptional economic circumstances associated with the Bank of England's [[quantitative easing]] from 2009, the regulator was placing unrealistic expectations on UK pensions nationally.<ref name=\":17\">David Bailey and John Clancy, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-regulator-blame-pensions-crisis USS strike: regulator is to blame for pensions crisis]', ''Times Higher Education'' (13 March 2013).</ref><ref name=\"timeshighereducation.com\" />\n* Concern also grew, on the basis of research by [[Michael Otsuka]] from the [[London School of Economics]], that UUK's negotiating position was disproportionately influenced by the views of Oxford and Cambridge Universities, whose constituent colleges made separate submissions to consultations.<ref name=\"auto7\">Richard Adams, '[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/feb/21/universities-strike-blamed-on-vote-by-oxbridge-colleges Universities strike blamed on vote by Oxbridge colleges] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227001146/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/feb/21/universities-strike-blamed-on-vote-by-oxbridge-colleges |date=27 February 2018 }}', ''The Guardian'' (21 February 2018).</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/oxbridge-universities-higher-education-strike-pensions-cuts-more-say-ucu-a8223011.html |title=Oxbridge universities 'given greater say than other institutions' on pensions cuts driving higher education strike |last=Baynes |first=Chris |date=22 February 2018 |work=The Independent|access-date=18 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304081549/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/oxbridge-universities-higher-education-strike-pensions-cuts-more-say-ucu-a8223011.html|archive-date=4 March 2018|url-status=}}</ref><ref name=\":300\" />\n* Current employees were annually paying \u00a32.1bn into the USS fund, while it was annually paying out \u00a31.8bn to pensioners. To cover the current annual cost of pensions from investment returns, the fund required a net annual return of 3%.<ref>Anthony Hesketh, '[https://www.theguardian.com/higher-education-network/2018/feb/22/the-solution-to-university-pensions-better-fund-managers The solution to university pensions? Better fund managers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227003931/https://www.theguardian.com/higher-education-network/2018/feb/22/the-solution-to-university-pensions-better-fund-managers |date=27 February 2018 }}', ''The Guardian'', 22 February 2018.</ref> One of the assumptions used in the July 2017 valuation was that the fund would stop accepting contributions \u2014 the sort of situation that would normally arise if the companies in a pension scheme went bust, which was an unlikely real-world situation for the UK higher education sector.<ref name=\"LeechBlog\">{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.warwick.ac.uk/dennisleech/entry/is_the_uss_1_2/ |title=Is the USS really in crisis?, 23/11/17, Dennis Leech's blog |website=blogs.warwick.ac.uk|access-date=6 February 2018}}</ref> USS's analyses showed that, assuming the most likely circumstances rather than the most challenging circumstances (technically referred to as the \"best estimate\"), the pension scheme was sustainable in the long-term. In contrast to technical deficits based on stringently conservative assumptions, this more probable valuation showed the fund in credit by \u00a38.3&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"LeechBlog\" />\n* At the inception of USS, employer contributions were 16% of salary, rising to 18.55% in 1983. However, from January 1997 to September 2009 they were decreased to 14% (before rising to 16% from October 2009 to 2016 and 18% thereafter). It was suggested that staff were bearing the consequences of an earlier lack of investment by employers.<ref name=\"Logan1985\" /><ref name=\"Cooper2014\">Susan Cooper, '[https://users.physics.ox.ac.uk/~scooper/USS/2014-11%20Pensions.pdf A Pensions Proposal: Constant Contributions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228041225/https://users.physics.ox.ac.uk/~scooper/USS/2014-11%20Pensions.pdf |date=28 February 2018 }}' (p. 1).</ref>\n\n===UCU ballots for industrial action (29 January 2018)===\nOn 29 January, UCU announced that 88% of UCU members had voted to back strike action and 93% backed action short of a strike.<ref name=\"auto8\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9242/UCU-announces-14-strike-dates-at-61-universities-in-pensions-row |title=UCU announces 14 strike dates at 61 universities in pensions row |website=www.ucu.org.uk |language=en-gb|access-date=6 February 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180202232646/https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9242/UCU-announces-14-strike-dates-at-61-universities-in-pensions-row |archivedate=2 February 2018 }}</ref> The turnout was 58%,<ref name=\":0\" /> meeting the 50% minimum set by the [[Trade Union Act 2016]].\n\nShortly after, on 13 February, the trade union [[UNISON]], many of whose members in the Higher Education sector were also USS members, began a consultative ballot on striking alongside UCU.<ref>'[https://www.unison.org.uk/news/article/2018/02/uss-letter/ HE members to be consulted over proposed pension changes]' (13 February 2019).</ref> On 20 February, UNISON wrote to vice-chancellors in support of UCU's position.<ref>'[https://www.unison.org.uk/news/article/2018/02/uss-letter/ UNISON writes to vice chancellors over university pensions dispute]' (20 February 2018).</ref>\n\n===Strike action commences (23 February 2018) and new negotiations follow===\n[[File:International Women's Day and Leeds UCU signs, 2018.jpg|thumb|International Women's Day and Leeds UCU signs, 2018]]\nStrikes commenced on 23 February, whereupon UUK agreed to meet UCU for further negotiations on 27 February. Leaked emails suggested they would not negotiate on UCU's key issue, retaining defined benefits.<ref>Camilla Turner, '[{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/2018/02/24/lecturers-poised-escalate-disruption-leaked-letter-reveals-university/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=16 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226205324/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/2018/02/24/lecturers-poised-escalate-disruption-leaked-letter-reveals-university/ |archivedate=26 February 2018 }} Lecturers' strike: universities refusing to bow on pension reforms, leaked letter reveals', ''The Sunday Telegraph'' (24 February 2018).</ref> The meeting led to an agreement to undergo conciliation through [[Acas]], the UK's national industrial dispute conciliation body. UCU tabled and published a set of proposals which it argued was consistent with the majority of UUK members' positions in USS's earlier consultation, but strikes were not called off.<ref>Richard Adams and Emily Hawkins, '[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/feb/27/university-staff-pension-dispute-moves-to-acas University staff pension dispute moves to Acas] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316183540/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/feb/27/university-staff-pension-dispute-moves-to-acas |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''The Guardian'' (27 February 2018).</ref><ref>Camilla Turner, '[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/2018/02/27/lecturers-university-leaders-enlist-conciliation-service-acas/ Lecturers and university leaders enlist conciliation service Acas but strikes are set to continue] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304115142/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/2018/02/27/lecturers-university-leaders-enlist-conciliation-service-acas/ |date=4 March 2018 }}', ''The Telegraph'' (27 February 2018).</ref><ref>'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9364/Further-talks-agreed-in-universities-pensions-dispute Further talks agreed in universities pensions dispute] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228201401/https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9364/Further-talks-agreed-in-universities-pensions-dispute |date=28 February 2018 }}' (27 February 2018).</ref>\n\nA spokesperson for Universities UK said: \"Both sides are currently engaged in serious and constructive talks at [[Acas]]. We are committed to seeking a viable, affordable and mutually acceptable solution to the current challenges facing USS pensions.\"<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43337090|title=Fresh strikes could hit university exams|date=8 March 2018|work=BBC News|language=en-GB|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180311202906/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43337090|archivedate=11 March 2018|url-status=live|access-date=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===UCU's proposal (27 February 2018)===\n\nUCU tabled an alternative proposal at the first round of talks with UUK which UCU stated would involve universities accepting some increased risk and small increased contributions from employers and scheme members.<ref name=\":1\" /> UUK's response was that they would need time to cost the union's proposal which it feared would require \"very substantial increases in contributions\". However, some vice-chancellors voiced support for UCU's plan.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nUCU's proposal, along with suggestions for longer-term strategies, was:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9364/Further-talks-agreed-in-universities-pensions-dispute |title='Further talks agreed in universities pensions dispute' (27 February 2018) |access-date=28 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228201401/https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9364/Further-talks-agreed-in-universities-pensions-dispute |archive-date=28 February 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Universities should accept a slightly riskier but probably more lucrative investment strategy, leading to a deficit of \u00a35.1 billion rather than \u00a36.1 billion, a level accepted by the majority of institutions when it was proposed by USS in September 2017.\n* Retaining defined benefits on salaries up to \u00a355,550.\n* Reducing the annual accrual rate from 1/75 to 1/80.\n* Increasing contributions by 2.7% for employers and 1.4% for members (i.e. 4.1% split 65/35 between employers and employees).\n\nThe parties held inconclusive talks on 5 March, scheduling the next talks for 7 March.<ref name=\":4\" /> However, a bizarre Twitter spasm from UUK on the night of 5 March insisted that the group was available for talks on 6 March, and this led to talks at noon on 6 March.<ref>Judith Burns, '[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43295334 University strike talks resume after Twitter skirmishes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312192658/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43295334 |date=12 March 2018 }}', ''BBC News'' (6 March 2018).</ref> Talks continued on 7 March, inconclusively. On 8 March, UCU's Higher Education Committee agreed that it would call further strikes if necessary after the Easter vacation, between April and June.<ref>Robert Wright, '[https://www.ft.com/content/57a6f7b6-22fb-11e8-ae48-60d3531b7d11 UK universities could be hit by new strikes amid pension dispute] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309054353/https://www.ft.com/content/57a6f7b6-22fb-11e8-ae48-60d3531b7d11 |date=9 March 2018 }}', ''Financial Times'' (8 March 2018).</ref>\n\n===Joint UUK and UCU proposal (12 March 2018)===\n[[File:Placard from March 13 2018 UCU protest, Leeds.jpg|thumb|Placard from 13 March 2018 UCU protest, Leeds.]]\nOn the evening of Monday 12 March UCU and UUK issued a joint agreement, arrived at through ACAS, to be put to their respective members.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43380857 |title=Deal offered in university pensions row |last=Coughlan |first=Sean |date=13 March 2018 |work=BBC News|access-date=13 March 2018 |language=en-GB |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313001707/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43380857 |archivedate=13 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe agreement was specifically for a three-year \"transitional benefit arrangement\" lasting from 1 April 2019, maintaining defined benefits up to a salary threshold of \u00a342,000, reducing the accrual rate to 1/85, but raising contributions to 19.3% of salaries for employers and 8.7% for members. The next valuation was to be informed by an \"independent expert group\", 'aiming to promote greater transparency and understanding' of the methodologies, assumptions, and viability of the scheme. Indexation and revaluation was to be measured using CPI and capped at up to 2.5% p.a. (meaning that if inflation, measured by CPI, rose above 2.5%, the pension would lose value in real terms). UCU was to suspend industrial action and \"encourage\" branches to reschedule any classes disrupted by the strike. The agreement stated that \"there is commitment between both sides to engage in meaningful discussions as soon as possible to explore risk sharing alternatives for the future from 2020, in particular Collective Defined Contributions\".<ref>University and College Union and Universities UK, '[https://www.ucu.org.uk/media/9300/Agreement-reached-between-UCU-and-UUK-under-the-auspices-of-ACAS/pdf/UCU_UUK_agreement_at_ACAS_12_March_Final.pdf Agreement reached between UCU and UUK under the auspices of ACAS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312190956/https://www.ucu.org.uk/media/9300/Agreement-reached-between-UCU-and-UUK-under-the-auspices-of-ACAS/pdf/UCU_UUK_agreement_at_ACAS_12_March_Final.pdf |date=12 March 2018 }}' (12 March 2018).</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/mar/13/striking-university-staff-irate-over-pensions-deal-ucu |title=University strikes to continue after staff reject pension offer |last=Weale |first=Sally |date=13 March 2018 |website=the Guardian |language=en|access-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313190115/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/mar/13/striking-university-staff-irate-over-pensions-deal-ucu |archivedate=13 March 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\":7\" />\n\nVice-chancellors were to inform UUK whether they would back this deal by the end of day on Wednesday 14 March while UCU representatives consulted with their members on whether to reject the deal or not the next day.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n===Acas agreement withdrawn by UCU (13 March 2018)===\n[[File:Picket at University of Edinburgh.jpg|alt=UCU meeting at University of Edinburgh|thumb|293x293px|UCU meeting at the [[University of Edinburgh]]]]\nLocal branch meetings were held on Tuesday 13 March to consider the ACAS agreement. These meetings informed a meeting of elected and branch representatives the same day. This agreement was rejected by UCU's membership on the grounds that it failed to address members' concerns.<ref>'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9401/University-strikes-remain-on-as-UCU-rejects-proposals?list=1676 University strikes remain on as UCU rejects proposals] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313164953/https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9401/University-strikes-remain-on-as-UCU-rejects-proposals?list=1676 |date=13 March 2018 }}' (13 March 2018).</ref><ref>Sean Coughlan, '[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43388912 University strikers reject pension deal] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316130245/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43388912 |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''BBC News'' (13 March 2018).</ref><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9401/University-strikes-remain-on-as-UCU-rejects-proposals?list=1676 |title=University strikes remain on as UCU rejects proposals |website=www.ucu.org.uk |language=en-gb|access-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313164953/https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9401/University-strikes-remain-on-as-UCU-rejects-proposals?list=1676 |archivedate=13 March 2018 }}</ref> Many UCU members used the Twitter hashtag #NoCapitulation to express their disapproval of the agreement,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/mar/13/striking-university-staff-irate-over-pensions-deal-ucu |title=University strikes to continue after staff reject pension offer |last=Weale |first=Sally |date=13 March 2018 |work=The Guardian|access-date=18 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318013105/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/mar/13/striking-university-staff-irate-over-pensions-deal-ucu|archive-date=18 March 2018|url-status=}}</ref> helping to co-ordinate a strong response to the proposals.<ref name=\"auto9\">Nicole Kobie, '[https://www.wired.co.uk/article/no-capitulation-uk-university-pension-protest-twitter #NoCapitulation: How one hashtag saved the UK university strike] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321050532/http://www.wired.co.uk/article/no-capitulation-uk-university-pension-protest-twitter |date=21 March 2018 }}', ''Wired'' (18 March 2018).</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43388912|title=University strikers reject pension deal|last=Coughlan|first=Sean|date=13 March 2018|work=BBC News|language=en-GB|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313200220/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43388912|archivedate=13 March 2018|url-status=live|access-date=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nUCU general secretary [[Sally Hunt]] said that preparations for strikes during the exam period would be made, while urgently seeking further talks.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>See further '[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9404/How-we-got-to-yesterday-and-whats-next How we got to yesterday and what's next]' (14 March 2018).</ref>\n\nA UUK spokesperson said: <blockquote>It is hugely disappointing that students' education will be further disrupted through continued strike action. We have engaged extensively with UCU negotiators to find a mutually acceptable way forward.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.universitiesuk.ac.uk/news/Pages/UCU-rejects-proposals-jointly-agreed-at-ACAS.aspx |title=UCU rejects proposals jointly agreed at ACAS |website=www.universitiesuk.ac.uk |language=en-GB |access-date=14 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315133330/http://www.universitiesuk.ac.uk/news/Pages/UCU-rejects-proposals-jointly-agreed-at-ACAS.aspx |archivedate=15 March 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref></blockquote>\nIn some places, the decision was followed the next day by rallies.<ref name=\"auto10\">Kristian Johnson, '[https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/news/leeds-news/five-things-learned-latest-ucu-14410973 Five things we learned from the latest UCU rally through Leeds city centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318060411/https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/news/leeds-news/five-things-learned-latest-ucu-14410973 |date=18 March 2018 }}', ''LeedsLive'' (14 March 2018).</ref>\n\n===Developments 14\u201323 March 2018===\n\nAs of 14 March, UUK's consultation with its members remained ongoing.<ref>'[http://www.universitiesuk.ac.uk/news/Pages/planning-more-talks-with-UCU.aspx Universities UK planning more talks with UCU to end pensions dispute] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316023228/http://www.universitiesuk.ac.uk/news/Pages/planning-more-talks-with-UCU.aspx |date=16 March 2018 }}' (14 March 2018).</ref>\n\nA statutory 64-day consultation by USS on pension changes had been due to commence on 19 March, but as of 15 March, USS were declaring an unspecified delay to the commencement of consultations.<ref>'[https://www.ussconsultation2018.co.uk/members/info Employer consultation in relation to proposed changes to Universities Superannuation Scheme] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316151911/https://www.ussconsultation2018.co.uk/members/info |date=16 March 2018 }}' (accessed 15 March 2018).</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, UCU called on members employed as external examiners to resign until the dispute was resolved.<ref>Chris Havergal, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/call-external-examiners-quit-uk-pensions-dispute Call for external examiners to quit in UK pensions dispute] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316214248/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/call-external-examiners-quit-uk-pensions-dispute |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''Times Higher Education'' (16 March 2018).</ref> By 23 March over 600 resignations had occurred.<ref name=\"auto12\">Sophie Inge, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/hundreds-external-examiners-resign-uk-pensions-dispute Hundreds of external examiners resign in UK pensions dispute]', ''Times Higher Education'' (23 March 2018).</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, UUK announced that it would convene an \"independent panel\", featuring an independent chair and involving academics and pension professionals, to \"consider issues of methodology, assumptions and monitoring, aiming to promote greater transparency and understanding of the USS valuation\". The panel would invite UCU \"to play a full role in providing evidence to the panel\" and would also liaise with USS and the pensions regulator.<ref>'[https://www.universitiesuk.ac.uk/news/Pages/Panel-of-independent-experts-to-review-processes-for-arriving-at-pension-deficit.aspx Panel of independent experts to review processes for arriving at pension deficit]' (18 March 2018).</ref><ref name=\"auto6\" /> UCU's response was that \"UCU will of course look at any proposals UUK makes but our members have made it quite clear that what is needed is a much improved offer\".<ref>'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9412/UCU-responds-to-UUK-valuation-review UCU responds to UUK valuation review]' (18 March 2018).</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, UCU sanctioned fourteen further strike days to fall in the April to June 2018 exam period should the talks fail to come to a resolution.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nOn 23 March, UNISON announced that its consultative ballot of its USS members had returned 91% support for industrial action, and that it would begin a formal ballot for strike action in April.<ref>'[https://www.unison.org.uk/news/2018/03/he-pension/ University members asked to strike to defend USS pension scheme]' (23 March 2018).</ref><ref>Talya Misiri, '[https://www.pensionsage.com/pa/Enough-is-enough-Unison-urges-USS-members-to-join-industrial-action.php \u2018Enough is enough\u2019 Unison urges USS members to join industrial action]', ''PensionsAge'' (23 March 2018).</ref><ref>'[https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/unison-strike-ballot-over-university-pensions Unison strike ballot over university pensions]', ''Morning Star'' (24 March 2018).</ref>\n\n===UUK makes a new offer (23 March 2018)===\n\nOn 23 March, UCU announced a new offer from UUK. This proposed the creation of a formal \"Joint Expert Panel\" to reconsider how valuations should be undertaken, leaving open the possibility of maintaining the status quo not only for the statutory period up to April 2019, but possibly beyond. The panel would\n<blockquote>take into account the unique nature of the HE sector, inter-generational fairness and equality considerations, the need to strike a fair balance between ensuring stability and risk. Recognising that staff highly value Defined Benefit provision, the work of the group will reflect the clear wish of staff to have a guaranteed pension comparable with current provision whilst meeting the affordability challenges for all parties, within the current regulatory framework.<ref>'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9422/New-offer-sent-to-UCU-members-in-USS-pensions-dispute?list=1676 New offer sent to UCU members in USS pensions dispute]' (23 March 2018).</ref></blockquote>\nThe ''Financial Times'' noted that this would be \"a far more comprehensive review of the current structure and valuation of the Universities Superannuation Scheme\" than previously considered, but also noted that \"the new agreement avoids any mention of increases in contributions by either employers or employees to plug the hole in the scheme\".<ref name=\"ft.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/5d991390-2ebb-11e8-a34a-7e7563b0b0f4|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times}}</ref> UCU was due to consult members' representatives at a formal meeting on 28 March.<ref name=\"ft.com\" /><ref>Max Jenner, '[https://oxfordstudent.com/2018/03/23/uuk-tables-new-proposal-for-ucu/ NewsUUK tables new proposal for UCU]', ''Oxford Student'' (23 March 2018).</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, on 26 March, the UK's Joint Negotiating Committee for Higher Education Staff began its round of negotiations for pay in the sector for 2018/19, with unions demanding a large pay uplift.<ref name=\"HE_Pay_claim_submitted 2018\">'[http://www.ucu.org.uk/media/9311/UCUBANHE29/pdf/HE_Pay_claim_submitted.pdf University and College Union Higher Education Branch Action Note]', UCUBAN/HE29 (21 March 2018).</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Jack Grove, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/uk-university-staff-offered-17-cent-pay-rise-2018-19 UK university staff offered 1.7 per cent pay rise for 2018-19]', ''Times Higher Education'' (16 April  2018 ).</ref>\n\n===New strike dates announced as UCU members balloted on proposal (28 March 2018)===\nUCU announced that members would be electronically balloted on the new offer in April to decide on the proposal for the Joint Expert Panel.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/mar/28/uk-university-staff-to-vote-on-latest-pensions-offer|title=UK university staff to vote on latest pensions offer|last=Adams|first=Richard|date=2018-03-28|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> UUK pledged to maintain the current contributions and retirement benefits until at least April 2019 while the review by the panel of experts took place.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nAt the same time, UCU gave formal notice of a five-day strike action, aimed at disrupting the exams and assessments period, at some universities for 16 April to 20 April 2018, potentially to be called off  if there was progress in the negotiations.<ref name=\":15\" /> 13 universities including Manchester, Cardiff, Oxford, St Andrews, Leeds and Southampton would be affected by this next round of strikes with the prospect of industrial action at the other 52 universities to take place later in April and continuing into July if no agreement was reached.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":14\" /> However, staff would not take part in additional strike action if UCU members vote to accept the UUK proposal.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nAs of 28 March, nearly 700 external examiners had recorded their resignations in a UCU document.<ref name=\":14\" /> ''The Guardian'' reported that \"students at the end of their courses could find themselves unable to graduate if crucial exams cannot be invigilated, marked or assessed\" as a worst-case scenario.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nDebate followed among UCU members as to whether to accept the proposals or not.<ref>Steven Parfitt, '[https://www.jacobinmag.com/2018/03/universities-uk-strike-contract-vote-education Deal or No Deal?]', ''Jacobin'' (3 March 2018).</ref> As of 4 April, some branches had decided to recommend that their members reject the proposals as they stood,<ref>Richard Adams, '[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/apr/04/university-staff-vote-on-pensions-offer-without-a-deal-in-sight University staff vote on pensions offer \u2013 without a deal in sight]', ''The Guardian'' (4 April 2018).</ref><ref>Sophie Inge, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/under-pressure-ucu-leader-urges-members-accept-pensions-deal Under-pressure UCU leader urges members to accept pensions deal]', ''Times Higher Education'' (4 April 2018).</ref> and prominent discontent with the proposals continued to be registered in the run-up to the ballot closing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/union-unrest-opens-new-front-uk-university-pensions-dispute|title=Union unrest opens new front in UK university pensions dispute|date=2018-04-09|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2018-04-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== UCU accepts UUK proposal (13 April 2018) and Joint Expert Panel is formed ===\n\nThe result of the ballot was the UCU members accepted UUK proposal. Industrial action was suspended and the impending strikes of 16 April were called off.<ref>'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9438/Members-vote-to-accept-employers-latest-offer Members vote to accept employers' latest offer]' (13 April 2018).</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.universitiesuk.ac.uk/news/Pages/ballot-result-on-joint-expert-panel.aspx|title=Ballot result on Joint Expert Panel|website=www.universitiesuk.ac.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-04-17}}</ref><ref>Chris Havergal, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/strikes-suspended-union-members-vote-end-pensions-dispute Strikes suspended as union members vote to end pensions dispute]', ''Times Higher Education'' (13 April 2018).</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n|Total balloted\n|53,415\n|-\n|Total votes cast\n|33,973\n|-\n|Total number valid votes\n|33,913\n|-\n|Turnout\n|63.5%\n|-\n|Yes to accept the UUK offer\n|21,683 (64%)\n|-\n|No to reject the UUK offer\n|12,230 (36%)\n|}\nOn 18 April, UCU confirmed that it was ending its call for external examiners to stand down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9441/Latest-developments|title=Latest developments|website=www.ucu.org.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> Commentary suggested that scrutiny of the pension negotiations by the union membership was nonetheless ongoing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/apr/16/university-pensions-strikes-union-campaign|title=Universities ending the strikes is not a climbdown \u2013 the fight goes on {{!}} Des Freedman|last=Freedman|first=Des|date=2018-04-16|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May, UUK and UCU announced that the Joint Expert Panel would be chaired by Joanne Segars.<ref>'[https://www.universitiesuk.ac.uk/news/Pages/UCU-and-UUK-announce-appointment-of-Chair-for-USS-Joint-Expert-Panel.aspx UCU and UUK announce appointment of Chair for USS Joint Expert Panel]', 18 May 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9490/UCU-and-UUK-announce-appointment-of-Chair-for-USS-Joint-Expert-Panel UCU and UUK announce appointment of Chair for USS Joint Expert Panel]' (18 May 2018).</ref> On 21 May UCU announced three nominations to the panel.<ref>'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9493/UCU-announces-nominations-to-USS-joint-expert-panel= UCU announces nominations to USS joint expert pane]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}' (221 May 201).</ref> Other members were later determined as Ronnie Bowie, Sally Bridgeland, and Chris Curry (appointed by UUK) and Catherine Donnelly, Saul Jacka, and Deborah Mabbett (appointed by UCU).<ref>The Joint Expert Panel on the Universities Superannuation Scheme commissioned by the University and College Union and Universities UK, '[https://web.archive.org/web/20180913161622/http://www.ussjep.org.uk/files/2018/09/report-of-the-joint-expert-panel.pdf Report of the Joint Expert Panel]' (September 2018), pp. 70-71.</ref> The Joint Expert Panel was scheduled to report in September.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/uss-announces-increases-higher-education-pension-contributions|title=USS announces increases in higher education pension contributions|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 1\u20133 June, a tumultuous UCU congress included calls for the general secretary, Sally Hunt, to resign over what was perceived to be undemocratic practice within the Union's prosecution of the dispute. Much of the congress's proceedings had to be aborted, and a new congress was proposed for the future.<ref>Chris Havergal, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/sally-hunt-clings-ucu-leader-congress-curtailed Sally Hunt clings on as UCU leader as congress curtailed]', ''Times Higher Education'' (1 June 2018).</ref> (On 18 October a recalled congress saw the withdrawal of motions to call for resignation, but a motion of censure was passed complaining at a lack of transparency and accountability in Hunt's representation of UCU members during the dispute.<ref>Jack Grove, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/ucus-sally-hunt-censured-over-handling-pensions-strike UCU\u2019s Sally Hunt censured over handling of pensions strike]', ''Times Higher Education'' (18 October 2018).</ref>)\n\n=== USS plans contribution increases (25 July 2018) ===\nWhile the Joint Expert Panel deliberated, USS announced that, given that the legal deadline for addressing the fund's deficit had passed, it would, in accordance with statutory procedure, act already to raise both staff and employer contributions, following a statutory consultation period, to maintain the scheme's benefits. The proposed rises (as a percentage of salary) were to be phased in over a year:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!\n!Staff contributions\n!Employer contributions\n|-\n|status quo\n|8%\n|18%\n|-\n|April 2019\n|8.8%\n|19.5%\n|-\n|October 2019\n|10.4%\n|22.5%\n|-\n|April 2020\n|11.7%\n|24.9%\n|}\nThese plans were announced against a backdrop of USS's annual report calculations of the deficit falling, due to changing assumptions about factors such as returns on corporate bonds and mortality. On different measures, the 2018 annual report showed a 2014 deficit of 12.6bn falling to a 2018 deficit of 12.1bn; or a \u00a317.5bn deficit falling to \u00a38.4 billion deficit.<ref name=\":16\" /> Though this plan was criticised by UCU and UUK, as of 22 November 2018, USS continued to plan to implement it.<ref name=\"Concluding the 2017 valuation\">'[https://www.uss.co.uk/how-uss-is-run/valuation/2017-valuation-updates/concluding-the-2017-valuation Concluding the 2017 valuation]' (22 November 2018).</ref><ref name=\"Jack Grove 2018\">Jack Grove, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/uss-revisit-ps75-billion-deficit-valuation USS to revisit \u00a37.5 billion deficit valuation]', ''Times Higher Education'' (22 November 2018).</ref>\n\n=== Joint Expert Panel releases first report (13 September 2018) ===\nOn 13 September, the Joint Expert Panel that had been convened to re-examine the valuation of the USS scheme issued its first report.<ref>The Joint Expert Panel on the Universities Superannuation Scheme commissioned by the University and College Union and Universities UK, '[https://web.archive.org/web/20180913161622/http://www.ussjep.org.uk/files/2018/09/report-of-the-joint-expert-panel.pdf Report of the Joint Expert Panel]' (September 2018).</ref><ref name=\"ucu.org.uk\" /> The Panel's press release recommended a number of adjustments to the methodology and data used in the 2017 valuation of the USS scheme, and stated that \"it is the Panel\u2019s belief, based on independent actuarial analysis, that the full implementation of these adjustments could mean total required contributions estimated at 29.2% to fund current benefits [...] This compares to the current rate of 26% (18% of salary paid by employers, 8% by employees) and the rate of 36.6% from April 2020 which is proposed by USS, based on the valuation as it stands\".<ref>'[https://web.archive.org/web/20180913141628/http://www.ussjep.org.uk/report-of-the-joint-expert-panel/ USS Joint Expert Panel]' (13 September 2018).</ref> It was suggested that this proposal might entail raising employees' contributions to 9.1% of salary, and employers' by 2.1%, taking their contribution to 20.1%.<ref>Jack Grove, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/pay-extra-1-salary-save-uss-pension-benefits-says-panel Pay extra 1% of salary to save USS pension benefits, says panel]', ''Times Higher Education'' (13 September 2018).</ref>\n\nOn 15 October Sam Marsh, of the University of Sheffield, reported in detail on his own analysis of data obtained from USS after a long period of requesting the information. He found that the methodologies by which USS's 'test 1' measures the pension scheme's viability were flawed, and that by maintaining previous investment strategies, USS would have the surplus it would require to meet its future liabilities. UUK asked the USS trustee to investigate Marsh's arguments.<ref>Josephine Cumbo, '[https://www.ft.com/content/3778c62c-d142-11e8-a9f2-7574db66bcd5 University pension fund accused of exaggerating shortfall]', ''The Financial Times'' (16 October 2018).</ref><ref>Sam Marsh, '[https://medium.com/ussbriefs/a-flawed-valuation-the-laypersons-guide-to-my-findings-on-uss-s-test-1-b9e0c53f5d67 A flawed valuation: the layperson\u2019s guide to my findings on USS\u2019s \u2018Test 1\u2019]' (15 October 2018).</ref><ref>Felicity Callard, [[Jo Grady]], Nick Hardy,  Jaya John John, Nicky Priaulx, and Ruth Stirton, '[https://medium.com/ussbriefs/there-must-be-something-missing-here-sam-marsh-exposes-new-problems-in-the-uss-valuation-351c90b1ab30 Sam Marsh exposes new problems in the USS valuation', ''USSbriefs'', 59 (16 October 2018).]</ref> Marsh's commentary had also attracted prominent support from [[Michael Otsuka]].<ref>Michael Otsuka, '[https://web.archive.org/web/20181018204618/https://medium.com/@mikeotsuka/usss-valuation-rests-on-a-large-and-demonstrable-mistake-691103c94ca6 USS\u2019s valuation rests on a large and demonstrable mistake]' (13 October 2018).</ref> USS defended its position the next day, accepting that Marsh's reanalysis was 'not wrong in isolation', but arguing that de-risking was necessary anyway.<ref>'[https://web.archive.org/web/20181019200234/https://www.uss.co.uk/how-uss-is-run/valuation/2017-valuation-updates/claims-of-a-large-and-demonstable-error Claims of a \u2018large and demonstrable error\u2019 in the valuation]', (16 October 2018).</ref><ref>Jack Grove, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/universities-superannuation-scheme-rejects-valuation-error-claim Universities Superannuation Scheme rejects valuation error claim]', ''Times Higher Education'' (17 October 2018).</ref> In response, UCU commissioned an independent report by [[First Actuarial]] which on 16 November 2018 supported Marsh's arguments and levelled a number of criticisms at USS's valuations and reasoning.<ref>Hilary Salt and Derek Benstead, '[https://www.ucu.org.uk/media/9971/First-Actuarial-three-questions-on-the-valuation/pdf/firstactuarial-3questions_nov18.pdf Report for University and College Union: Three Questions on the USS 2017 valuation]' (16 November 2018).</ref>\n\nOn 8 November, UUK reported on a consultation of its members, which found them, like UCU, to support the Joint Expert Panel's recommendations.<ref>'[https://www.ussemployers.org.uk/news/update-employers-views-jep-recommendations Update: employers' views on JEP recommendations]' (8 November 2018).</ref> The news was welcomed by UCU.<ref>'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9766/UCU-welcomes-universities-acceptance-of-expert-pensions-reports-findings?list=1676 UCU welcomes universities' acceptance of expert pensions report's findings]' (14 November 2018).</ref> This suggested that a consensus position between these parties had been more or less achieved, meaning that the main faultline in the dispute now ran between USS on the one side, and UCU and UUK on the other.<ref>Jack Grove, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/universities-back-panels-plans-uss-pension-contributions Universities back panel\u2019s plans for USS pension contributions]', ''Times Higher Education'' (14 November 2018).</ref>\n\n=== USS declares 2017 valuation complete but agrees to a new 2018 valuation (22 November 2018) ===\n\nOn 22 November, USS declared that 'as member and employer representatives on the Joint Negotiating Committee could not agree on an alternative outcome to the 2017 valuation', it would maintain the defined benefits scheme but implement contribution increases using the Scheme's default rules for cost-sharing between members and employers, as published on 25 July (starting with a small increase in contributions in April 2019). The 2017 valuation was eventually signed off on 29 January 2019.<ref>'[https://web.archive.org/web/20190409132135/https://www.uss.co.uk/~/media/document-libraries/uss/how-uss-is-run/av-archive/actuarialreportasatmarch2017.pdf Scheme Funding Report of the Actuarial Valuation: Universities Superannuation Scheme, as at 31 March 2017]' (Birmingham: Mercer, 2019).</ref>\n\nHowever, USS agreed to undertake a new valuation of the fund as it stood at 31 March 2018, which the Joint Expert Panel had suggested would indicate a far smaller deficit. It was thought that this new valuation might forestall further requirements for contribution increases after April 2019.<ref name=\"Concluding the 2017 valuation\" /><ref name=\"Jack Grove 2018\" />\n\n=== Consultation on 2018 USS valuation closes (28 February 2019) ===\n\nOn 2 January 2019, USS began a consultation with UUK on its 2018 valuation, which closed 28 February. USS proposed that it should be possible to increase overall contributions from 26% of salary (the contribution level that obtained from April 2016 to April 2019) to 29.7% of salary, rather than the higher increases planned in response to the 2017 valuation\u2014but only if scheme members agreed to a system of 'trigger contributions' (additional contributions that would be triggered if short-term measures of deficit exceeded a certain level).<ref>Universities Superannuation Scheme, '[https://web.archive.org/web/20190409133429/https://www.ussemployers.org.uk/sites/default/files/field/attachemnt/2018-technical-provisions-consultation.pdf 2018 Actuarial Valuation: A consultation with Universities UK on the proposed assumptions for the scheme\u2019s Technical Provisions and Statement of Funding Principles]' (2 January 2019).</ref> UUK members, however, expressed scepticism at the necessity and appropriateness of this arrangement.<ref>Stephanie Hawthorne, '[http://www.pensions-expert.com/DB-Derisking/Employers-reject-call-for-contingency-contributions-from-USS?ct=true Employers reject call for contingency contributions from USS]', ''Pensions Expert'' (March 15, 2019).</ref> In response, on 9 May 2019, USS proposed three options 'for finalising the 2018 valuation', retaining the scheme's previous benefits, and requiring lower contributions than the arrangement that the scheme had defaulted to in the absence of an agreement, but requiring much higher contributions than the proposals put forward by the JEP:<ref>'[https://www.uss.co.uk/how-uss-is-run/2018-valuation/2018-valuation-updates/9-may-2019 2018 Valuation update: 9 May 2019]' (9 May 2019).</ref>\n\n# A fixed total contribution rate of 33.7% of salary.\n# A standard total contribution rate of 29.7% but with 'sufficiently strong contingent contribution arrangements' enabling higher contributions in certain circumstances.\n# A fixed total contribution rate of 30.7%, 'subject to a 2020 valuation'.\n\nMeanwhile, on 15 March the Council of [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] voted to withdraw the college unilaterally from USS as of 31 May 2019, in a move that came to be called [[Trexit]]. By October 2019, the college had replaced the USS scheme with a defined benefits scheme to avoid the college bearing any responsibility for other pensions in the UK higher education system in the event of foreclosures in the sector. The move sparked protests, resignations, and a boycott.<ref>Noella Chye, '[https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/16687 Revealed: Trinity plans exit from national pension scheme, isolating college from higher education sector]', ''Varsity'' (8 December 2018).</ref><ref>Rosie Bradbury, '[https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/17600 Trinity confirms exit from national pensions scheme \u2013 over 230 academic staff will now boycott supervising Trinity students]', ''Varsity'' (24 May 2019).</ref><ref>Chris Havergal, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/cambridges-trinity-confirms-departure-uss-pension-scheme Cambridge\u2019s Trinity confirms departure from USS pension scheme]', ''Times Higher Education'' (24 May 2019).</ref><ref>Natalie Tuck, '[https://www.pensionsage.com/pa/UCU-threatens-boycott-of-Trinity-College-over-USS-exit.php UCU threatens boycott of Trinity College over USS exit]', ''PensionsAge'' (21 June 2019).</ref><ref>Camilla Turner, \"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/02/cambridge-college-faces-resignations-decision-switch-pension/amp/ Cambridge college faces resignations over decision to switch pension plans for staff]\", ''The Telegraph'' (3 October 2019), p. 11.</ref><ref>Ellie Arden and Dylan Perera, '[https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/17938 Trexit conflicts continue as Trinity welcomes new master]', ''Varsity'' (8 October 2019).</ref>\n\nOn 21 May 2019, it was revealed that [[Jane Hutton]], in her capacity as a non-executive director on the USS board of trustees, had in March 2018 complained to the Pensions Regulator, alleging that her efforts in 2017 to check whether the USS deficit had been miscalculated had been frustrated by delays and obstructions to providing her with data to which she needed access to fulfil her [[fiduciary duties]]. As of May 2019, the Pensions Regulator and Financial Reporting Council were investigating the allegations.<ref>Josephine Cumbo, '[https://www.ft.com/content/96cf2da6-7ad8-11e9-81d2-f785092ab560 Regulators probe claims about university pension plan]', ''Financial Times'' (21 May 2019).</ref> On 14 June 2019, as the investigation continued, the Regulator rebuked USS for claiming that aspects of USS policy were mandated by the Regulator when in fact they were not.<ref>Josephine Cumbo, '[https://www.ft.com/content/3b6a2f18-8e94-11e9-a1c1-51bf8f989972 Regulator rebukes UK university pension scheme]', ''Financial Times'' (14 June 2019).</ref> On 11 October 2019, it was reported that Hutton had been dismissed as a director of USS on the grounds that, according to an independent investigation, \"she had breached a number of her director\u2019s duties owed under company law and contract\". USS said that the dismissal was independent of Hutton's whistleblowing and the ongoing investigation; Hutton said she did not view the decision as valid and was considering further action.<ref>Anna McKie, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/whistleblowing-professor-jane-hutton-fired-uss-board Whistleblowing professor Jane Hutton fired from USS board]', ''Times Higher Education'' (11 October 2019).</ref><ref>Jack Gray, '[https://pensionsage.com/pa/USS-whistleblower-fired.php USS whistleblower fired]', ''PensionsAge:'' (11 October 2019).</ref>\n\nOn 22 August 2019, the Joint Negotiating Committee, representing UCU and UUK, met to determine the position that they would put to the USS trustees. The independent chair, [[Andrew Cubie]], used his deciding vote to support UUK's preferred plan. In this scheme, total contributions per member would be 30.7% of salary, with 9.6% being paid by the employee and 21.1% by the employer. A further valuation would follow in 2020 and in the absence of an alternative agreement, the contribution rate would rise to 34.7% in October 2021 with members paying 11% and employers 23.7%. UCU argued that employees' contributions should not rise above 8%, and that the Joint Expert Panel had suggested alternative paths to achieving this that had been agreeable to both UCU and UUK. UUK offered to limit staff contributions to 9.1% instead of 9.6% if UCU would agree to hold no strikes on pensions for two years, an offer which UCU rejected.<ref>Richard Adams, '[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2019/aug/25/uk-universities-brace-for-strike-action-in-pensions-dispute UK universities brace for strike action in pensions dispute]', ''The Guardian'' (25 August 2019).</ref><ref>'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10260/Autumn-pension-strikes-more-likely-as-universities-impose-higher-costs Autumn pension strikes more likely as universities impose higher costs]' (22 August 2019).</ref><ref>'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10263/Employers-strike-ban-rejected-by-UCU-in-pensions-dispute Employers' strike ban rejected by UCU in pensions dispute]' (23 August 2019).</ref> The 21.1%:9.6% contribution rates were ratified on 12 September by the USS trustee board.\n\n==Responses to the 2018 pension strikes==\n[[File:UCU Higher Education Strike rally.jpg|alt=UCU Higher Education Strike rally, George Square, Glasgow.|thumb|Crowds gather at a UCU strike rally in George Square, Glasgow.]]\n\n=== Changes in UK law ===\nThe strike brought to the attention of unions and the UK government a potential ambiguity in UK legislation: migrant workers on [[Visa policy of the United Kingdom|Tier 2 and 5 visas]] have an annual 20-day limit on unpaid absence from work.<ref name=\":25\">Tyler Denmead, 'Tier Two Worker Remote Office: Resisting the Marketization of Higher Education', ''Journal of Curriculum and Pedagogy'', 16:1 (2019), 6-34, {{DOI|10.1080/15505170.2018.1500325}}.</ref>{{rp|13\u201315}} As some universities had seen local strike action during 2017\u201318 in addition to the 14 days of national strike action, fears arose that staff members who were on strike for more than 20 days in a year might have their visas revoked, and that this might in turn impinge on their legal rights to take industrial action.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/opinion/curtailing-overseas-scholars-right-strike-undermines-their-academic-citizenship|title=Curtailing overseas scholars\u2019 right to strike undermines their academic citizenship|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref> On 12 July, the [[Home Secretary|home secretary]] [[Sajid Javid]] declared that it was \"not the government\u2019s policy to prevent migrant workers from engaging in legal strike action\" and that he would introduce changes to the rules and guidelines on immigration to be explicit that strike action did not count as \"unpaid absence\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/javid-foreign-staff-can-strike-without-risking-right-remain|title=Javid: foreign staff can strike without risking right to remain|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2018-07-12/HCWS848|title=Immigration:Written statement - HCWS848|last=Javid|first=Sajid|date=12 July 2018|website=parliament.uk|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Staff===\n[[File:Dinosaur of Solidarity Lino Print.jpg|thumb|Dinosaur of Solidarity lino print, alluding to the presence of a dinosaur on Southampton UCU's picket lines.]]\nIn the ballot for the strike, UCU achieved an unusually high turnout and strong support for industrial action, and membership grew by about 15,000 between the beginning of 2018 and 12 April.<ref name=\"auto13\">Jack Grove, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/features/uss-strike-and-the-winter-of-academics-discontent The USS strike and the winter of academics\u2019 discontent]', ''Times Higher Education'' (12 April 2018).</ref>\n\nStaff organised \"teach-outs\" off campus at \"every university with a substantial picket line\";<ref name=\"auto11\">Sanjana Varghese, '[https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/education/2018/03/why-students-are-coming-out-support-their-striking-lecturers Why students are coming out in support of their striking lecturers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312083841/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/education/2018/03/why-students-are-coming-out-support-their-striking-lecturers |date=12 March 2018 }}', ''The New Statesman'' (8 March 2018).</ref> these featured education sessions which tended to be left-wing or critical of recent changes in UK higher education,<ref name=\":500\">John Marenbon, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-academics-are-wrong-walk-out USS strike: academics are wrong to walk out] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307151221/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-academics-are-wrong-walk-out |date=7 March 2018 }}', ''Times Higher Education'' (2 March 2018).</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/14886 |title=Academics to hold alternative teach-outs during strike action |last=Lally |first=Catherine |date=21 February 2018 |work=Varsity|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308042141/https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/14886 |archivedate=8 March 2018 }}</ref><ref>'[https://www.thebangoraye.com/bangor-university-staff-to-teach-out-during-strike/ Bangor University staff to \u2018Teach-Out\u2019 during strike] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308041633/https://www.thebangoraye.com/bangor-university-staff-to-teach-out-during-strike/ |date=8 March 2018 }}', ''The Bangor Aye'' (20 February 2018).</ref><ref>Jana Bacevic, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-picket-line-debates-will-re-energise-scholarship USS strike: picket line debates will re-energise scholarship]', ''Times Higher Education'' (13 March 2018).</ref> apparently led by the University of Leeds, whose UCU branch had tested the model during a local dispute in autumn 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.leedsucu.org.uk/organising-a-teach-out/ |title=Organising a teach-out |date=15 December 2017 |website=University of Leeds UCU|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308042724/http://www.leedsucu.org.uk/organising-a-teach-out/ |archivedate=8 March 2018 }}</ref><ref>Lesley McCorrigan, 'Fourteen Days, Hold Tight: Reflections from Leeds on the USS Strike', ''Another Education is Possible'', 10 (Spring 2018), 12-13.</ref> Some pickets also featured staff singing rewrites of popular songs, among them Leeds University UCU's ''Strike Up Your Life'' (based on the [[Spice Girls]]' hit ''[[Spice Up Your Life]]'')<ref name=\"auto10\"/> or dance routines, prominently including Cambridge University UCU's performance to [[Public Enemy (band)|Public Enemy's]] ''[[Fight the Power (Public Enemy song)|Fight the Power]]''.<ref>'[https://scroll.in/video/871677/watch-cambridge-university-teachers-show-off-funky-dance-moves-in-protest-against-pension-cuts Watch: Cambridge University teachers show off funky dance moves in protest against pension cuts]', ''Scroll.in'' (13 March 2018).</ref><ref>Ellie Mullett, '[https://www.varsity.co.uk/violet/15128 Striking Cambridge dons dance for their pensions in flash mob video] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318054756/https://www.varsity.co.uk/violet/15128 |date=18 March 2018 }}', ''Violet by Varsity'' (11 March 2018).</ref> Geographers at the [[University of Nottingham]] produced a 'strike zine'.<ref>'[https://eprints.nottingham.ac.uk/51556/ Demanding the Impossible: A Strike Zine]' (2018).</ref> A Cambridge researcher working in the UK under a visa made an art installation reflecting their precarious situation.<ref name=\":25\" /> Meanwhile, Southampton University UCU's 'Dinosaur of Solidarity', a person in a dinosaur costume, became a minor social-media sensation.<ref>Arun Aggarwal, '[https://southampton.web.ucu.org.uk/2018/03/12/interview-with-a-dinosaur/ Interview with a Dinosaur]{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}' (12 March 2018).</ref>\n\nAs the strikes commenced, academics at Oxford and Cambridge began using those universities' democratic structures to change the universities' position on pension reform.<ref name=\"auto7\" /><ref name=\":3\">Richard Adams, '[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/mar/02/uk-universities-threaten-punish-striking-staff-cancelled-lectures Universities threaten to punish striking staff over cancelled lectures] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316183535/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/mar/02/uk-universities-threaten-punish-striking-staff-cancelled-lectures |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''The Guardian'' (2 March 2018).</ref> Oxford staff's attempts to use the university's supreme governing body, [[Congregation (university)|Congregation]], to effect a change of policy failed due to procedural problems on 5 March, but the next day Oxford's vice-chancellor [[Louise Richardson]] declared that the University would nonetheless heed the wishes of staff to \"reverse its response to the UUK survey\".<ref>Richard Adams, '[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/mar/07/oxford-university-backs-down-in-pensions-dispute Oxford University backs down in pensions dispute] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316183526/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/mar/07/oxford-university-backs-down-in-pensions-dispute |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''The Guardian'' (7 March 2018).</ref>\n\nAs the strikes developed, university staff increasingly called into question the governance structures of UUK, individual universities, and USS, along with the marketisation of the UK higher education sector and its increasingly precarious workforce.<ref>Christopher Phelps, '[https://www.dissentmagazine.org/online_articles/uk-lecturers-strike-university-pensions-austerity-student-solidarity Britain: Universities on Strike] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319151314/https://www.dissentmagazine.org/online_articles/uk-lecturers-strike-university-pensions-austerity-student-solidarity |date=19 March 2018 }}', ''Dissent'' (15 March 2018).</ref><ref name=\"auto4\" /><ref>Richard Watermeyer, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-academics-and-football-fans-are-fed-dehumanising-conditions USS strike: academics (and football fans) are fed up with \u2018dehumanising\u2019 conditions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321193041/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-academics-and-football-fans-are-fed-dehumanising-conditions |date=21 March 2018 }}', ''Times Higher Education'' (20 March 2018).</ref><ref>Celine Tan, '[http://slsablog.co.uk/blog/blog-posts/uss-strikes-defending-the-collective-public-goods-mandate-of-the-uk-universities/ USS Strikes: Defending the Collective Public Goods Mandate of the UK Universities]', ''SLSA Blog'' (16 March 2018).</ref> By 13 April, over 12,000 people had signed a petition calling for UUK to be made subject to the [[Freedom of Information Act 2000]].<ref name=\"auto13\" />\n\nStaff also made extensive use of social media (see below).\n\n===Universities===\n[[File:Email the VC.jpg|thumb|Chalk graffiti reading \"email the VC\", at the Downing Street entrance to the Sedgwick Site, Cambridge University, during the spring 2020 strikes.]]\nUniversities were represented in the dispute by UUK.\n\nHowever, some vice-chancellors expressed support for UCU's position before the strike. [[Anthony Forster (academic)|Anthony Forster]], vice-chancellor at the [[University of Essex]], described a staff consultation process that led Essex to support retaining defined benefits via increased pension contributions.<ref>Anthony Forster, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/universities-must-pay-more-protect-pensions Universities must pay more to protect pensions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310201015/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/universities-must-pay-more-protect-pensions |date=10 March 2018 }}', ''Times Higher Education'' (19 February 2018).</ref> The [[University of Warwick]]'s [[Stuart Croft (academic)|Stuart Croft]] publicly stated that \"I am sure that I am not alone in being mystified at this [proposed] change\",<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.warwick.ac.uk/execteam/entry/which_way_forward/ |title=Which way forward for USS?, 28/11/17, VC blog |website=blogs.warwick.ac.uk|access-date=6 February 2018}}</ref> and argued, in line with the position of the Liberal Democrats, that the UK government should underwrite USS pensions.<ref>Stuart Croft, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-it-time-nationalise-university-pensions USS strike: is it time to nationalise university pensions?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316041053/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-it-time-nationalise-university-pensions |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''Times Higher Education'' (26 February 2018).</ref>\n\nAfter the strike began, other vice chancellors voiced concern about UUK's position, and by the second day of strike action, 18 were being reported as calling for renewed negotiations, or as supporting UCU's position.<ref>Todd Gillespie and Catherine Lally, '[https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/14919 Stephen Toope joins calls for renewed talks to end strikes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225181649/https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/14919 |date=25 February 2018 }}', ''Varsity'' (23 February 2018).</ref> Some joined staff on picket lines, among them [[Anton Muscatelli]] (Glasgow), [[Keith Burnett]] (Sheffield) and [[Robert Allison (academic)|Robert Allison]] (Loughborough).<ref>Sophie Inge, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/pensions-strike-poisons-relations-uk-campuses Pensions strike \u2018poisons relations\u2019 on UK campuses] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312204748/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/pensions-strike-poisons-relations-uk-campuses |date=12 March 2018 }}', ''Times Higher Education'' (8 March 2018).</ref> In a letter to ''The Times'' of 16 March, the vice-chancellor of Cambridge University, [[Stephen Toope]], expressed sympathy with the concerns of staff and students about not only pensions, but also marketisation of UK universities,<ref>Stephen Toope, '[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/comment/british-retaliation-against-russia-s-actions-p5hmpj8jh The future of UK universities]', ''The Times'' (16 March 2018), accessed from {{cite web |url=https://www.cam.ac.uk/news/the-future-of-uk-universities-vice-chancellors-blog |title=Archived copy |accessdate=21 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319151339/https://www.cam.ac.uk/news/the-future-of-uk-universities-vice-chancellors-blog |archivedate=19 March 2018 }}.</ref><ref>Rosemary Bennett, '[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/turning-universities-into-businesses-caused-strikes-hzrxsv2q6 Turning universities into businesses \u2018caused strikes\u2019, says Cambridge vice-chancellor Stephen Toope]', ''The Times'' (16 March 2018).</ref><ref>Louis Ashworth, '[https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/15179 Toope attacks \u2018fundamental error\u2019 of university marketisation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319151252/https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/15179 |date=19 March 2018 }}', ''Varsity'' (16 March 2018).</ref> and held a wide-ranging public meeting with around 550 staff and students in [[Great St Mary's Church]], scheduling a further such meeting for 26 April.<ref>Noella Chye & Jack Conway, '[https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/15184 Hundreds of students gather to quiz Toope on pensions, divestment, and Prevent] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319151315/https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/15184 |date=19 March 2018 }}', ''Varsity'' (16 March 2018).</ref>\n\nSome universities decided to cushion the financial impact of strike action on their staff by deducting pay for the days not worked over several months. These included Glasgow,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://glasgowguardian.co.uk/2018/03/22/university-pension-row-14-days-of-strike-action-across-the-uk/|title=University pension row: 14 days of strike action across the UK \u2039 Glasgow Guardian|date=2018-03-22|website=Glasgow Guardian|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> Leicester,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uculeicester.org.uk/ucu/strike-day-pay-deductions-agreement/|title=Strike-day pay deductions agreement {{!}} University of Leicester UCU|website=www.uculeicester.org.uk|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> Cardiff,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cardiff.ac.uk/media/media-statements/action-short-of-a-strike|title=Cardiff University|website=Cardiff University|language=en|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> Cambridge,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/reporter/2017-18/weekly/6501/section11.shtml|title=Report of Discussion: Tuesday, 20\u00a0March 2018 - Cambridge University Reporter 6501|website=www.admin.cam.ac.uk|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/15547|title=Strike pay deducted in one go for hundreds of Cambridge staff|website=Varsity Online|language=en|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> and York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.york.ac.uk/admin/hr/news/2018/3/12/ucu-industrial-action/|title=Message from the VC and the President of the York branch of UCU - News - Human Resources at the University of York|website=www.york.ac.uk|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref>\n\nVideo recording of lectures had become widespread in UK universities by 2016,<ref>John Elmes, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/universities-uncertain-about-lecture-capture-copyright Universities \u2018uncertain\u2019 about lecture-capture copyright'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321130440/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/universities-uncertain-about-lecture-capture-copyright|date=21 March 2018}}, ''Times Higher Education'' (8 December 2016).</ref> and some universities sought to use lectures recorded in previous years to substitute for teaching missed during the strikes. This prompted renewed debates about what rights universities should claim in the intellectual output of their staff.<ref>Jack Grove, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/academics-must-sign-away-authorship-rights-recorded-lectures Academics \u2018must sign away authorship rights\u2019 to recorded lectures]', ''Times Higher Education'' (20 March 2018).</ref>\n\n==== Threatened pay deductions for not rescheduling teaching ====\nConversely, many universities demanded that staff reschedule teaching that had not been delivered during the strike, noting their right to deduct pay for [[partial performance]] if staff did not. However, a smaller number appeared to be committed to implementing deductions. Examples which attracted media attention included:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!University\n!Threatened deduction\n|-\n|[[University of St Andrews]]\n|100%<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/media/human-resources/new-policy-section-documents/strike/FAQ%202018%207%20Feb.pdf |title=Human Resources Strike Action & Action Short of a Strike FAQ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301212642/https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/media/human-resources/new-policy-section-documents/strike/FAQ%202018%207%20Feb.pdf |archivedate=1 March 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|[[University of Sheffield]]\n|25%<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sheffield.ac.uk/hr/thedeal/pensionupdates/uss-valuation-industrial-action/faqs |title=Frequently Asked Questions |access-date=1 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301080446/https://www.sheffield.ac.uk/hr/thedeal/pensionupdates/uss-valuation-industrial-action/faqs |archivedate=1 March 2018 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[University of Kent]]\n|50% per breach of contract<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kent.ac.uk/human-resources/pensions/uss-industrial-action2018/kents-pay-policy.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302232141/https://www.kent.ac.uk/human-resources/pensions/uss-industrial-action2018/kents-pay-policy.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 March 2018 |title=Kent's pay policy during this period of industrial action }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[University of Leeds]]\n|25%<ref>Sophie Inge, '[https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-times-higher-education/20180222/281711205130993 Tensions Mount on Campus as USS Pensions Strike Looms] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304231542/https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-times-higher-education/20180222/281711205130993 |date=4 March 2018 }}', ''Times Higher Education'' (22 February 2018).</ref><ref>Kristian Johnson, '[https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/news/leeds-news/staff-hit-out-university-leeds-14351183 Staff hit out at the University of Leeds for 'penalising striking members twice'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303225212/https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/news/leeds-news/staff-hit-out-university-leeds-14351183 |date=3 March 2018 }}', ''LeedsLive'' (28 February 2018).</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.leedsucu.org.uk/ucu-calls-on-university-senior-management-to-drop-asos-25-deduction-plan/ |title=UCU calls on university senior management to drop ASOS 25% deduction plan |access-date=2 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303050807/http://www.leedsucu.org.uk/ucu-calls-on-university-senior-management-to-drop-asos-25-deduction-plan/ |archivedate=3 March 2018 }}</ref><ref>'[https://www.pressreader.com/uk/yorkshire-post/20180302/282364040175672/textview Universities urged not to withhold staff pay]', ''Yorkshire Post'' (2 March 2018).</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://thetab.com/uk/leeds/2018/03/07/we-spoke-to-leeds-alumni-who-are-withdrawing-their-donations-following-the-strikes-42035 |title=We spoke to Leeds alumni who are withdrawing their donations following the strikes |last=Maclure |first=Abbey |date=7 March 2018 |work=The Tab|access-date=7 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308231631/https://thetab.com/uk/leeds/2018/03/07/we-spoke-to-leeds-alumni-who-are-withdrawing-their-donations-following-the-strikes-42035 |archivedate=8 March 2018 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Keele University]]\n|20%<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>Kathie McInnes, '[https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/local-news/union-boss-claims-university-punishing-1293687 Union boss claims university is 'punishing' striking academics by docking their pay twice over] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306202540/https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/local-news/union-boss-claims-university-punishing-1293687 |date=6 March 2018 }}', ''The Stoke Sentinel'' (3 March 2018).</ref>\n|}\nIn Sheffield's case, pay deduction of 25% for partial performance, rising to 100% after five days, was initially threatened,<ref>Lee Peace, '[https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/striking-university-of-sheffield-lecturers-in-fresh-row-over-pay-deductions-1-9043737 Striking University of Sheffield lecturers in fresh row over 'pay deductions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304081438/https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/striking-university-of-sheffield-lecturers-in-fresh-row-over-pay-deductions-1-9043737 |date=4 March 2018 }}', ''The Star'' (2 March 2018).</ref> provoking alumni to threaten to withdraw donations. The University then explained that it would not implement deductions for partial performance.<ref name=\":200\">Dominic Penna, '[https://thetab.com/uk/sheffield/2018/03/01/breaking-former-students-are-withdrawing-donations-to-the-university-of-sheffield-over-draconian-strike-policy-30297 BREAKING: Former students are withdrawing donations to the University of Sheffield over \u2018draconian\u2019 strike policy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304081547/https://thetab.com/uk/sheffield/2018/03/01/breaking-former-students-are-withdrawing-donations-to-the-university-of-sheffield-over-draconian-strike-policy-30297 |date=4 March 2018 }}', ''The Tab'' (1 March 2018).</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> Similar developments occurred at St Andrews, with the Principal, [[Sally Mapstone]], writing that \"having considered all matters in the round, I believe that our current policy to deduct pay at 100% for failure to reschedule classes cancelled due to strike action is inconsistent with this University's values and the store we place on our shared sense of community\".<ref name=\":100\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesaint-online.com/2018/03/lecturers-to-receive-pay-for-failing-to-reschedule-class-due-to-strikes/|title=Lecturers to receive pay for failing to reschedule class due to strikes|last=Smith|first=Annie|date=5 March 2018|work=The Saint|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305154226/http://www.thesaint-online.com/2018/03/lecturers-to-receive-pay-for-failing-to-reschedule-class-due-to-strikes/|archive-date=5 March 2018|url-status=|access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref> At Leeds, a number of external examiners resigned in protest at the university's plans, ongoing as of 10 March, to deduct pay for partial performance,<ref>Nathan Hyde, '[https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/news/leeds-news/examiners-resign-protest-after-university-14387728 Examiners resign in protest after University of Leeds threatens to dock striking lecturers' pay]', ''LeedsLive'' (10 March 2018); archived at: https://web.archive.org/web/20180318213931/https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/news/leeds-news/examiners-resign-protest-after-university-14387728.</ref><ref name=\"auto12\" /> while [[Alice Goodman]], widow of the university's noted professor [[Geoffrey Hill]], addressed an open letter to the university's vice chancellor asking the University to reconsider its stance.<ref>Sarah Colvin, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/opinion/uk-academics-have-snapped-and-not-just-over-pensions UK academics have snapped \u2013 and not just over pensions]', ''Times Higher Education'' (22 March 2018).</ref><ref>Alice Goodman, '[https://www.lrb.co.uk/blog/2018/03/10/alice-goodman/an-open-letter-to-the-vice-chancellor-of-leeds-university/ An Open Letter to the Vice Chancellor of Leeds University]', ''LRB Blog'' (10 March 2018).</ref>\n\n===Students===\n[[File:Leeds University students supporting the 2018 USS Pension Strikes.jpg|thumb|Leeds University students supporting the 2018 USS Pension Strikes on International Women's Day]]\n\n====Polls====\nA [[Yougov]] poll of 738 undergraduate students conducted for UCU between 13 and 20 February 2018 found that nationally, 61% of students said they supported the strikes, with 19% opposed and the remainder unsure. At striking institutions, support was 66%, with 18% opposed.<ref name=\":0\">Sally Weale and Alexandra Topping, '[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/feb/22/lecturers-begin-14-day-strike-over-pensions University lecturers begin strike action over pensions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227014405/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/feb/22/lecturers-begin-14-day-strike-over-pensions |date=27 February 2018 }}', ''The Guardian'' (22 February 2018); 'UCU Pension Strike', {{cite web |url=http://www.ucu.org.uk/media/9234/YouGov-USS-strike-action-poll/spreadsheet/UK12225972_Pension_strike_UCU.xlsx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=16 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228044350/http://www.ucu.org.uk/media/9234/YouGov-USS-strike-action-poll/spreadsheet/UK12225972_Pension_strike_UCU.xlsx |archivedate=28 February 2018 }}.</ref> In February 2018, a poll of 1,500 students for ''[[Times Higher Education]]'' magazine found over half (51.8%) would support their lecturer in a walk-out and just under a third (29.3%) would not.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/students-split-over-support-uss-pensions-strike-poll-reveals|title=Students split over support for USS pensions strike, poll reveals|date=15 February 2018|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|language=en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225075404/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/students-split-over-support-uss-pensions-strike-poll-reveals|archivedate=25 February 2018|url-status=live|access-date=12 March 2018}}</ref> Support for the national strike was evenly balanced, with 38.4% in favour and 38.4% against.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nBy 8 March, extensive student support for the strikes was still being reported, observing that students were joining with staff in solidarity against the marketisation of UK higher education.<ref name=\"auto11\"/>\n\n====Occupations and other activism====\nOn the first day of the strikes the UUK head office in London was occupied by students.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenationalstudent.com/Student/2018-02-22/universities_uk_offices_occupied_by_students_as_part_of_ussstrike.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=16 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316214510/http://www.thenationalstudent.com/Student/2018-02-22/universities_uk_offices_occupied_by_students_as_part_of_ussstrike.html |archivedate=16 March 2018 }}</ref> Students undertook occupations of university buildings in support of the strike at various institutions, including [[University College London]] (26 February),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thetab.com/uk/london/2018/02/27/ucl-strike-occupiers-stop-the-provost-from-getting-into-his-office-31457 |title=UCL strike occupiers stop the Provost from getting into his office |last=Bacon |first=Lucy |date=27 February 2018 |work=The Tab|access-date=5 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306083355/https://thetab.com/uk/london/2018/02/27/ucl-strike-occupiers-stop-the-provost-from-getting-into-his-office-31457 |archivedate=6 March 2018 }}</ref> the [[University of Liverpool]] (28 February)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/university-liverpool-students-occupy-vice-14343772 |title=University of Liverpool students 'occupy' Vice Chancellor's office |last=Traynor |first=Luke |date=27 February 2018 |work=The Liverpool Echo|access-date=5 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304081541/https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/university-liverpool-students-occupy-vice-14343772|archive-date=4 March 2018|url-status=}}</ref> and the [[University of Bristol]] (5 March),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-43292861 |title=Bristol students stage staff pensions strike occupation |last= |first= |date= |work=|access-date=}}</ref> along with students at Leicester, Bath, Exeter, Southampton, Sussex, and Reading.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> A fresh wave of occupations began on 12 March, following the publication of the first ACAS-brokered joint agreement between UCU and UUK, which UCU members rejected. Universities with occupations during that week included Reading,<ref>Luke Adams,'[http://www.readingchronicle.co.uk/news/16083906.Students_call_for_university_s_vice_chancellor_to_resign_during_hunger_strike/ Protesters refused to leave to support lecturers at the University of Reading] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319084822/http://www.readingchronicle.co.uk/news/16083906.Students_call_for_university_s_vice_chancellor_to_resign_during_hunger_strike/ |date=19 March 2018 }}', ''The Reading Chronicle'' (13 March 2018).</ref> Cambridge (in the [[Old Schools]]),<ref>Oliver Guest and Todd Gillespie, '[https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/15145 Student activists occupy Old Schools in support of strikes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316023037/https://www.varsity.co.uk/news/15145 |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''Varsity'' (12 March 2018).</ref> Dundee,<ref>Nadia Vidinova, [https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/dundee/616612/dundee-university-students-occupy-tower-building-night-support-striking-lecturers/ Dundee University students occupy Tower building all night in support of striking lecturers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316084802/https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/dundee/616612/dundee-university-students-occupy-tower-building-night-support-striking-lecturers/ |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''The Courier'' (13 March 2018).</ref> York (in [[Heslington Hall]]),<ref>Chloe Laversuch, '[https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/educationnews/news/16083438.Students_occupy_Heslington_Hall_in_support_of_lecturers_in_pension_dispute/ York University students occupy Heslington Hall in support of lecturers in pension dispute]', ''The Press'' (13 March 2018).</ref> Sheffield (in the [[Arts Tower]]),<ref>Dominic Penna, '[https://thetab.com/uk/sheffield/2018/03/14/there-have-been-mixed-reactions-to-the-occupation-of-the-arts-tower-today-30818 Opinion divided as students react to the occupation of the Arts Tower] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316024032/https://thetab.com/uk/sheffield/2018/03/14/there-have-been-mixed-reactions-to-the-occupation-of-the-arts-tower-today-30818 |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''The Tab'' (14 March 2018).</ref> Stirling,<ref>Sean Bell, '[https://www.commonspace.scot/articles/12509/we-will-not-tolerate-any-strikebreaking-stirling-students-stage-occupation-support \"We will not tolerate any strikebreaking\": Stirling students stage occupation in support of UCU strike] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316151723/https://www.commonspace.scot/articles/12509/we-will-not-tolerate-any-strikebreaking-stirling-students-stage-occupation-support |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''Commonspace'' (14 March 2018).</ref> Aberdeen,<ref>'[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-north-east-orkney-shetland-43400643 Police called to University of Aberdeen protest] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314215445/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-north-east-orkney-shetland-43400643 |date=14 March 2018 }}', ''BBC News'' (14 March 2018).</ref> Surrey,<ref>Joe Burn, '[https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/surrey-news/university-surrey-strikes-students-occupy-14410433 University of Surrey strikes: Students occupy Senate House in support of ongoing UCU pensions dispute] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316151725/https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/surrey-news/university-surrey-strikes-students-occupy-14410433 |date=16 March 2018 }}', ''Get Surrey'' (14 March 2018).</ref> Sussex,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thetab.com/uk/sussex/2018/03/15/forty-students-occupy-new-east-slope-accommodation-construction-site-26510 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=16 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316214649/https://thetab.com/uk/sussex/2018/03/15/forty-students-occupy-new-east-slope-accommodation-construction-site-26510 |archivedate=16 March 2018 }}</ref> and Glasgow.<ref>'[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-43413006 Students occupy Glasgow uni room in pension row] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319095739/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-43413006 |date=19 March 2018 }}', ''BBC News'' (15 March 2018).</ref>\n\nThe purpose of the occupations extended into other issues: on 19 March, University of London students occupied [[Senate House, London|Senate House]] in support of a strike called for 25\u201326 April by outsourced worked including cleaners, porters and receptionists.<ref>Sanjana Varghese, '[https://londonstudent.coop/news/2018/03/20/uol-premises-in-senate-house-occupied-by-students/ BREAKING: UoL premises in Senate House occupied by students] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323032017/https://londonstudent.coop/news/2018/03/20/uol-premises-in-senate-house-occupied-by-students/ |date=23 March 2018 }}', ''London Student'' (20 March 2018).</ref> At one point during the occupation, students were locked into a room by staff members of the university.<ref>Ceren Sagir, '[https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/university-of-london-seals-protesting-students-into-a-room University of London seals protesting students into a room]', ''Morning Star'' (22 March 2018).</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the February\u2013March strikes, the students' union at [[SOAS]] called on its members to refuse to submit work with deadlines before 23 March, arguing that deadlines so soon after the end of the strikes would negatively affect students' work.<ref>Safa Daud, '[https://londonstudent.coop/news/2018/03/18/soas-su-calls-for-student-boycott-of-coursework-deadlines/ SOAS SU calls for student boycott of coursework deadlines] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323030623/https://londonstudent.coop/news/2018/03/18/soas-su-calls-for-student-boycott-of-coursework-deadlines/ |date=23 March 2018 }}', ''London Student'' (18 March 2018).</ref>\n\n==== Compensation ====\nStudents, who in [[England]] had since 2012 paid fees covering most of the cost of their education, responded by demanding compensation from their universities, explicitly in support of the striking staff: by 20 February 2018, 70,000 had signed letters and petitions of this kind,<ref>Sally Weale, '[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/feb/20/70000-students-call-for-compensation-over-ucu-lecturer-strike 70,000 students call for compensation over UCU lecturer strike] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227003554/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/feb/20/70000-students-call-for-compensation-over-ucu-lecturer-strike|date=27 February 2018}}', ''The Guardian'' (20 February 2018).</ref> rising to around 126,000 by 5 March.<ref name=\":400\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43295334|title=University strike talks suspended without agreement|last=Burns|first=Judith|date=5 March 2018|work=BBC News|url-status=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305225924/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-43295334|archive-date=5 March 2018|access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March 2018, it was reported that [[King's College London]] had become the first university to offer to use money not spent on striking staff's salaries to compensate students.<ref>Sian Griffiths, '[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/kings-college-london-students-offered-refund-over-lecturers-strike-bmf0czbc6 King\u2019s College London offers student refunds over lecturers\u2019 strike]', ''The Sunday Times'' (4 March 2018).</ref><ref>Sylvie Dumont, '[https://thetab.com/uk/kings/2018/03/04/breaking-kcl-is-offering-refunds-to-students-for-the-ucu-strikes-20744 King\u2019s College London is offering refunds to students for the lecturer strikes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305062922/https://thetab.com/uk/kings/2018/03/04/breaking-kcl-is-offering-refunds-to-students-for-the-ucu-strikes-20744|date=5 March 2018}}', ''The Tab'' (4 March 2018).</ref> Robert Liow, a third-year law student at the university, told the [[BBC]] that if universities did not refund students part of their fees, they would be profiting from the dispute, as they would gain the money not paid to striking university staff:\n<blockquote>I don't want a consumerist education service. I believe education is a public good and not a service to be sold. But if we are going to be treated as consumers we are going to ask for our money back.<ref name=\":5\" /></blockquote>\n\nOn 23 March 2018, it was reported that the international disputes lawyers Asserson had begun co-ordinating a no-win no-fee suit for compensation for students affected by the strikes, inviting students to sign up to participate online.<ref>Jamie Barlow, '[https://www.nottinghampost.com/news/nottingham-news/international-law-firm-launches-claim-1378812 International law firm launches claim for University of Nottingham students to receive compensation amid strike action]', ''Nottingham Post'' (23 March 2018).</ref> On 24 April 2018, it was announced that over 1,000 students had signed up: enough to apply for a [[Group Litigation Order|group litigation order]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/students-bid-uk-strike-compensation-passes-legal-milestone|title=Students\u2019 bid for UK strike compensation \u2018passes legal milestone\u2019|date=2018-04-24|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en}}</ref> By 17 June, over 5,000 had joined. Asserson estimated that one million students had been affected by the strike, with 575,000 teaching hours lost. They suggested that universities might be liable for \u00a320m compensation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/thousands-uk-students-join-pensions-strike-compensation-claim|title=Thousands of UK students join pensions strike compensation claim|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nBy May 2019, the [[Office of the Independent Adjudicator]] for Higher Education (designated under the Higher Education Act 2004 to run the higher education student complaints scheme within England and Wales) has issued a number of adjudictions in response to student complaints, asking universities to offer partial refunds of fees.<ref>Eleanor Busby, '[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/students-university-strikes-tuition-fees-compensation-office-independent-adjudicator-complaints-a8913806.html Universities told to refund half of students\u2019 tuition fees for failing to make up missed lectures during strikes]', ''The Independent'' (14 May 2019).</ref>\n\n==== In media ====\nOn 25 November 2019, Joshua Curiel, a student at the [[University of Kent]], wrote an article for ''[[The Guardian]]'' encouraging fellow students to support their lectures. Curiel  argued that \"This strike will have a greater impact if universities see that the lecturers have the full support of their students and understand that changes must be made. We have a part to play in these strikes, to keep the pressure up to ensure fairer working conditions.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2019/nov/25/students-dont-complain-about-your-striking-lecturers-join-them|title=Students: don't complain about your striking lecturers \u2013 join them|last=Curiel|first=Joshua|date=2019-11-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Politicians===\n\nOn 29 November 2017, [[Carol Monaghan]] (Scottish National Party) tabled an [[Early Day Motion]] in the [[House of Commons]] entitled \"Defending Academic Pensions\", noting \"with concern the proposal by Universities UK to close the defined benefit portion of the Universities Superannuation Scheme (USS) to all future service\". The motion was sponsored by [[Caroline Lucas]] (Green Party), [[Martyn Day (politician)|Martyn Day]] and [[Pete Wishart]] (SNP), and [[Jim Cunningham (British politician)|Jim Cunningham]], and [[Mary Glindon]] (Labour). As of 19 March, it had been signed by 133 MPs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.parliament.uk/edm/2017-19/619/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=16 March 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317102206/https://www.parliament.uk/edm/2017-19/619/ |archivedate=17 March 2018 }}.</ref><ref>Djuna Thurley, '[https://dera.ioe.ac.uk/31113/1/CBP-8156_Redacted.pdf Universities Superannuation Scheme (USS)]', House of Commons Library, briefing paper CBP-8156 (20 February 2018), p. 14.</ref>\n\nDuring the first week of industrial action, UCU's stance was explicitly supported by the Labour<ref>Emma Bartlett, '[https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/jeremycorbynsends-solidarity-thanks-lecturers-university-12069042 Jeremy Corbyn sends 'solidarity and thanks' to lecturers and other university staff who begin a month of walkouts over pensions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304081459/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/jeremycorbynsends-solidarity-thanks-lecturers-university-12069042 |date=4 March 2018 }}', ''The Mirror'' (22 February 2018).</ref> and Green Parties.<ref>Liam Soutar, '[https://www.wigantoday.net/news/politics/backing-for-lecturers-strike-1-9032979 Backing for lecturers\u2019 strike] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223193630/https://www.wigantoday.net/news/politics/backing-for-lecturers-strike-1-9032979 |date=23 February 2018 }}', ''Wigan Today'' (23 February 2018).</ref> The Liberal Democrats argued that the government should underwrite the USS pension scheme, easing its assessment of risk.<ref>Lizzy Buchan, '[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/university-strike-lecturers-pensions-government-vince-cable-a8225801.html University strikes: Ministers urged to step in to guarantee lecturers' pensions after mass walkouts]', ''The Independent'' (24 February 2018).</ref> The Conservative universities minister [[Sam Gyimah]] encouraged the parties to negotiate, and encouraged universities to compensate students for missed education.<ref>Eleanor Busby, '[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/university-strikes-compensation-lecturers-students-sam-gyimah-direct-minister-latest-a8232746.html University strikes: Students set to receive 'direct compensation' over lectures missed due to action, minister says] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180311071501/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/university-strikes-compensation-lecturers-students-sam-gyimah-direct-minister-latest-a8232746.html |date=11 March 2018 }}', ''The Independent'' (28 February 2018).</ref>\n\nThe Chinese embassy in the UK also made representations to the Department for Education, expressing concern for the situation of Chinese students in the UK.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>'[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-03/01/c_137006815.htm Chinese embassy concerned as lasting UK university strike affects students] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303105726/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-03/01/c_137006815.htm|date=3 March 2018}}', ''China-Europe'' (1 March 2018).</ref>\n\n===UCU===\nThe \"intense infighting\" experienced by parts of UCU during and following the 2018 pension strikes and negotiations led UCU to establish a 'democracy commission' to recommend ways to improve participatory democracy within the Union. Among its recommendations was the suggestion that the office of General Secretary should be held for three-year terms, and for a maximum of three terms. The commission suggested introducing a mechanism for members to recall general secretaries. Its recommendations were put to a special congress of the union of 7 December 2019.<ref>Vicky Blake, \"[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/more-transparency-will-improve-theucus-democratic-processes More transparency will improve the UCU\u2019s democratic processes]\", ''Times Higher Education'' (5 December 2019).</ref>\n\n===Scholarly societies===\n\nSome scholarly societies issued statements supporting the strike or its goals. They included [[History UK]], which said it 'believes universities should try to maintain the conditions of employment under which academics were originally employed. That includes pensions';<ref>'[https://www.history-uk.ac.uk/2018/03/05/huk-statement-on-current-industrial-action/ HUK statement on current industrial action]' (5 March 2018)</ref><ref>George Gosling, '[https://www.socialhistory.org.uk/2018/03/10/shs-statement-on-the-uss-pensions-dispute/ SHS Statement on the USS Pensions Dispute]' (10 March 2018).</ref> the Englineering Professors' Council;<ref>'[https://web.archive.org/web/20180807030553/http://epc.ac.uk/statement-on-strike-action-over-uss-pensions/ Statement on strike action over USS Pensions]' (1 March 2018).</ref> and the British Dental Association.<ref>'[https://bda.org/academicpensions Changes to Academic Pensions]'.</ref> Others did not take a position but did publicly discuss the issues, among them the [[British Psychological Society]].<ref>Julianna Challenor, Trudi Edginton, Deborah Rafalin, Carla Willig, '[https://thepsychologist.bps.org.uk/volume-31/april-2018/call-support-pensions-dispute Call to support in pensions dispute]', ''The Psychologist'', 31 (April 2018), 1-2.</ref>\n\n===Media===\n\n==== Traditional media ====\nThe action attracted national television coverage,<ref>E.g. Jane Deith, '[https://www.channel4.com/news/university-staff-strike-over-pensions University staff strike over pensions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304081457/https://www.channel4.com/news/university-staff-strike-over-pensions|date=4 March 2018}}', ''Channel 4 News'' (22 February 2018).</ref> and supportive editorials from newspapers including the ''Observer''<ref>'[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/feb/25/observer-view-on-the-shambolic-way-universities-are-run?CMP=share_btn_fb The Observer view on the shambolic way universities are run] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301044621/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/feb/25/observer-view-on-the-shambolic-way-universities-are-run?CMP=share_btn_fb |date=1 March 2018 }}', ''The Observer'' (25 February 2018).</ref> and the ''Financial Times'', which opined that \"the universities must increase their pensions offer, and lecturers should give a fair hearing to any new proposals. Failing that, students should be compensated by the colleges\".<ref name=\"auto2\" /> Support for UUK, meanwhile, was offered in ''The Times'', with [[Daniel Finkelstein]], for example, arguing that \"the pension fund is a pot of money shared between current and past staff. All that the trustees and the regulator are trying to do is to make sure it is fairly shared out. They are ensuring the money hasn't all been given away while there are people with future claims against it\".<ref>Daniel Finkelstein, '[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lecturers-can-t-expect-us-to-pay-their-pensions-nsq30t2fw Lecturers can\u2019t expect us to pay their pensions]', ''The Times'' (27 February 2018).</ref>\n\nA number of commentators expressed exasperation at a tendency in the media, and on social media, to refer to the strike as a \"lecturers' strike\", when it involved a wide range of staff, academic and non-academic.<ref>Fiona Whelan, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-why-arent-more-administrative-staff-picket-lines USS strike: why aren\u2019t more administrative staff on picket lines?]', ''Times Higher Education'' (28 February 2018).</ref>\n\n====Social media====\nUCU members made extensive use of social media during the dispute. They were used to disseminate activists' research on the changes to pensions.<ref>Sherrill Stroschein, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/uss-strike-social-media-has-collapsed-case-pension-cuts USS strike: social media has collapsed the case for pension cuts]', ''Times Higher Education'' (12 March 2018).</ref> Social media were also used to satirise universities' senior management: for example, the hashtag #FindMyProvost was used to mock vice-chancellors who did not engage with staff,<ref name=\"auto9\"/> and the 'UCU Strikeposting' meme page on Facebook, which was ran by students and staff who supported the strike, and quickly amassed over 6,000 likes in 4 weeks.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/shitpostingoncompanytime/</ref> Hashtags were also a powerful organising tool. A prominent example was the Twitter hashtag '''''#NoCapitulation''''', which emerged as the unifying message university staff rallied behind twenty hours after the Acas agreement of 12 March.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref>Phil Hedges, '[https://www.academia.edu/38024462 (Still) writing a history of now: #NoCapitulation]', ''Interface: A Journal for and about Social Movements'', 10 (2018), 196-214.</ref> Dr Ed Rooksby, a tutor at [[Ruskin College]] Oxford, said \"the leadership saw this wave of hostility coming towards them and backed down ... I'm sure there wouldn't have been as much momentum without Twitter, and without someone coming up with that hashtag.\"<ref name=\":11\" /> Dr. Jo Grady, a senior lecturer in employment relations at [[University of Sheffield|Sheffield University]], stated her belief that Twitter had helped people connect \"outside of traditional union frameworks\" and that this was ironic as their employers were the ones who encouraged staff to use social media as a tool for self-promotion.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n== 2019\u201320 industrial action on pensions and on the 'four fights' ==\n[[File:UCU Four Fights placard.jpg|thumb|UCU Four Fights placard]]\nConcern about pay and conditions, particularly in relation to high senior pay and expenditure on new buildings in the face of declining staff pay, the gender pay gap, precarious contracts and casualisation, and workloads were all expressed as part of the wider context of the pensions dispute, but also formed the basis of ballots for industrial action across all UK higher education unions ([[UNISON]], [[Unite the Union|Unite]], [[Educational Institute of Scotland|EIS]], [[GMB (trade union)|GMB]] and UCU) during the period of the pensions strikes.\n\nAccordingly, from September to October 2019, UCU balloted members for industrial action in two disputes: renewed industrial action on pensions (for those institutions participating in USS), and new industrial action on pay and conditions (which UCU called the 'four fights'\u2014pay inequality, job insecurity, rising workloads, and pay deflation\u2014for all higher education branches). Ballots were undertaken separately for each institution in the belief that turnout might pass the 50% of members required by the [[Trade Union Act 2016]] at a sufficient number of institutions to enable meaningful industrial action, while averting the risk of an aggregated national ballot falling below the 50% threshold. It was argued that it was necessary to make industrial action possible on both issues at once to avoid gains to overall remuneration made via one channel being negated by losses on the other.\n\n=== Ballot on USS pensions (31 October 2019) ===\nOn 26 May 2019, UCU's Higher Education Sector Conference voted to commence a further dispute with USS employers. UCU wrote to relevant vice-chancellors on 7 June asking them to avert possible industrial action by committing \"to uphold the level of contributions no higher than 26% (8% for members)\", in the first instance by seeking to influence USS policy via employers' representatives on the Employers\u2019 Pension Forum (EPF) and the UUK nominees to USS's joint negotiating committee. The Union asked that, failing that, employers \"must cover any increases in full that are needed to maintain current benefits until USS\u2019s governance and valuation methods and assumptions have been overhauled\".<ref>Paul Bridge, '[https://web.archive.org/web/20190617140150/http://www.leedsucu.org.uk/notice-of-trade-dispute-over-uss-pensions/ Notice of Trade Dispute Over USS Pensions]' (7 June 2019).</ref>\n\nOn 31 October 2019, UCU reported that of 64 branches balloted, at least 43 had passed the 50% turnout threshold or were otherwise able to take industrial action. The national aggregate of votes (with four institutions still to be counted) achieved a 53% turnout with 79% voting for strike action.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10399/UCU-members-back-strikes-over-both-pensions-and-pay-and-conditions|title=UCU members back strikes over both pensions and pay and conditions|last=|first=|date=31 October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Ballots concerning joint higher education trade union national pay claim (31 October 2019)===\n\n==== 2018-19 pay negotiations ====\n[[File:UCU strike placard reading re equal pay.jpg|thumb|Strike placard relating to the equality component of the \"four fights\".]]\nIn March 2018, the UK's Joint Negotiating Committee for Higher Education Staff began its round of negotiations for pay in the sector for 2018/19, with unions demanding a large pay uplift.<ref name=\"HE_Pay_claim_submitted 2018\" /><ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> Citing long-term real-term declining pay, on 26 March 2018 the unions submitted a pay claim seeking a 7.5% pay increase or \u00a31,500, whichever was greater; a \u00a310 minimum wage to make all higher education institutions \"[[living wage]]\" employers; and gender pay equality by 2020.<ref name=\"HE_Pay_claim_submitted 2018\" /> In April 2018, the [[Universities and Colleges Employers Association]] proposed a 1.7% pay increase for 2018\u201319, raising the offer to 2% (and 2.8% for the lowest paid) in May. These figures were both below inflation, which in March 2018 stood at 2.7%.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /><ref>Ellie Bothwell, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/uk-university-staff-offered-2-cent-pay-rise UK university staff offered 2 per cent pay rise]', ''Times Higher Education'' (11 May 2018).</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 2018, UCU commenced a consultative ballot to determine whether to conduct a formal ballot for industrial action in relation to the UK Joint Negotiating Committee for Higher Education Staff's negotiations over 2018-19 pay. The ballot closed on 27 June 2018, with 82% of participating members voting to reject the offer from the University and Colleges Employers\u2019 Association of a minimum pay rise of 2 per cent, rising to 2.8 per cent for the lowest paid.<ref name=\"Anna McKie 2018\">Anna McKie, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/uk-university-staff-vote-strike-action-pay-dispute UK university staff to vote on strike action in pay dispute]', ''Times Higher Education'' (29 June 2018).</ref> UCU formally declared a trade dispute on 24 July 2018.<ref name=\"HE national negotiations 2018-19\">'[https://web.archive.org/web/20180911184449/https://www.ucu.org.uk/he2018?utm_source=lyr-ucu-members&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=members&utm_term=he-full-jnches&utm_content=Pay+and+equality+ballot+now+open HE national negotiations 2018-19]' (accessed 11 September 2018).</ref> On 21 August 2018, UCU served statutory notice of its intention to ballot members for industrial action regarding the 2018-19 national pay dispute. The ballot opened on 30 August 2018.<ref name=\"Anna McKie 2018\" /><ref name=\"HE national negotiations 2018-19\" /> On 22 October 2018 UCU announced the results of the ballot. Although the majority of Union members who voted elected to take industrial action, the turnout only passed the 50% of members required by the [[Trade Union Act 2016]] at seven universities (alongside which three Northern Irish universities, unaffected by the legislation, also voted to strike).<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/9724/Trade-union-laws-frustrate-national-support-for-strike-action-on-pay Trade union laws frustrate national support for strike action on pay]' (22 October 2018).</ref> Likewise, on 29 October Unison reported that although a majority of voting members had supported strike action, the vote was frustrated by insufficient turnout.<ref>'[https://web.archive.org/web/20181031130100/https://www.unison.org.uk/news/article/2018/10/he-ballot-result/ Higher education ballot result]' (29 October 2018).</ref> On 7 November, UCU's special higher education sector conference decided to run another ballot, this time aggregating votes across the sector rather than running a different ballot for each university. On 23 November, the ballot was scheduled to run from 14 January to 22 February 2019.<ref name=\"Next Steps Agreed' 2018\">'Next Steps Agreed', ''[https://www.ucu.org.uk/he2018 HE national negotiations 2018-19]'' (26 November 2018).</ref> This ballot achieved a turnout of only 41%, so again led to no industrial action.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /><ref name=\"Chris Havergal 2019\">Chris Havergal, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/ucu-members-vote-strike-over-pay-threshold-falls-short UK union members vote to strike over pay but turnout falls short]', ''Times Higher Education'' (22 February 2019).</ref><ref name=\"McNeill, 2019\">Jo McNeill, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/blog/pay-ballot-shows-ucu-stronger-ever The pay ballot shows that the UCU is stronger than ever]', ''Times Higher Education'' (25 February 2019).</ref>\n\n==== 2019-20 pay negotiations ====\n[[File:University of Leeds UCU placard re secure contracts.jpg|thumb|Strike placard relating to the casualisation and workload components of the \"four fights\".]]\nOn 1 May 2019, employers' final offer in the 2019-20 pay negotiations was 1.8%, rising to 3.65% for the lowest paid (deleting the lowest point on the pay scale to ensure a living wage for all staff). For most members, the offered raise was below inflation (then 2.4% RPI), and unions called for an increase of RPI+3% or of \u00a33,349 \u2013 whichever was greater.<ref>Chris Havergal, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/final-pay-offer-promises-34-cent-average-rise-uk-staff Final pay offer promises 1.8 per cent minimum rise for UK staff]', ''Times Higher Education'' (1 May 2019).</ref> Later that month, the UCU congress resolved to campaign to win an industrial action ballot on this offer, with a campaign naming the 'four fights' of pay, equality, casualisation, and workload. Unite and Unison also resolved to ballot on pay.\n\nOn 31 October 2019, Unison reported that although around 66% of members voting had voted for strike action, turnout had not passed the 50% threshold.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unison.org.uk/news/article/2019/10/he-ballot-result-2/|title=Higher education pay ballot result|last=|first=|date=31 October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Likewise, Unite announced that 73.3% of members had voted to take action, but that turnout had been 32.1%.<ref>'[https://unitetheunion.org/campaigns/higher-education-pay-vote-to-strike/ Higher Education Pay  Vote to strike]'.</ref>\n\nOn the same day, UCU reported that of 148 branches balloted, at least 54 had passed the 50% turnout threshold or were otherwise able to take industrial action. The national aggregate of votes achieved a 49% turnout with 74% voting for strike action (with four institutions still to be counted).<ref name=\":18\" />\n\n=== UCU announces eight days of strikes (5 November 2019) ===\nOn 5 November 2019, UCU announced that at those institutions with a legal mandate to strike, eight consecutive strike days would be held from Monday 25 November to Wednesday 4 December, 'unless', in the words of UCU's general secretary Jo Grady, 'the employers start talking to us seriously about how they are going to deal with rising pension costs and declining pay and conditions'. Following 4 December, Union members were also to begin action short of a strike (such as 'working to contract'). 60 universities were to be affected (43 regarding both pensions and pay, 14 regarding pay only, and 3 regarding pensions only).<ref>'[https://web.archive.org/web/20191105181624/https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10408/UCU-announces-eight-days-of-strikes-starting-this-month-at-60-universities UCU announces eight days of strikes starting this month at 60 universities]' (5 November 2019).</ref><ref>Sally Weale, '[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/nov/05/university-strike-could-affect-over-a-million-students-says-union University strike could affect more than a million students, says union]', ''The Guardian'' (5 November 2019).</ref><ref name=\"Bethan Staton 2019\"/>\n\nIt was estimated that the strikes would affect over a million students.<ref>Eleanor Busby, '[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/uk-university-strikes-pensions-students-staff-ucu-ballot-pay-a9181281.html UK university strikes: Walkouts at 60 institutions to hit more than a million students]', ''The Independent'' (5 November 2019).</ref>\n\nSpokespeople for UUK and Universities & Colleges Employers Association argued that UCU did not have a strong mandate for action given that the majority of branches had not qualified to take strike action. The UUK spokesperson expressed hopes that the industrial dispute could be resolved without strike action and that UCU 'will now join us to consider governance reforms and alternative options for future valuations' regarding USS. The UCea spokesperson argued that the 2019-20 national pay negotiations had delivered a pay deal 'at the very limit of what is affordable'.<ref>Anna McKie, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/ucu-announces-eight-days-strikes-starting-late-november UCU announces eight days of strikes, starting late November]', ''Times Higher Education'' (5 November 2019).</ref> Opinion among university leaders was not uniform, however: on 15 November, the vice-chancellor of the University of Essex argued that 'the University of Essex is willing to increase contributions to the scheme to sustain critical features of the USS, including defined benefits'.<ref>Anthony Forster, '[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2019/nov/15/as-a-university-leader-i-think-we-can-afford-a-better-pensions-deal-for-striking-staff As a university leader, I think we can afford a better pensions deal for striking staff]', ''The Guardian'' (15 November 2019).</ref><ref name=\":19\">Chris Havergal, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/essex-v-c-says-universities-can-afford-pay-more-pensions Essex v-c says universities can afford to pay more into pensions]', ''Times Higher Education'' (18 November 2019).</ref><ref name=\":19\" />\n\nOn 19 November, UUK and UCEA jointly wrote an open letter 'to staff impacted by the UCU pensions and pay disputes', partly arguing that 'the publication of the JEP's second report will present UUK and UCU with the opportunity to develop a valuable and sustainable future for USS' and that while universities 'simply cannot afford to put more into this year's pay increases than they already have', UCEA had invited negotiations on 'workload, gender pay/equality and casual employment arrangements'.<ref>https://www.universitiesuk.ac.uk/news/Documents/uuk-ucea-open-letter-ucu-disputes-pensions-pay.pdf</ref> UCU's response included the argument that 'you cannot refuse to talk about pay yet say you want to talk about closing pay gaps that exist for women and [[Black and Minority Ethnic|BME]] staff' and that 'we are always keen to negotiate and will attend talks to try and avert the disruption the strikes will inevitably cause'.<ref>'[https://ucu.org.uk/article/10448/UCU-accuses-universities-of-playing-games-after-they-offer-to-talk-about-anything-but-pay UCU accuses universities of 'playing games' after they offer to talk about anything but pay]' (19 November 2019).</ref>\n\n=== Strikes take place (25 November\u20134 December 2019) ===\n[[File:UCU Strike Rally, Buchanan Street, Glasgow 02.jpg|thumb|UCU Strike Rally, Buchanan Street, Glasgow.]]\n[[File:University of Leeds Sociologists on Strike banner.jpg|thumb|University of Leeds Sociologists on Strike banner]]\nStrikes began on 25 November. According to figures subsequently gathered by UCEA, 29.2% of UCU members at the affected universities took strike action, representing 5% of all staff at those universities (not all of whom were in the constituency represented by UCU), though around 26% reported pockets of high impact on teaching.<ref>Anna McKie, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/one-three-union-members-joined-strikes-say-employers One in three union members joined strikes, say employers]', ''Times Higher Education'' (7 January 2020).</ref>\n\nAs in 2018, striking staff at a number of universities ran educational 'teach-outs' off campus, which were open to students affected by the strikes.<ref>Andrew Jack, '[https://www.ft.com/content/06c0f420-0fa1-11ea-a7e6-62bf4f9e548a University staff launch 8-day strike across UK]', ''Financial Times'' (25 November 2019).</ref> On 27 November, negotiators from UCU and UCEA met, with UCEA pledging to consult its members on 'gender and ethnicity pay gaps, casual employment arrangements and workload' ahead of a meeting the next week, while stating that it had no mandate to alter the pay increase that had been implemented for the 2019\u201320 academic year.<ref>'[https://www.ucea.ac.uk/news-releases/26nov19/ Statement from today's meeting between UCEA and UCU]' (27 November 2019).</ref><ref>'[https://web.archive.org/web/20191127190649/https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10467/UCU-statement-on-latest-pay-talks UCU statement on latest pay talks]' (27 November 2019).</ref>\n\nEmployers' organisations continued to argue that the strike represented a minority of staff in a minority of universities,<ref>Anna McKie, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/solid-support-strikes-staff-rally-over-pay-and-pensions \"Solid\" support for strikes as staff rally over pay and pensions]', ''Times Higher Education'' (25 November 2019).</ref> with Oxford Brookes University's vice-chancellor Alistair Fitt arguing further that 'the call for more money comes at a time when universities are operating in a challenging environment amid increased competition, a freeze on tuition fees, and prolonged uncertainty over the implications of Brexit'.<ref>Alistair Fitt, '[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/why-were-asking-college-lecturers-to-stop-striking-over-pensions-and-get-back-to-talking-wjs23rp6x Why we\u2019re asking college lecturers to stop striking over pensions and get back to talking]', ''The Times'' (25 November 2019).</ref> A few universities were reported as being heavy-handed in their response to the strikes, with the University of Liverpool attracting criticism for telling its students they must not join picket lines;<ref name=\":21\">Sally Weale and David Batty, '[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2019/nov/27/international-students-crossing-picket-lines-out-of-fear-of-losing-visas International students crossing picket lines \"out of fear of losing visas\"]', ''The Guardian'' (27 November 2019).</ref> [[Sheffield Hallam University|Sheffield Hallam]] putting a form online for students to record which lecturers were on strike (which attracted a large number of satirical submissions);<ref>Helena Horton, '[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/25/students-complain-asked-snitch-university-asks-names-striking/ Students complain they are being asked to 'snitch' after university asks for names of striking lecturers as eight day industrial action begins]', ''The Telegraph'' (25 November 2019).</ref> and the [[University of Birmingham]] telling its staff that picketing on campus would be trespass (which attracted a large petition in opposition).<ref name=\":20\" />\n\nAs the strikes began, the ''Guardian'' published an editorial arguing that the strikes represented \"a battle for the soul of the campus\" and that \"the market model in higher education has created an intellectual precariat who are right to fight back\".<ref>'[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/nov/25/the-guardian-view-on-university-strikes-a-battle-for-the-soul-of-the-campus The Guardian view on university strikes: a battle for the soul of the campus]', ''The Guardian'' (25 November 2019).</ref> Soon after, the ''Financial Times'' ran en editorial arguing that \"while academics and universities might not want to hear it, if the USS is to continue operating, the money has to come from them\", and also saying that \"the current industrial action carries wider significance than the fate of a disputed retirement plan. It has exposed the precariousness of Britain's higher education system as it has become more of a marketplace\", and calling for an \"independent inquiry\" into the handling of the USS valuation \"by all key players, including the Pensions Regulator\".<ref>\"[https://amp.ft.com/content/94c1d5ca-11e8-11ea-a7e6-62bf4f9e548a Universities strike is over more than just pensions]\", ''The Financial Times'' (28 November 2019).</ref>\n\nThe [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]] supported the strikes, as did the Labour shadow secretary for education, [[Angela Rayner]].<ref>Jasmin Gray, '[https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/ucu-strike-university-staff-pensions-pay_uk_5ddbb178e4b00149f71ff63f University Strike 2019: Why Are UCU Lecturers And Staff Taking Action?]', ''Huffington Post'' (25 November 2019).</ref><ref>Eleanor Busby, '[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/university-strikes-pensions-students-pay-ucu-ballot-disruption-a9216816.html University strikes: Picket lines and cancelled lectures as tens of thousands of staff walk out]', ''The Independent'' (25 November 2019).</ref> Support from individual university students' unions was less clear, with some, such as the [[University of Birmingham Guild of Students]], taking an explicitly neutral stance.<ref name=\":20\">Ewan Somerville and Phoebe Southworth, '[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/28/picket-lines-trespassing-university-birmingham-tells-striking/ Picket lines are trespassing, University of Birmingham tells its striking lecturers]', ''The Telegraph'' (28 November 2019).</ref> [[Reading University Students' Union|Reading University Students Union]] voted to support the strikes, but was unusual in doing so.<ref>Alex Seabrook, '[https://www.readingchronicle.co.uk/news/18067445.university-reading-students-support-strike/ University of Reading students support the strike]', ''The'' ''Reading Chronicle'' (28 November 2019).</ref> ''The Times'' reported that 'by and large' students 'support their lecturers and their anger is with universities and vice-chancellors'.<ref>Rosemary Bennett, '[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/university-lecturers-strike-will-hit-a-million-students-nq759wskw Students join picket lines to support striking lecturers]<nowiki>', ''The Times''</nowiki> (26 November 2019), p. 2.</ref> In [[University of Edinburgh|Edinburgh]], students occupied [[David Hume Tower]] in solidarity with the strike,<ref>Joshua King, '[https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/education/edinburgh-students-occupy-david-hume-tower-solidarity-striking-lecturers-1325198 Edinburgh students occupy David Hume Tower in solidarity with striking lecturers]', ''Edinburgh Evening News'' (26 November 2019).</ref> while students at [[University of Strathclyde|Strathclyde University]] occupied a lecture theatre (both in support of the strikes and in protest at what they called 'rampant mismanagement, alleged corruption and irresponsible fossil fuel investment at the University of Strathclyde').<ref>Lynn Love, '[https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/strathclyde-university-students-barricade-themselves-20963093 Strathclyde University students barricade themselves in lecture theatre to support striking staff]', ''The Daily Record'' (26 November 2019).</ref><ref>James Delaney, '[https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18061296.scottish-university-students-take-lecture-hall-solidarity-striking-staff/ Scottish University students take over lecture hall in solidarity with striking staff]', ''The Herald'' (26 November 2019).</ref> Students at the [[University of Stirling]] occupied a management building for two weeks, later receiving an eight-week suspension in punishment.<ref>Eleanor Busby and Gina Gambetta, \"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/university-strikes-uk-students-staff-compensation-stirling-winchester-occupation-a9351681.html University strikes: Students face punishment after supporting staff walkouts]\", ''The Independent'' (21 February 2020).</ref>\n\nSome scholarly societies, such as the [[American Studies Association]], expressed support for the strike.<ref>'[https://theasa.net/about/news-events/announcements/statement-support-uk-university-college-union Statement of Support with the (UK) University and College Union]' (2 December 2019).</ref>\n\nThe 2019 strikes took place in a somewhat different regulatory and legal environment from the 2018 ones, due to the establishment of the [[Office for Students]] and the emergence of a body of case-law from the [[Office of the Independent Adjudicator]] on the compensation of students for lost teaching in the wake of the 2018 strikes.<ref>Bill Gardner, '[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/26/lecturers-strike-having-damaging-effect-students-mental-health/ Lecturers' strike risks having a damaging effect on students with mental health problems, complaints watchdog warns]', ''The Telegraph'' (26 November 2019).</ref><ref>Fabio Aric\u00f2, '[https://theconversation.com/university-strikes-yes-students-should-get-compensation-but-not-in-the-form-of-monetary-payment-127535 University strikes: yes, students should get compensation \u2013 but not in the form of monetary payment]', ''The Conversation'' (27 November 2019).</ref> Growing anxiety about the position of international students whose visa requirements for class attendance might be affected by the strikes, in the context of the [[Home Office hostile environment policy|UK Home Office's hostile environment]] policy towards migrants, was also in evidence.<ref name=\":21\" /> The [[University of Liverpool]] and [[Goldsmiths, University of London|Goldsmiths University]] attracted particular attention for telling international students that missing classes on account of refusing to cross picket lines might jeopardise their visas.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref>Max Clements, '[https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/university-liverpool-under-fire-over-17310653 University of Liverpool under fire over 'intimidating' letter to students about strike action]', ''The Liverpool Echo'' (25 November 2019), p. 13.</ref>\n\n=== Following strike action (5\u201312 December 2019) ===\nIn the wake of the strike action, UCU called for 'action short of a strike' in the form of 'working to contract', interpreted primarily as working only the hours notionally required and not rescheduling teaching missed during the strikes. As in 2018, universities' responses to this varied, with some threatening pay deductions for 'partial performance' in the event of staff not rescheduling teaching and others not planning to deduct pay.<ref>Anna McKie, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/universities-split-over-pay-deductions-action-short-strike Universities split over pay deductions for action short of strike]', ''Times Higher Education'' (3 December 2019).</ref><ref>Andrew Chitty, Felicity Callard, and Leon Rocha, '[https://web.archive.org/web/20191209132133/https://medium.com/ussbriefs/university-management-tactics-on-strike-and-asos-pay-deductions-and-ways-to-push-back-c23e9c296003 University management tactics on strike and ASOS pay deductions \u2014 and ways to push back]', ''USSbriefs'' (5 December 2019).</ref> Press coverage included mentioning the University of Liverpool for threatening partial pay deductions<ref name=\":22\">Rachel Hall, '[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2019/dec/06/staff-warn-of-intimidatory-tactics-at-liverpool-university-after-strike Staff warn of 'intimidatory' tactics at Liverpool University after strike]', ''The Guardian'' (6 December 2019).</ref> and Reading for threatening 100% pay deductions,<ref>Alex Seabrook, \"[https://www.readingchronicle.co.uk/news/18078551.university-reading-threatening-cut-100-per-cent-pay-staff-dont-work-unpaid-overtime/ University of Reading threatening to cut 100 per cent of pay if staff don\u2019t work 'unpaid overtime']\", ''The Reading Chronicle'' (4 December 2019).</ref> whereas Cambridge offered to reimburse lecturers for pay lost during the strikes if they rescheduled teaching.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nOn 4 December, UCU began reballoting thirteen branches which had nearly succeeded in achieving the 50% voter turnout necessary to take strike action, in the belief that the strike action at other branches would galvanise members into voting. It was believed that this would strengthen the threat of further industrial action.<ref>Anna McKie, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/fresh-ballots-13-uk-universities-pay-and-pensions-dispute Fresh strike ballots at 13 UK universities over pay and pensions]', ''Times Higher Education'' (26 November 2019).</ref><ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/*/https://ucu.org.uk/article/10506/Strike-ballots-to-open-at-another-24-universities Strike Ballots to Open at another 24 Universities]\" (18 December 2019).</ref>\n\n===Second report of the Joint Expert Panel on pensions (13 December 2019)===\n\n13 December saw the publication of the Joint Expert Panel's second report. This recommended changes to the governance of USS, to build on \"the establishment of a new, jointly agreed purpose statement and shared valuation principles\".<ref>\"[https://ussjep.org.uk/second-report-of-the-joint-expert-panel/ Second Report of the Joint Expert Panel]\" (13 December 2019).</ref><ref>\"[https://ussjep.org.uk/files/2019/12/JEP2-Final-Report.pdf Report of the Joint Expert Panel]\" (December 2019).</ref> Reporting focused on the Panel's proposal to introduce a dual [[discount rate]]{{disambiguation needed|date=March 2020}} into the USS pension scheme, whereby the fund supporting members who had retired would be put into low-risk, low-return investments, but the remainder of the fund (accruing to working members who had not yet retired) would be free to be invested in higher-risk, higher-return holdings.<ref>https://www.professionalpensions.com/news/4008278/uss-joint-panel-dual-discount-rate-proposal-%E2%80%98broadly-aligns%E2%80%99-tpr-views.</ref><ref>https://www.pensionsage.com/pa/JEP-publishes-recommendations-to-ease-USS-dispute.php.</ref> The report was welcomed by UUK and UCU and media reporting suggested that negotiations in its wake could lead to the cessation of impending industrial action;<ref>Anna McKie, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/fresh-uk-pension-scheme-talks-could-avert-further-strikes Fresh UK pension scheme talks \u2018could avert further strikes\u2019]', ''Times Higher Education'' (23 December 2019).</ref> as strikes loomed in February, however, the UCU general secretary Jo Grady commented that 'most importantly, employers have not yet offered to cover the unfair contribution increases that are pricing members out of the scheme', implying that this was a key sticking point.<ref>Jo Grady, '[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10623/UCU-calls-14-more-days-of-strike-action-in-higher-education UCU calls 14 more days of strike action in higher education]' (3 February 2020).</ref>\n\nThe report also recommended three-way talks between UCU, UUK and USS on the governance of USS to lead to future pension policies being more satisfactory to scheme stakeholders. The 'tripartite group' first met on 17 January 2020.<ref>Joanne Segars, '[https://ussjep.org.uk/statement-of-the-first-meeting-of-the-tripartite-group/ Statement of the first meeting of the tripartite group]' (17 January 2020).</ref>\n\nIn mid-January 2020, the [[University of Sussex]] launched an \"industrial action ex gratia scheme\" to compensate students up to \u00a3100 for inconvenience caused by the ongoing industrial action. It this became the first UK university to offer compensation while industrial action was still in process.<ref>Richard Adams, \"Sussex University offers students up to \u00a3100 for strike distress\", ''The Guardian'' (15 January 2020).</ref>\n\nOn 15 January, the [[Wellcome Trust]] published the report 'What Researchers Think About the Culture They Work In',<ref>\"[https://wellcome.ac.uk/sites/default/files/what-researchers-think-about-the-culture-they-work-in.pdf What Researchers Think About the Culture They Work In]\" (London: Wellcome Trust, 2020).</ref> which found that 29% of respondents felt secure in their jobs.<ref>Ian Sample, \"[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/jan/15/researchers-facing-shocking-levels-of-stress-survey-reveals Researchers facing \u2018shocking\u2019 levels of stress, survey reveals]\", ''The Guardian'' (15 January 2020).</ref> On 20 January, UCU published a report on 'the dehumanising effects of casualisation in higher education' that noted that '67,000 research staff were on fixed-term contracts, making up two-thirds of the total research staff employed at universities, alongside 30,000 contracted teaching staff, many paid by the hour. A further 69,000 academic staff were on \u201catypical contracts\u201d and so are not counted in the main staff record, while an estimated 6,500 were on zero-hours contracts'.<ref>Richard Adams, \"[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/jan/20/thousands-of-uk-academics-treated-as-second-class-citizens Thousands of UK academics 'treated as second-class citizens'\", ''The Guardian'' (20 January 2020).]</ref><ref>Nick Megoran and Olivia Mason, \"[https://www.ucu.org.uk/media/10681/second_class_academic_citizens/pdf/secondclassacademiccitizens Second class academic citizens: The dehumanising effects of casualisation in higher education]\" (London: University and College Union, 2020).</ref>\n\n===UCEA publish negotiating position (27 January 2020)===\nOn 27 January, UCEA published a document 'offered as part of a potential composite JNCHES settlement for 2019-20' addressing the Four Fights issues, with the exception of pay (where the pay rise offered remained at 1.8%).<ref>'[https://www.ucea.ac.uk/our-work/collective-pay-negotiations-landing/Current-pay-negotiations/without-prejudice-text-shared-with-trade-unions-on-27-january-002final.pdf REVISED PROPOSALS presented on 27 January 2020]'.</ref><ref name=\":23\">Anna KcKie, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/uk-universities-make-offer-sector-working-conditions-dispute UK universities make offer on sector working conditions in dispute]', ''Times Higher Education'' (29 January 2020).</ref> UCEA noted that it had been 'given the scope to go further than ever before as a national employer representative body', proposed to set 'expectations' for the employment practices of individual institutions, and summarised its offer at sector-level thus:<ref>'[https://www.ucea.ac.uk/our-work/collective-pay-negotiations-landing/Current-pay-negotiations/leaflet-on-uceas-offer-on-contractual-arrangements What\u2019s in UCEA\u2019s offer on contractual arrangements; workload and mental health; and gender pay gap and ethnicity pay]' (London: UCEA, 2020).</ref>\n<blockquote>\n* For '''contractual arrangements''', a new trade union/employer working group to examine the annual national staff record (HESA), looking for example at trends in \u2018zero hours\u2019 and \u2018hourly-paid\u2019 employment, and  contractual arrangements across protected characteristics. The group will produce a report of the analysis and  findings.\n* For '''workload and mental health''', trade union/employer work to further develop the national Stress and Mental Wellbeing resources through our established HE Safety and Health Forum, Trade unions, Universities UK and UCEA involvement in advancing sector-level initiatives to address staff mental health issues.\n* For '''gender pay gap''', trade unions and employers to develop an HE specific \u2018checklist\u2019 of suggestions to address blockages and enablers of women\u2019s career progression and balanced representation in gender dominated roles. There will also be collection and analysis of the overall data.\n* On '''ethnicity pay''', trade unions and employers to examine and report on national ethnicity pay gap data and investigate kinds of actions and interventions being taken by employers. Both also commit to encouraging colleagues to disclose protected characteristics.</blockquote>UCU welcomed these offers as progress but criticised the lack of an improved offer on pay and argued that UCEA needed to provide universities with 'a clear set of mechanisms for policing and enforcing the expectations which they are signing up to'.<ref name=\":23\" />\n\n===Fourteen more universities ballot for strike action (29 January 2020)===\n[[File:UCU strike what you need to know posters 2020 02 26.jpg|thumb|Posters in Leeds, February 2020.]]\nOn 29 January 2020, UCU announced results from the December\u2013January reballots of selected universities that had failed to secure a 50% turnout in the 2019 ballots. As a result, two further universities joined the disputes on pensions and pay/conditions; nine joined the dispute on pay/conditions alone; and three joined the dispute on pensions alone; and two that had been on strike about pensions only added pay/conditions to their disputes. The number of institutions with a mandate to strike at this point stood at 74 in total: 47 for pay/conditions and pensions, 22 for pay/conditions only, and 5 for pensions only.<ref name=\":26\">\"[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10555/Staff-at-another-14-universities-can-join-strike-action Staff at another 14 universities can join strike action]\" (29 January 2020).</ref>\n\n=== Strikes recommence (20 February 2020) ===\n\n==== Before the strikes ====\n[[File:University of Leeds strike rally Parkinson Building 2020 02 26 with students.jpg|thumb|University of Leeds strike rally outside the [[Parkinson Building]], 26 February 2020.]]\n[[File:KCL seal on gates and Strand Building entrance 2020.jpg|thumb|Group of people assembled for a [[teach-out]] in front of King's College London entrance on the Strand, 2 March 2020]]\nOn 3 February 2020, following consultation with branch representatives at the union's Higher Education Committee, UCU announced fourteen days of strike action, escalating over a period running from 20 February to 13 March: 20\u201321 February, 24\u201326 February, 2\u20135 March and 9\u201313 March.<ref>Anna McKie, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/union-calls-14-day-strike-uk-pay-and-pensions-dispute Union calls 14-day strike in UK pay and pensions dispute]', ''Times Higher Education'' (3 February 2020).</ref><ref>Anna McKie, '[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/union-tries-keep-members-board-more-strikes-near Union tries to keep members on board as more strikes near]', ''Times Higher Education'' (10 February 2020).</ref><ref>'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10621/UCU-announces-14-strike-days-at-74-UK-universities-in-February-and-March UCU announces 14 strike days at 74 UK universities in February and March]' (3 February 2020).</ref>\n\nDuring February, UUK consulted its members on the possibility of making a new offer in the pensions dispute, responding to UCU's request that employers shoulder more of the burden of rising pensions contributions. 84% opposed the idea of making a new offer. Meanwhile, UCEA did not alter the offer it had made on 27 January.<ref>Anna McKie, \"[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/employers-refuse-back-down-eve-uk-university-strikes Employers refuse to back down on eve of UK university strikes]\", ''Times Higher Education'' (18 February 2020).</ref><ref>https://www.ussemployers.org.uk/briefing-resources/background-and-briefings/open-letter-uuk-and-ucea-staff-about-2020-industrial-action.</ref> During the same period, the ''Times Higher Education'' reported restiveness among some UCU members about the desirability of further strikes.<ref>Anna McKie, \"[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/union-tries-keep-members-board-more-strikes-near Union tries to keep members on board as more strikes near]\", ''Times Higher Education'' (10 February 2020).</ref>\n\n==== Weeks 1-2 (20\u201326 February) ====\nStrikes began on 20 February, with 74 universities affected, and news reporting on the day focusing on the determination of striking staff picketing in rainy weather.<ref name=\":24\" /><ref>Anna McKie, \"[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/uk-university-strikes-grim-determination-picket-lines UK university strikes: \u2018grim determination\u2019 on the picket lines]\", ''Times Higher Education'' (20 February 2020).</ref><ref>Sally Weale and Laith Al-Khalaf, \"[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/feb/20/thousands-of-university-workers-strike-across-uk Thousands of university workers strike across UK]\", ''The Guardian'' (20 February 2020).</ref><ref>\"Education Workers Strike Back\", ''The Socialist'' (20-26 February 2020), pp. 16, 7.</ref> Following a few days with little apparent progress,<ref>Anna McKie, \"[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/stand-both-sides-dig-uk-sector-strikes \u2018Stand-off\u2019 as both sides dig in for UK sector strikes\", ''Times Higher Education'' (24 February 2020).]</ref> UCEA resumed negotiations with UCU on Monday 24 February,<ref>Jo Grady, \"[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10661/Further-talks-and-more-on-the-Four-Fights-dispute Further talks and more on the Four Fights dispute]\" (24 February 2020).</ref> and UUK resumed negotiations on Tuesday 25th.<ref>Jo Grady, \"[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10664/Employers-agree-to-further-negotiations Employers agree to further negotiations]\" (26 February 2020).</ref> Negotiations continued throughout that week.<ref>Jo Grady, \"[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10667/Negotiations-update-more-USS-talks-on-Friday Negotiations update: more USS talks on Friday]\" (27 February 2020).</ref>\n\n==== Week 3 (2\u20135 March) ====\nNegotiations went on.<ref>Jo Grady, \"[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10678/Four-Fights-talks---and-a-leaked-employer-document-showing-the-true-cost-of-casualisation Four Fights talks - and a leaked employer document showing the true cost of casualisation]\" (4 March 2020).</ref><ref>https://www.ucu.org.uk/media/10761/Negotiators-statement-on-four-fights-talks-5-Mar-20/pdf/ucu_negotiatorsstatement_5mar20.pdf.</ref> and, following the leaking of minutes from a Russell Group meeting about casualisation, the Russell Group issued a statement pledging to address casualisation in that part of the university sector.<ref>\"[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10676/Fear-of-reputational-damage-prompts-secret-Russell-Group-meeting-to-call-for-leadership-on-casualisation Fear of 'reputational damage' prompts secret Russell Group meeting to call for leadership on casualisation]\" (3 March 2020).</ref><ref>\"[https://russellgroup.ac.uk/news/russell-group-publishes-joint-statement-on-working-practices/ Russell Group publishes joint statement on working practices]\" (3 March 2020).</ref><ref>Sadie Robinson , \"[https://socialistworker.co.uk/art/49707/University+bosses+admit+damage+caused+by+casual+contracts University bosses admit damage caused by casual contracts]\", ''Socialist Worker'', 2694 (4 March 2020).</ref><ref>Chris Havergal, \"[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/tackling-use-fixed-term-contracts-priority-russell-group Tackling use of fixed-term contracts \u2018priority\u2019 for Russell Group]\", ''Times Higher Education'' (4 March 2020).</ref>\n\nBy the end of the third week of strike action (Friday 6 March), UCU summarised the position of negotiations as showing good progress on achieving a UK-wide, sector level framework to address casualisation, gender pay-gaps, and workload, with continued debate concerning the pay deal. Regarding pensions, the Union represented UUK as putting more pressure on USS for reform, but little progress on convincing employers to shoulder a higher proportion of rising pension contributions.<ref>Jo Grady, \"[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10680/Detailed-negotiations-update Detailed negotiations update]\" (5 March 2020).</ref><ref>\"[https://www.ucu.org.uk/media/10761/Negotiators-statement-on-four-fights-talks-5-Mar-20/pdf/ucu_negotiatorsstatement_5mar20.pdf Negotiators' statement on Four Fights negotiations]\" (5 March 2020).</ref>\n\n==== Week 4 (9\u201313 March) ====\nLittle news emerged from negotiations, and on 11 March UCU negotiators on the Four Fights made it clear that good progress had been made on three, but that the sticking point for them was pay, and argued that UCU members would need to continue industrial action to achieve improvements in that area.<ref>'[https://www.ucu.org.uk/media/10783/Negotiators-update-on-Four-Fights-11-March-2020/pdf/Four_Fights_negotiators_update_11_March.pdf?utm_source=Lyris&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=&utm_term=&utm_content= Four Fights negotiators\u2019 update 11 March]' (11 March 2020).</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, debate on USS was complicated by USS beginning their 2020 valuation, with UCU criticising USS's valuation methods and calling on UUK for support. No significant change appeared to have come about in employers' willingness to shoulder more of the rising costs of the pension scheme.<ref>Anna McKie, \"[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/union-says-uss-valuation-proposals-ignore-members-views Union says USS valuation proposals \u2018ignore members\u2019 views\u2019]\", ''Times Higher Education'' (10 March 2020).</ref>\n\nAs the strikes came to an end, UK universities found themselves under a relatively sudden set of pressures as the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] led to falling projections for international student recruitment,<ref>Richard Adams and Rachel Hall, \"[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/mar/06/uk-universities-face-cash-black-hole-coronavirus-crisis UK universities face cash black hole amid coronavirus crisis]\", ''The Guardian'' (6 March 2020).</ref> and UK universities rapidly switching their teaching to online modes.<ref name=\":27\">John Morgan, \"[https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/coronavirus-lse-teach-online-rest-academic-year Coronavirus: LSE to teach online for rest of academic year]\", ''Times Higher Education'' (12 March 2020).</ref><ref>Richard Adams, \"[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/12/uk-universities-switching-to-online-lectures-and-exams UK universities switching to online lectures and exams]\", ''The Guardian'' (12 March 2020).</ref><ref>\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-51857142 Coronavirus: Face-to-face lectures cancelled at some universities]\", ''BBC News'' (12 March 2020).</ref> UCU cancelled rallies on the last day of strikes to reduce the risk of infection.<ref>Jo Grady, \"[https://www.ucu.org.uk/article/10689/Coronavirus-advice-in-relation-to-industrial-action?list=10241 Coronavirus advice in relation to industrial action]\" (12 March 2020).</ref> The prospect of convulsive changes to university staff workload and working conditions as universities responded to the pandemic increased the complexities and tensions surrounding the dispute.<ref name=\":27\" />\n\n==== Responses to the strike ====\nStudent support at the outset of the strike was estimated at 47% by an unscientific poll reported by the BBC.<ref>\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-51533712 Students hit by 14-day university staff strike]\", ''BBC News'' (20 February 2020).</ref> With continued NUS support for the strikes, twenty-six students' unions wrote to the Minister of State for Universities, the chairs of the UCEA and USS trustee boards and the Chief Executive of Universities UK, expressing support for UCU and urging a swift resolution to the strikes.<ref>https://www.ucu.org.uk/media/10756/Joint-student-unions-HE-dispute-letter-Mar-20/pdf/studentunions_hedisputeletter_mar20.pdf.</ref> As in previous strikes, there was a student occupation, in this case of the Old Schools in Cambridge.<ref>Claudia Rowan, \"[https://thetab.com/uk/cambridge/2020/03/03/old-schools-occupied-by-cambridge-marxist-society-and-cambridge-defend-education-133565 Old Schools occupied by Cambridge Marxist Society and Cambridge Defend Education]\", ''The Cambridge Tab'' (3 March 2020).</ref>\n\nUCU members continued to find innovative ways to picket, with developments including a group of picketing runners circumnavigating the University of Leeds campus.<ref>Peter Lazenby, \"[https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/striking-ucu-lecturers-stage-a-running-picket-line-at-leeds-university Striking UCU lecturers stage a \u2018running picket line\u2019 at Leeds University]\", ''The Morning Star'' (2 March 2020).</ref>\n\n== Table of UK higher education strikes 2018\u201320 ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n|\n|'''2018<ref name=\":1\" />'''\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''2019<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20200313001021/https://ucu.org.uk/article/10464/More-universities-to-be-balloted-for-strikes?list=9820 More universities to be balloted for strikes]\" (26 November 2019).</ref>'''\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''2020<ref name=\":26\" />'''\n|'''2018-20'''\n|-\n|\n|'''USS'''\n|'''USS'''\n|'''Four Fights'''\n|'''USS'''\n|'''Four Fights'''\n|'''Local disputes'''\n|-\n|Aberdeen, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|-\n|Aberystwyth University\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Aston University\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Bangor University\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Bath, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Bath Spa University\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Birkbeck College, University of London\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Birmingham, University of\n|?\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|2019: Caterers, cleaners, and security guards in Unison to secure a local pay increase of 4.85% for the lowest-paid, scaling to 3% for the highest paid.<ref>'[https://uobunison.org.uk/end-of-dispute Press Release \u2013 End of the 18-19 Dispute and Plans for the Future]' (25 November 2019).</ref>\n|-\n|Bishop Grosseteste University\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Bournemouth University\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Bradford, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|The University of Brighton\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Bristol, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Brunel University\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Cambridge, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Cardiff University\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|City, University of London\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Courtauld Institute of Art\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Cranfield University\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|De Montfort University\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Dundee, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Durham University\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|East Anglia, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|East London, University of\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Edge Hill University\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Edinburgh, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Essex, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Exeter, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Glasgow Caledonian University\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Glasgow School of Art\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Glasgow, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Goldsmiths, University of London\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Greenwich, University of\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Heriot-Watt University\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Huddersfield, University of\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Hull, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Imperial College London\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|-\n|Institute for Development Studies\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|-\n|Institute of Education\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Keele University\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|-\n|Kent, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|King's College London\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\n|-\n|Lancaster, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Leeds Trinity University\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Leeds, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Leicester, University of\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Liverpool Hope University\n|\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|\u00d7\n|\n|-\n|Liverpool Institute of Performin